# PATTERN RECOGNITION MASTER GUIDE
# The single most important page in this book.
# Left column: what the problem says. Right column: what algorithm to use.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# ── ARRAY / SEQUENCE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   maximum subarray sum                           -> Kadane O(n)           [Ch7]
#   maximum subarray sum, non-empty required       -> Kadane nonempty       [Ch7]
#   longest increasing subsequence                 -> LIS O(n log n)        [Ch7]
#   minimum deletions to make sorted               -> n - LIS               [Ch7]
#   count inversions in array                      -> Merge sort count      [Ch3]
#   kth smallest / largest element                 -> Quickselect or heap   [Ch4]
#   sliding window max or min                      -> Monotone deque O(n)   [Ch4]
#   subarray sum equals k                          -> Prefix sum + hash     [Ch9]
#   subarrays with at most k distinct values       -> Two pointers          [Ch8]
#   range sum queries, static                      -> Prefix sum O(1)       [Ch9]
#   range sum + point updates                      -> Fenwick tree O(log n) [Ch9]
#   range min/max queries, static                  -> Sparse table O(1)     [Ch9]
#   range min/max + updates                        -> Segment tree          [Ch9]
#
# ── BINARY SEARCH ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   minimize the maximum                           -> Binary search on answer [Ch3]
#   maximize the minimum                           -> Binary search on answer [Ch3]
#   minimum days/operations to achieve X           -> Binary search on answer [Ch3]
#   find boundary in sorted array                  -> bisect_left/right      [Ch3]
#
# ── GREEDY ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   maximize non-overlapping intervals             -> Sort by end time       [Ch6]
#   minimum intervals to cover range               -> Sort by start time     [Ch6]
#   minimize max lateness of tasks                 -> Sort by deadline       [Ch6]
#   fractional knapsack                            -> Sort by value/weight   [Ch6]
#   minimum merge cost / Huffman                   -> Min-heap greedy        [Ch6]
#   jump game, can reach end                       -> Greedy max-reach       [Ch6]
#
# ── DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   number of ways to reach a state                -> Count DP               [Ch7]
#   minimum cost to reach a state                  -> Min cost DP            [Ch7]
#   0/1 item choices with capacity                 -> 0/1 Knapsack           [Ch7]
#   unlimited item copies with capacity            -> Unbounded knapsack     [Ch7]
#   split string into valid segments               -> Word break DP          [Ch7]
#   edit distance between two strings              -> Levenshtein DP         [Ch7]
#   longest common subsequence                     -> LCS DP                 [Ch7]
#   palindrome substrings or partitioning          -> Palindrome DP          [Ch7]
#   bitmask states over small set n<=20            -> Bitmask DP             [Ch10]
#   count integers [0..N] with digit property      -> Digit DP               [Ch27]
#   DP transition cost is linear in j              -> Convex Hull Trick      [Ch27]
#   DP on intervals / matrix chain                 -> Interval DP            [Ch7]
#   DP on tree nodes                               -> Tree DP post-order     [Ch14]
#   DP on tree with root changes                   -> Rerooting DP           [Ch14]
#   sum over all subsets of a mask                 -> SOS DP                 [Ch27]
#   can split into two equal-sum subsets           -> Subset sum DP          [Ch7]
#
# ── GRAPH ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   shortest path, unweighted graph                -> BFS O(V+E)            [Ch12]
#   shortest path, non-negative weights            -> Dijkstra O(E log V)   [Ch13]
#   shortest path, negative edges present          -> Bellman-Ford O(VE)    [Ch13]
#   shortest path, edge weights are 0 or 1         -> 0-1 BFS               [Ch12]
#   all-pairs shortest path                        -> Floyd-Warshall O(V^3) [Ch13]
#   minimum spanning tree                          -> Kruskal (DSU)         [Ch15]
#   connected components                           -> BFS/DFS or DSU        [Ch11]
#   topological sort / task ordering               -> Kahn's BFS            [Ch16]
#   cycle detection in directed graph              -> DFS 3-color            [Ch16]
#   strongly connected components                  -> Kosaraju / Tarjan     [Ch17]
#   bridges and articulation points                -> Tarjan low-link DFS   [Ch17]
#   bipartite check                                -> BFS 2-coloring        [Ch12]
#   LCA queries on tree                            -> Binary lifting        [Ch14]
#   path queries on tree (sum/max)                 -> HLD + segment tree    [Ch18]
#   maximum flow                                   -> Dinic O(V^2 * E)      [Ch19]
#   bipartite matching                             -> Hopcroft-Karp / flow  [Ch19]
#   project selection (yes/no items, dependencies) -> Min cut               [Ch19]
#
# ── STRINGS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   find single pattern in text                    -> KMP O(n+m)            [Ch26]
#   find multiple patterns simultaneously           -> Aho-Corasick          [Ch26]
#   longest palindromic substring                  -> Manacher O(n)         [Ch26]
#   compare arbitrary substrings O(1)              -> String hashing        [Ch26]
#   is string a rotation of another                -> KMP on doubled string [Ch26]
#   minimum period of string                       -> KMP failure function  [Ch26]
#   all suffixes sorted                            -> Suffix array          [Ch28]
#   longest repeated substring                     -> SA + LCP (Kasai)     [Ch28]
#   count distinct substrings                      -> Suffix automaton      [Ch28]
#   count palindromic substrings                   -> Manacher              [Ch26]
#
# ── NUMBER THEORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   count primes up to N                           -> Sieve O(n log log n)  [Ch21]
#   factorize N                                    -> SPF sieve             [Ch21]
#   nCr mod prime p                                -> Lucas + precomputed   [Ch22]
#   a^b mod m                                      -> Fast pow (built-in)   [Ch21]
#   modular inverse                                -> pow(a, m-2, m)        [Ch21]
#   system of congruences                          -> CRT                   [Ch21]
#   sum floor(n/i) for i=1..n                      -> Harmonic number trick [Ch21]
#
# ── GEOMETRY ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   convex hull of point set                       -> Monotone chain        [Ch20]
#   area of polygon                                -> Shoelace formula      [Ch20]
#   lattice points inside polygon                  -> Pick's theorem        [Ch20]
#   closest pair of points                         -> D&C O(n log n)        [Ch20]
#   diameter of convex polygon                     -> Rotating calipers     [Ch20]
#
# ── GAME THEORY ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   take from piles, last move wins                -> Nim: XOR of piles     [Ch25]
#   take from piles, last move loses               -> Misere Nim            [Ch25]
#   arbitrary combinatorial game                   -> Sprague-Grundy values [Ch25]
#   sum of independent games                       -> XOR Grundy values     [Ch25]
#
# ── COMBINATORICS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   number of valid bracket sequences              -> Catalan C(2n,n)/(n+1) [Ch22]
#   permutations with no fixed point               -> Derangements          [Ch22]
#   distribute n identical into k distinct bins    -> Stars and bars        [Ch22]
#   Nth term of linear recurrence                  -> Matrix exponentiation [Ch23]
#   Fibonacci(N) for large N (N up to 10^18)       -> Fast matrix doubling  [Ch23]
#
# ── OFFLINE / ADVANCED ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   range queries with updates (offline, known Q)  -> Mo's algorithm        [Ch27]
#   binary search on a process / simulation        -> Parallel binary search [Ch27]
#   range add + range min (complex updates)        -> Segment tree beats    [Ch9]
#   assign value to range, sparse overlap          -> Chtholly tree (ODT)  [Ch27]
#
