# ▶ PRE-CHAPTER 1 — PYTHON SETUP & MATH ESSENTIALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# §0. THE MATH YOU NEED FOR COMPETITIVE PROGRAMMING

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Before you start solving CP problems, it helps to know a bit of the math
# that sits underneath all the algorithms. Don't worry — this is not a textbook.
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Think of it as a quick "math cheat sheet" explained in plain English.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 🔥 0.1  DIVISIBILITY AND MODULAR ARITHMETIC (the "clock math" of CP)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# DIVISIBILITY — what it means:
#   "a divides b" (written a | b) just means b is a multiple of a.
#   Examples: 3 divides 12 ✓  |  7 divides 49 ✓  |  5 does NOT divide 13 ✗
#
# EVERY NUMBER IS MADE OF PRIMES (Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic):
# • Think of primes (2, 3, 5, 7, 11, ...) as the "atoms" of all numbers.
# • Every whole number ≥ 2 can be broken down into prime factors in exactly one way.
# • Example: 360 = 2 × 2 × 2 × 3 × 3 × 5  (written as 2³ · 3² · 5).
#   This is super useful for figuring out GCD, LCM, and counting divisors.
#
# GCD and LCM explained simply:
# • GCD(a, b) — the biggest number that divides BOTH a and b.
# • GCD(12, 8) = 4  (both divisible by 4, nothing bigger works)
# • LCM(a, b) — the smallest number divisible by BOTH a and b.
# • LCM(4, 6) = 12  (12 is the first number in both the 4-table and 6-table).
#   Key identity: GCD(a,b) × LCM(a,b) = a × b   ← memorize this for CP!
#
# MODULAR ARITHMETIC — think of a clock:
# • "a mod m" is just the remainder when you divide a by m.
# • On a 12-hour clock, 14:00 is the same as 2:00 — that's mod 12.
# • In CP, mod is used to keep big numbers from getting too large.
# • The most common modulus is 10^9 + 7 (a prime number).
#
# How mod works with +, -, ×:
#   (a + b) % m  =  ((a % m) + (b % m)) % m   ← always safe to do this
#   (a - b) % m  =  ((a % m) - (b % m) + m) % m  ← the +m avoids negatives
#   (a × b) % m  =  ((a % m) × (b % m)) % m
# ⚠️ WARNING:
#   • Division with mod is NOT the same as regular division!
#     You need a "modular inverse" for that (covered in Chapter 21).
#
# FERMAT'S LITTLE THEOREM (for modular division):
# • If p is prime: a^(p-1) mod p = 1  when a is not a multiple of p.
# • This lets us compute: a^(-1) mod p  =  a^(p-2) mod p  (in O(log p) time).
# • Translation: to "divide by a" in modular arithmetic, multiply by a^(p-2) % p.
#
# • WHY IS 10^9 + 7 USED EVERYWHERE IN CP? 1.
# • It's prime → modular division always works cleanly.
# • [C++ concern] Two numbers each less than 10⁹+7, when multiplied, give a
#   product < (10⁹+7)² ≈ 10¹⁸ < 2⁶³−1, so it fits in a signed 64-bit int.
#   In Python this point is moot — Python integers have arbitrary precision
#   and never overflow. The note matters for C++/Java contestants.
# • It's small enough to be convenient, big enough to rarely cause collisions.
#
# ⚡ FORMULA:
#   • code: b % a == 0.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   a%m is the clock-remainder; (a*b)%m = ((a%m)*(b%m))%m — wrap BEFORE overflow
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "divisible by"
#   - "remainder when divided"
#   - "modulo"
#   - "last K digits"
#   - "periodic pattern"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Doing (a*b)%m without wrapping a,b first → overflow in C++ (fine in Python but slow)
#   ✗ Subtracting mod: (a-b)%m can be negative → use (a-b+m)%m
#   ✗ Division mod p: a/b%p ≠ (a%p)/(b%p) → use modular inverse b^(p-2)%p
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What does brute force look like?
#   2. What is the complexity bottleneck?
#   3. What structure or property enables optimization?
#   → Code the optimized approach
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ⚡ 0.2  FLOOR AND CEILING — ROUNDING FOR INTEGER MATH
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# floor(x) — round DOWN to the nearest whole number.   floor(3.7) = 3
# ceil(x)  — round UP to the nearest whole number.     ceil(3.2)  = 4
#
# • In Python code (no floats needed, 100% exact): floor(a / b)  →  a // b
#       (Python's // always rounds down) ceil(a / b)   →  (a + b - 1) // b  (the
#       classic "ceiling trick")
#
# Why does the ceiling trick work?
# • If a fits exactly into b-sized groups: no rounding needed → same as floor.
# • If there's any leftover: we need one extra group.
# • Adding (b-1) before dividing forces that extra group to appear.
#
#   Example: ceil(10 / 3) = (10 + 2) // 3 = 12 // 3 = 4  ✓
#   (10 items in groups of 3: you need 4 groups — 3+3+3+1)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   ceil(a,b) = (a+b-1)//b — the single most-reused integer trick in CP
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS (when to apply floor/ceiling):
#   - "minimum number of trips / pages / boxes / groups needed"
#   - "distribute n items into buckets of size k"
#   - "how many full passes are required"
#   - "round up to the nearest multiple of k"
#   - "partition n items into exactly k equal parts" (ceiling for sizes)
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Using int(a/b) instead of a//b — float precision errors for large numbers
#   ✗ Forgetting Python // floors toward −∞, not toward 0:
#       -7 // 2 == -4 in Python, but -3 in C++. Use -((-a)//b) for "toward-zero ceil"
#   ✗ Applying the ceiling trick when a or b can be 0 (division by zero)
#   ✗ Using (a+b-1)//b when a could be negative — only correct for a,b > 0
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   • "I need to fit a items into groups of b — how many groups?" → ceil(a,b)
#   • "How many complete groups of b fit into a?" → floor(a,b) = a//b
#   → Always ask: am I rounding up or rounding down? Then pick the right formula.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ⚡ 0.3  USEFUL SUM FORMULAS (memorize these — they appear constantly)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. Sum of 1 to n:  1 + 2 + 3 + ... + n  =  n*(n+1)/2
# • How to remember: pair up the first and last (1+n), (2+n-1), ... You get n/2 pairs, each summing to (n+1).
# • So total = n*(n+1)/2.
# • Famous example: 1+2+...+100 = 100*101/2 = 5050  (Gauss figured this out at age 9!).
#
# 2. Sum of squares:  1² + 2² + ... + n²  =  n*(n+1)*(2n+1)/6
#    Just memorize the formula — it comes up in geometry and combinatorics problems.
#
# • Sum of cubes:  1³ + 2³ + ... + n³  =  (n*(n+1)/2)² Amazingly, this equals the
#       SQUARE of the sum-of-1-to-n formula! Check: 1³+2³+3³ = 1+8+27 = 36 =
#       (1+2+3)² = 6² ✓
#
# • Geometric series (powers of r):  1 + r + r² + ... + r^(n-1)  =  (r^n - 1)/(r-1)
#   Special case r=2:  1 + 2 + 4 + ... + 2^(n-1)  =  2^n - 1
#   This is why n bits can represent numbers 0 to 2^n - 1 (all bits set = 2^n - 1).
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   1+2+…+n = n(n+1)/2 — never write O(n) loop when O(1) formula exists
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "sum of first N"
#   - "sum from 1 to"
#   - "total after N steps"
#   - "arithmetic sequence"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Computing sum in a loop when n=10^9 → TLE; use n*(n+1)//2
#   ✗ Forgetting integer division: n*(n+1)/2 returns float in Python 3 → use //
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Recognize the pattern (consecutive integers, squares, cubes, geometric?)
#   2. Look up or derive the closed-form formula
#   3. Apply modular arithmetic when n is large (use //2 → inv(2,MOD) *2)
#   → A O(1) formula always beats an O(n) loop — memorise the five core formulas
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 💡 0.4  LOGARITHMS — WHY O(log n) ALGORITHMS ARE SO FAST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# What is log?  log_b(x) = "how many times do I multiply b by itself to get x?"
#   log_2(8) = 3   because 2×2×2 = 8
#   log_2(1024) = 10  because 2^10 = 1024
#
# In CP, base-2 log is everywhere:
#   Binary search on n items → at most log_2(n) steps
#   A balanced tree on n nodes → height is log_2(n)
#   n stored in binary → log_2(n) bits
#
# Quick values to memorize:
#   2^10 ≈ 10³   (1024 ≈ 1000)
#   2^20 ≈ 10^6  →  log_2(10^6) ≈ 20
#   2^30 ≈ 10^9  →  log_2(10^9) ≈ 30
#   2^60 ≈ 10^18 →  log_2(10^18) ≈ 60
#
# • Why binary search is O(log n) — picture this: Start with 16 elements.
# • Each step cuts the search space in half: 16 → 8 → 4 → 2 → 1
#       (4 steps = log₂(16)).
# • For n=10^9: only about 30 steps needed. That's the power of log.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   log₂(10⁹)≈30 — binary search on 10⁹ elements takes only 30 steps
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how many times halved"
#   - "bits needed"
#   - "tree height"
#   - "binary"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Confusing log base 2 vs log base 10: log₂(n) = log₁₀(n)/log₁₀(2) ≈ 3.32*log₁₀(n)
#   ✗ Using math.log(n,2) on large integers → floating-point precision loss → use n.bit_length()-1
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What does brute force look like?
#   2. What is the complexity bottleneck?
#   3. What structure or property enables optimization?
#   → Code the optimized approach
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 🎯 0.5  SETS AND FUNCTIONS — VOCABULARY YOU'LL SEE IN CP
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A SET is just a collection of distinct items (no duplicates, no order).
#   Size of set S is written |S|.
#   The "power set" of S = all possible subsets of S. Size = 2^|S|.
#   Example: S = {1,2,3} → power set has 2³ = 8 subsets.
#
# SET OPERATIONS (think of them as Venn diagrams):
#   A ∪ B  — everything in A OR B (union)
#   A ∩ B  — only things in BOTH A and B (intersection)
#   A \ B  — things in A but NOT in B (difference)
#
# INCLUSION-EXCLUSION (for counting problems):
#   |A ∪ B| = |A| + |B| − |A ∩ B|
#   You add both sets, then subtract the overlap (otherwise you counted it twice).
#   This idea extends to 3 or more sets — alternating add and subtract.
#
# FUNCTIONS in CP — three types worth knowing:
# • One-to-one: different inputs always produce different outputs.
# • Onto: every possible output is produced by at least one input.
# • Bijection (both): a perfect pairing between two sets, like a dictionary.
#
# • Coordinate compression = mapping big values to {0,1,...,n-1}  (a perfect
#       1-to-1 mapping) Hashing = mapping keys to array slots  (not necessarily
#       one-to-one) DP state mapping = turning problem states into array indices
#       (a unique mapping)
#
# 🚀 USE CASES (sets and inclusion-exclusion appear in CP as):
#   • Counting elements satisfying at least one of several conditions (|A∪B∪C|)
#   • Coordinate compression — mapping large value ranges to {0..n-1}
#   • Bitmask DP — each bit represents membership of an element in a subset
#   • Graph problems — adjacency represented as sets of neighbours
#   → See Chapter 22 (Combinatorics) for a deep dive on inclusion-exclusion
#     with 3+ sets and the general alternating-sign formula.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Power set of n elements = 2ⁿ subsets — n>20 makes brute-force impossible
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS (when sets / inclusion-exclusion apply):
#   - "count elements satisfying at least one condition"
#   - "how many numbers in [1..n] are divisible by a OR b"
#   - "number of subsets with property X"
#   - "Venn diagram overlap" phrasing
#   - "at least one / none of the following"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Forgetting to subtract the intersection: |A∪B| = |A|+|B| − |A∩B|, not |A|+|B|
#   ✗ Wrong sign in 3-set formula: |A∪B∪C| = |A|+|B|+|C| − |A∩B| − |A∩C| − |B∩C| + |A∩B∩C|
#   ✗ Confusing power-set size 2ⁿ with permutation count n! — very different magnitudes
#   ✗ Using Python set() when order matters — sets are unordered by definition
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
