#
#   ► "t test cases, n up to 10^6"     → precompute factorials / primes ONCE
#
#   ► "print many lines"               → batch with sys.stdout.write / print(*list)
#
#   ► "large integers, no overflow"    → Python handles it; still apply % MOD for answers
#
#   ► "interactive problem"            → flush after every print: print(x, flush=True)
#
#   ► "sum of n across test cases ≤ N" → amortised O(N) total; O(n) per case is fine

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  input() inside a tight loop with 10^5 iterations
#       → Each call flushes stdout, strips the line, handles encodings.
#          For 10^5 calls the overhead alone can TLE in Python.
#
#       → Direct file-descriptor read, ~3-5× faster per call.
#
#   ✗  print(answer) inside each test case in a loop
#       → 10^5 separate write() syscalls.
#
#   ✓  out = []; out.append(str(answer)); print('\n'.join(out))
#       → One syscall for all output.
#
#   ✗  for i in range(1, n+1): fact[i] = fact[i-1] * i % MOD   INSIDE the test loop
#       → Recomputes O(n) every time when n can repeat.
#
#   ✓  Precompute fact[] once before the test loop → O(1) per query.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Batch output in a list and print once — sys.stdout.write avoids per-line overhead
#
