#
# Think of it like a pipeline. For n = 10^5:
#   O(n)      →  10^5  ops   ✓  blazing fast
#   O(n log n)→  1.7×10^6  ✓  fast
#   O(n²)     →  10^10     ✗  instant TLE in Python
#
# Always estimate BEFORE coding. If your estimate doesn't fit, rethink.
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What is the constraint on n?
#   2. What complexity does the time limit allow?
#   3. Is Python fast enough or do I need PyPy/sys.stdin tricks?
#   → n≤10^3: O(n²) ok; n≤10^5: O(n log n); n≤10^6: O(n); n≤10^9: O(log n) or O(√n)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ THE MASTER COMPLEXITY TABLE (memorize every row)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Complexity   │ Max n for Python    │ What it usually means               │
# ├──────────────┼─────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────┤
# │ O(1)         │ any                 │ Direct formula, no loop             │
# │ O(log n)     │ 10^18               │ Binary search, modular exp, tree hei│
# │ O(√n)        │ 10^12               │ Factorization, prime test, floor of │
# │ O(n)         │ 5×10^6              │ Single pass, linear scan            │
# │ O(n log n)   │ 3×10^5              │ Sort, BIT update/query, segment tree│
# │ O(n√n)       │ 5×10^4              │ Mo's algorithm                      │
# │ O(n²)        │ 3000–5000           │ Two nested loops                    │
# │ O(n²log n)   │ 1000                │ Rare; sorted pairs                  │
# │ O(n³)        │ 300–500             │ Three nested loops, Floyd-Warshall  │
# │ O(2^n)       │ 20–25               │ Subset enumeration, bitmask DP      │
# │ O(n × 2^n)   │ 15–20               │ Bitmask DP with transitions         │
# │ O(n!)        │ 10–12               │ Permutation enumeration             │
