# ⚡ COMMON COMPLEXITY MISTAKES
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Mistake 1: "My algorithm is O(n log n) but I have t test cases." → Total = O(t
#       × n log n)
# • If t=10^4 and n=10^4: TLE! Fix: Look for global preprocessing or O(n log n)
#       total across all test cases
#
# • Mistake 2: "Python set/dict operations are O(1) so it's fine." → O(1) average,
#       but LARGE constants
# • Building a set of 10^6 elements is slower than a C++ array.
# • Careful with constant factors.
#
# • Mistake 3: "Recursion depth." Python default recursion limit is
# • → Always add sys.setrecursionlimit(300000) for DFS on large trees.
# • → Better: convert DFS to iterative (stack-based) to avoid overhead entirely.
#
# Mistake 4: "List concatenation in a loop." a += [x] inside a loop is O(n²)!
#   → Use a.append(x) — O(1) amortized. Or build all at once with list comp.
#
