# 💡 PRE-CHAPTER 4 — ABSTRACT DATA TYPES & DATA STRUCTURE THEORY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# §1. ABSTRACT DATA TYPES vs CONCRETE DATA STRUCTURES

# An ABSTRACT DATA TYPE (ADT) specifies WHAT operations are available and
# their semantics, without specifying HOW they are implemented.
#
# A DATA STRUCTURE is a concrete implementation of an ADT.
#
# Examples:
# • ADT Stack → implementations: array-based, linked list-based.
# • ADT Priority Queue → implementations: binary heap, Fibonacci heap, sorted list.
# • ADT Map → implementations: hash table, balanced BST (e.g., AVL, Red-Black).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY THIS MATTERS IN CP:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • You choose the ADT based on what OPERATIONS you need.
# • You choose the IMPLEMENTATION based on time/space complexity requirements.
# • Python gives you specific concrete structures; knowing the ADT helps you
#   use them correctly and understand their guarantees.

# §2. HEAP THEORY — THE COMPLETE BINARY TREE PROPERTY

# • A BINARY HEAP is a complete binary tree satisfying the heap property: MIN-
#       HEAP: parent ≤ both children at every node
# • MAX-HEAP: parent ≥ both children at every node.
#
# COMPLETE BINARY TREE: all levels are fully filled except possibly the last,
# which is filled from left to right.
#
# ARRAY REPRESENTATION (1-indexed):
#   Node at index i:
#     Left child  = 2i
#     Right child = 2i + 1
#     Parent      = i // 2
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — Min-heap as complete binary tree and array:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#           1           index 1
#         /   \
#        3     2        indices 2, 3
#       / \   / \
#      7   5 4   6      indices 4, 5, 6, 7
#
# • Array: [_, 1, 3, 2, 7, 5, 4, 6]  (index 0 unused in 1-indexed) Note: parent(6)=3 (index 3, value 2).
# • Verify: value at parent index 3 is 2, child at index 6 has value 4. 2 ≤ 4 ✓
# • parent(7) = 7//2 = 3.  Value at index 3 is 2, child at index 7 has value 6. 2 ≤ 6 ✓
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ OPERATION S:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • INSERT (push): Add at end, then SIFT UP.
# • Sift up: swap with parent while parent > new element.
# • O(log n): each swap moves up one level, at most log n levels.
#
# EXTRACT-MIN (pop): Remove root, put last element at root, SIFT DOWN.
#   Sift down: swap with smaller child while either child < current.
#   O(log n): same reasoning.
#
# BUILD-HEAP from n elements: Sift down from last internal node to root.
#   Surprisingly O(n), not O(n log n)!
#   Proof: nodes at depth d need to sift down at most d levels.
#   Total work = Σ_{d=0}^{log n} (n/2^d) · d = O(n) by geometric series analysis.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY HEAPS FOR PRIORITY QUEUES?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Balanced BST also gives O(log n) per op, but with much higher constant.
#   Heap is cache-friendly (array), simpler to implement, faster in practice.

# §3. HASH TABLE THEORY — O(1) AVERAGE CASE

# A hash table maps keys to values using a HASH FUNCTION h: Key → [0, m-1].
# Ideally: h(k) is uniform and independent (keys map uniformly to buckets).
#
# COLLISION: when h(k₁) = h(k₂) for k₁ ≠ k₂.
# COLLISION RESOLUTION strategies:
#   1. Chaining: Each bucket holds a linked list of (key, value) pairs.
#   2. Open addressing: On collision, probe for another empty bucket.
#
# • LOAD FACTOR α = n/m (elements / buckets).
# • For chaining: expected search time = O(1 + α).
# • Keep α ≤ 1 for O(1).
# • Python's dict rehashes when α > 2/3 (approximately), maintaining O(1) average.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY O(1) AVERAGE BUT O(n) WORST CASE?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • Worst case: all n keys hash to same bucket → linear scan.
# • With a good hash function + random data: expected O(1).
# • In CP: deliberate hash collisions can HACK your solution!
#   Use custom hashes or SortedList (from sortedcontainers) when adversarial inputs are possible.
#
# PYTHON DICT SPECIFICS:
# • Python's dict uses open addressing with quadratic probing.
# • Integer hashing: small integers hash to themselves (fast).
# • String hashing: polynomial rolling hash (randomized per-process in Python 3.3+.
#                   to prevent hash flooding attacks).

# §4. THE MONOTONIC STACK — THEORY OF "USEFUL PREVIOUS ELEMENTS"

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHAT THIS MEANS: A monotonic stack maintains the invariant that elements are always
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# in monotonically increasing or decreasing order (by their values).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ INVARIANT: When processing element a[i], all elements in the stack that are
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ≥ a[i] (for a decreasing stack) are popped first. They are "dominated" by a[i]
# and can never be the answer for any future query.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ KEY INSIGHT: "If a[j] < a[i] and j > i, then a[j] will be the answer for all
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# future queries before i would be. So a[i] is obsolete — pop it."
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — Next Greater Element with decreasing stack:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Array:  [4, 5, 2, 10, 8]
#
#   i=0: stack=[] → push 0. stack=[0]
#        Stack values: [4]  (always decreasing)
#
#   i=1: a[1]=5 > a[0]=4 → pop 0 (answer for 0 is a[1]=5). push 1. stack=[1]
#        Stack values: [5]
#
#   i=2: a[2]=2 < a[1]=5 → no pop. push 2. stack=[1,2]
#        Stack values: [5, 2]  (decreasing) ✓
#
#   i=3: a[3]=10 > a[2]=2 → pop 2 (answer for 2 is 10).
#              10 > a[1]=5 → pop 1 (answer for 1 is 10). push 3. stack=[3]
#        Stack values: [10]
#
#   i=4: a[4]=8 < a[3]=10 → no pop. push 4. stack=[3,4]
#        Stack values: [10, 8]  (decreasing) ✓
#
#   Remaining in stack: no next greater → answer = -1.
#   Result: [5, 10, 10, -1, -1] ✓
#
# AMORTIZED COMPLEXITY: Each element is pushed once and popped at most once.
# Total operations = at most 2n → O(n). ✓

# §5. THE MONOTONE DEQUE — SLIDING WINDOW THEORY

# PROBLEM: Find maximum in every window of size k as window slides.
# NAIVE: For each window, scan k elements. O(nk). TLE for n=10⁶, k=10³.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ INSIGHT: When element a[j] enters the window (j is right end), any element
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# a[i] with i < j and a[i] ≤ a[j] will NEVER be the window maximum while
# a[j] is in the window (a[j] is larger AND expires later).
# So a[i] can be safely discarded.
#
# • STRUCTURE: Maintain a deque of indices with VALUES in DECREASING order.
# • Front: always the current window maximum.
# • Back: most recently added element (smallest in window).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ INVARIANT maintained:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   1. All indices in deque are within the current window.
#   2. Values at deque indices are strictly decreasing front to back.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — Sliding window max with k=3 on [1, 3, -1, -3, 5, 3, 6, 7]:  [TWO-PTR]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   i=0: deque=[0]      values=[1]        window not full yet
#   i=1: 3>1→pop 0. deque=[1]  values=[3]
#   i=2: -1<3→push. deque=[1,2] values=[3,-1]. Window [0..2]. max=a[1]=3.
#   i=3: -3<-1→push. deque=[1,2,3] values=[3,-1,-3]. Pop front: 1 outside? 1 ≥ i-k+1=1. OK.
#          Window [1..3]. max=a[1]=3.
#   i=4: 5>-3→pop3. 5>-1→pop2. 5>3→pop1. deque=[4] values=[5].
#          Window [2..4]. max=a[4]=5.
#   i=5: 3<5→push. deque=[4,5] values=[5,3]. Pop front: 4 ≥ 3? Yes.
#          Window [3..5]. max=a[4]=5.
#   i=6: 6>3→pop5. 6>5→pop4. deque=[6] values=[6].
#          Window [4..6]. max=a[6]=6.
#   i=7: 7>6→pop6. deque=[7] values=[7].
#          Window [5..7]. max=a[7]=7.
#
#   Result: [3, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7] ✓
#
#   Total operations: each element pushed once + popped at most once = O(n). ✓
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Sliding window: expand right always, shrink left when constraint violated — O(n) total
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "subarray of length K"
#   - "maximum subarray with"
#   - "minimum window containing"
#   - "longest subarray where"
#   - "at most K distinct"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Shrinking left too aggressively (multiple shrinks per right step) → correct but misses subarrays
#   ✗ Not using deque for sliding window maximum → O(nk) instead of O(n)
#   ✗ Constraint: window must have AT MOST / EXACTLY k → these need different handling
#
