# 🧠 MENTAL MODELS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Stack  → "Last In, First Out — undo, match, previous-greater-element"
# • Queue  → "First In, First Out — BFS, sliding window events"
# • Heap   → "Always have the min/max ready in O(log n)"
# • Deque  → "Sliding window max/min — remove stale elements from both ends"
# • DSU    → "Who is in the same group? Merge groups in O(α(n)) ≈ O(1)"
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   BFS = explore level-by-level; dist[u] is the first time u is reached
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What operations are needed? (insert, delete, min/max, range query)
#   2. Which data structure supports all of them efficiently?
#   3. Verify the total complexity fits the time limit
#   → heap=min/max in O(log n); deque=sliding window; BIT=prefix sum in O(log n)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "valid parentheses / matching brackets"      → Stack
#
#   ► "previous greater / next smaller element"    → Monotonic Stack
#
#   ► "sliding window maximum / minimum"           → Monotonic Deque
#
#   ► "k-th largest, or top-k elements"            → Heap (heapq)
#
#   ► "merge K sorted arrays"                      → Heap
#
#   ► "are two nodes in the same component?"       → DSU
#
#   ► "simulate a process in arrival order"        → Queue / deque
#
#   ► "undo last K operations"                     → Stack

