#
# PROBLEM 5-1 [Easy]: Sum of All Subsets
# • Problem: Given array, find sum over all subsets of (sum of subset).
# • Insight: each element appears in 2^(n-1) subsets.
# • Answer = sum(a) * 2^(n-1).
# • O(n) solution! (Complete search would be O(n × 2^n).).
#
# • PROBLEM 5-2 [Easy]: Generate All Combinations nCk Problem: Generate all size-k
#       subsets of [1..n]. Solution: itertools.combinations(range(1,n+1), k)
#
# • PROBLEM 5-3 [Medium]: Sudoku Solver (Backtracking with constraint propagation)
#       Standard backtracking: for each empty cell, try 1..9, check validity,
#       recurse
# • With pruning: track which values are possible in each row/col/box.
#
# • PROBLEM 5-4 [Medium]: Partition into K Equal Subsets Classic backtracking: try
#       assigning each element to a bucket
# • Prune: if bucket sum > target, stop.
# • If bucket equals previous, skip (symmetry).
#
# • PROBLEM 5-5 [Hard]: Meet in the Middle — 4SUM Problem: Find if a+b+c+d=0 where
#       a,b from array A and c,d from array B
# • Generate all pairwise sums of A (O(n^2)) and B (O(n^2)), then sort and merge.
#
# 💡 PRO TIP:
#   • In backtracking, sort choices so promising ones come first.
# For example, in N-Queens, trying columns near the center first empirically
# finds solutions faster and prunes harder for infeasible branches.
#
# ⚠ COMMON MISTAKE:
#   • Not undoing the state properly during backtracking.
# Always verify: after backtrack() returns, the state is EXACTLY as it was before.
