#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Is n small enough for brute force? (n≤20 → 2^n subsets, n≤8 → n! permutations)
#   2. Can I prune early when the partial solution is already invalid?
#   3. What is the search space — subsets, permutations, combinations, or a grid?
#   → Enumerate all candidates; prune as early and aggressively as possible
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► n ≤ 8–12     → permutation search (n! is feasible up to ~12)
#
#   ► n ≤ 20       → subset enumeration 2^n is feasible
#
#   ► n ≤ 40       → meet in the middle (split into two halves of 2^20)
#
#   ► "find any valid assignment / coloring"  → backtracking with pruning
#
#   ► "generate all combinations of size k"  → itertools.combinations
#
#   ► Problem says "guaranteed to have a solution" → easier to search
#
#   ► Problem says "count all configurations" with n ≤ 20 → pure enumeration

