# 7C. 0/1 KNAPSACK — The Classic DP  [DP]

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# • Problem: n items, each with weight w[i] and value v[i]. Knapsack capacity W.
# • Maximize total value without exceeding capacity.
# • Each item: either take (1) or don't (0).
#
# STATE: dp[i][j] = max value using first i items with capacity j.
# TRANSITION:
#   Don't take item i: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j]
#   Take item i (if j >= w[i]): dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-w[i]] + v[i]
#   dp[i][j] = max(both)
#
# • SPACE OPTIMIZATION: We only need the previous row.
# • dp[j] = max value with capacity j (rolling array, 1D).
# • Process items in outer loop, capacities in DECREASING order (to avoid using item twice).
#
# DRY RUN on items=[(2,6),(2,10),(3,12)], W=5:
# dp = [0,0,0,0,0,0]
# Item 1 (w=2,v=6): j=5→max(dp[5],dp[3]+6)=6; j=4→max(0,dp[2]+6)=6; j=3→6; j=2→6
#   dp=[0,0,6,6,6,6]
# Item 2 (w=2,v=10): j=5→max(6,dp[3]+10)=16; j=4→max(6,dp[2]+10)=16; j=3→max(6,dp[1]+10)=10; j=2→10
#   dp=[0,0,10,10,16,16]
# Item 3 (w=3,v=12): j=5→max(16,dp[2]+12)=22; j=4→max(16,dp[1]+12)=16; j=3→max(10,dp[0]+12)=12
#   dp=[0,0,10,12,16,22]
# Answer: dp[5] = 22 (take items 2+3: value 10+12=22) ✓
#

# ── knapsack_01 — inline ──
# result→dp[W]
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   0/1 Knapsack: iterate capacity BACKWARDS so each item is used at most once — O(nW).
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "choose subset of items (each once), maximise value ≤ W"
#   - "can we achieve exactly sum S?" (subset sum variant)
#   - "partition into two equal halves"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Forward loop → unbounded knapsack (item used many times)
#   ✗ Not checking weights[i] <= j before accessing dp[j-weights[i]]
#   ✗ 2D dp[i][j] wastes memory when 1D rolling array suffices
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. dp[j] = best value with capacity j.
#   2. Backward ensures item i counted at most once per capacity.
#   3. dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j-w]+v).
#
# CF TAGS: dp, knapsack  |  Rating: 1200–1800

#
# UNBOUNDED KNAPSACK (each item can be used multiple times):
# Process capacities in INCREASING order:
#

# ── knapsack_unbounded — inline ──
# result→dp[W]
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Unbounded knapsack: iterate FORWARD — same item can be taken infinitely — O(nW).
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "unlimited copies of each item"
#   - "coin change: minimum coins to make amount"
#   - "ways to form sum using unlimited copies"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Backward loop → 0/1 knapsack (each item used once)
#   ✗ Initialising dp[0]=INF instead of 0 for min-cost variant
#   ✗ Not handling "no solution" (dp[target] remains INF)
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Forward loop: dp[j] = max(dp[j], dp[j-w]+v).
#   2. Forward allows item reuse at same capacity.
