# §1. THE MATHEMATICAL CONDITION FOR TWO POINTERS

# Two-pointer and sliding window work ONLY when the underlying problem has
# a MONOTONICITY property.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DEFINITION (Window Monotonicity):
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   A property P(l, r) is monotone if:
#     P(l, r) is true  →  P(l, r-1) is true  (shrinking from right preserves P)
#     P(l, r) is false →  P(l-1, r) is false  (expanding from left preserves ¬P)
#
# In other words: "If a window satisfies P, so does any sub-window.
#                  If a window doesn't satisfy P, neither does any super-window."
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ EXAMPLE S OF MONOTONE PROPERTIES:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   ✓ "Sum of window ≥ k" for positive arrays: sum only grows with larger window.
#   ✓ "At most k distinct elements": fewer distinct in sub-window.
#   ✓ "All elements ≤ threshold": sub-windows also satisfy this.
#   ✗ "Sum equals k" for arbitrary integers: not monotone (adding negatives can decrease sum).
#   ✗ "Exactly k odd elements": adding elements can add or remove odds.
#
# ALGORITHM TEMPLATE:
#   lo = 0
#   for hi in range(n):      ← right pointer always advances
#       extend window to include a[hi]
#       while condition violated:
#           shrink window from left (lo++)
#       record answer for current [lo, hi]
#
# COMPLEXITY: lo and hi each advance at most n times → O(n) total. ✓

# §2. PREFIX SUMS — FORMAL THEORY

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHAT THIS MEANS: The prefix sum array P of array A[0..n-1] is:  [RANGE]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   P[0] = 0
#   P[i] = A[0] + A[1] + … + A[i-1]   for i = 1..n
#
# Then: A[l] + A[l+1] + … + A[r] = P[r+1] − P[l]
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY this works: P[r+1] − P[l] = (A[0]+…+A[r]) − (A[0]+…+A[l-1]) = A[l]+…+A[r]. □
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                 🚀 APPLICATIONS                           │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# 1. Range sum queries: O(1) per query after O(n) build.
# 2. Counting subarrays with property: use prefix sum + hash map.
#    "How many subarrays have sum = k?"
#    Equivalent: how many pairs (l, r) with P[r+1] − P[l] = k?
#    Rearrange: P[l] = P[r+1] − k.
#    For each r, count previous l's where P[l] = P[r+1] − k.
#    Use a hash map: seen[P[l]] = number of times P[l] was seen.
#    O(n) total.
#
# 3. 2D prefix sums: O(1) rectangle sum queries.
#    P[i][j] = sum of A[0..i-1][0..j-1] (top-left rectangle).
#    P[i][j] = P[i-1][j] + P[i][j-1] − P[i-1][j-1] + A[i-1][j-1]
#    Rectangle sum (r1,c1)→(r2,c2):
#    = P[r2+1][c2+1] − P[r1][c2+1] − P[r2+1][c1] + P[r1][c1]
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — 2D prefix sum inclusion-exclusion:  [RANGE]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   r1,c1 ──────── r1,c2
#     |    query      |
#   r2,c1 ──────── r2,c2
#
#   sum(r1,c1,r2,c2) = P[r2+1][c2+1]
#                    - P[r1][c2+1]    ← subtract top strip
#                    - P[r2+1][c1]    ← subtract left strip
#                    + P[r1][c1]      ← add back doubly-subtracted corner

# §3. WHEN TO USE WHAT — DECISION GUIDE

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Problem type                         │ Technique                         │
# ├──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
# │ Range sum, no updates                │ Prefix sum, O(1)                  │
# │ Range sum + point updates            │ BIT/Fenwick, O(log n)             │
# │ Range min/max, no updates            │ Sparse table, O(1) query O(n log n│
# │ Any range query + updates            │ Segment tree, O(log n)            │
# │ Min subarray of sum ≥ k (pos. arr)  │ Sliding window, O(n)               │
# │ Subarray with sum = k                │ Prefix sum + hash map, O(n)       │
# │ Max sum subarray                     │ Kadane's, O(n)                    │
# │ Two Sum in sorted array              │ Two pointers, O(n)                │
# │ Max in every window of size k        │ Monotone deque, O(n)              │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# CHOOSING BETWEEN TWO POINTERS AND PREFIX SUM + HASH:
#   • Array has all positive elements + sum condition → two pointers.
#   • Array has negative elements → prefix sum + hash map (two pointers break).
#   • Need exact count of subarrays → prefix sum + hash map always works.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   |A∪B∪C| = |A|+|B|+|C| - |A∩B| - |A∩C| - |B∩C| + |A∩B∩C| — alternating sum
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "sum of first N"
#   - "sum from 1 to"
#   - "total after N steps"
#   - "arithmetic sequence"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Computing sum in a loop when n=10^9 → TLE; use n*(n+1)//2
#   ✗ Forgetting integer division: n*(n+1)/2 returns float in Python 3 → use //
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║                CHAPTER 8 — TWO POINTERS + SLIDING WINDOW                 ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║  ⚡ QUICK LOOK — CH08 DECISION TABLE                          [TWO-PTR]     ║
# ╠════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
# ║  PROBLEM TYPE                       → TECHNIQUE                             ║
# ║  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────  ║
# ║  Pair with target sum, sorted       → Two pointers converging               ║
# ║  Longest subarray with property     → Sliding window (expand/shrink)        ║
# ║  Exactly K distinct elements        → count(exactly k) = count(≤k)-count(≤k-1)║
# ║  Minimum window containing all      → Sliding window + frequency map        ║
# ║  Fixed window of size K             → Sliding window, deque for min/max     ║
