# 🧠 THE BIG PICTURE
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Two pointer techniques replace O(n²) nested loops with a single O(n) pass.
# The trick: instead of independently picking every pair (l, r), move them together.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ⚡ THE CORE IDEA — MONOTONICITY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • These techniques work when the answer has a MONOTONIC property: "If window [l,
#       r] is valid, then [l, r-1] is also valid." "If [l, r] is invalid, then [l,
#       r+1] is also invalid."
#
# • This means: as l increases, the optimal r can only INCREASE (never go back left).
# • So instead of trying all (l, r) pairs — O(n²) — we just move r forward as l moves.
# • Total moves: r goes from 0 to n at most once, l goes from 0 to n at most once → O(n).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 THREE PATTERNS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# 1. OPPOSITE ENDS: lo starts at left, hi at right. Move toward each other.
#    Use when: sorted array + find pair with sum = target.
#
# 2. SAME DIRECTION (sliding window): both move left to right.
#    Use when: find longest/shortest subarray satisfying a condition.
#
# 3. FAST & SLOW (Floyd's): one pointer moves 1x, other moves 2x.
#    Use when: detecting cycles in linked lists.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Two pointers work only when shrinking the window from the left is always correct as right expands
#   - "Longest subarray / substring satisfying constraint" → sliding window
#   - "Find pair with sum = target in sorted array" → opposite-end pointers
#   - "Count pairs (i,j) where a[i]+a[j] ≤ k" → sort + two pointer sweep
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Off-by-one in boundary conditions (l vs l-1, r vs r+1)
#   ✗ Not handling n=0 or n=1 edge case
#   ✗ Integer overflow: use // not / for integer division in Python
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What does brute force look like?
#   2. What is the complexity bottleneck?
#   3. What structure or property enables optimization?
#   ✗ Moving both pointers inward unconditionally — only move the one that fixes the invariant
#   ✗ Shrinking window before checking — always update answer BEFORE shrinking
#   ✗ Two-pointer on unsorted array when the monotonicity property only holds after sorting
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 💡 WHEN TO RECOGNIZE THIS PATTERN
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Signal words in problem: "subarray", "substring", "window", "consecutive",
# "at most k", "minimum length", "maximum sum". These scream two pointers.
#
# Two pointers and sliding window are AMORTIZED O(n) techniques.
# They replace nested loops with a single pass by exploiting MONOTONICITY.

# 8A. TWO POINTER — Opposite Ends

# Place left pointer at start, right at end. Move based on condition.
# Classic: Two Sum in sorted array.
