# 🧠 PRE-CHAPTER 9 — RANGE QUERY THEORY & THE BIT PROOF
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# §1. THE RANGE QUERY PROBLEM — FORMAL STATEMENT

# PROBLEM: Given array A[1..n], support two operations:
#   UPDATE(i, val): modify A[i].
#   QUERY(l, r): compute f(A[l], A[l+1], …, A[r]) for some function f.
#
# Where f can be: sum, min, max, GCD, XOR, product, …
#
# REQUIREMENT: f must be associative (we process in order).
#              f(a, f(b, c)) = f(f(a, b), c)  for all a, b, c.
#   ✓ sum, min, max, GCD, XOR, and, or, multiply.
#   ✗ average (not associative in the traditional sense without size info).
#
# With identity element e: f(e, x) = f(x, e) = x for all x.
#   sum: e=0.  product: e=1.  min: e=+∞.  max: e=−∞.  XOR: e=0.

# §2. WHY THE BINARY INDEXED TREE WORKS — THE PROOF

# The BIT exploits the binary representation of indices to decompose prefix sums.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHAT THIS MEANS: For integer i > 0, let lowbit(i) = i & (-i) = least significant bit of i.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   lowbit(6) = lowbit(110₂) = 010₂ = 2
#   lowbit(8) = lowbit(1000₂) = 1000₂ = 8
#   lowbit(12) = lowbit(1100₂) = 0100₂ = 4
#
# TREE STRUCTURE: BIT[i] stores the sum of A[i - lowbit(i) + 1 .. i].
#   Range covered by BIT[i]: [i - lowbit(i) + 1, i], length = lowbit(i).
#   Examples:
# • BIT[1]=A[1] (covers 1 element)    BIT[2]=A[1]+A[2] (covers 2) BIT[3]=A[3]
#       (covers 1)            BIT[4]=A[1..4]   (covers 4) BIT[5]=A[5]  (covers 1)
#       BIT[6]=A[5]+A[6] (covers 2) BIT[7]=A[7]  (covers 1)
#       BIT[8]=A[1..8]   (covers 8)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM for n=8:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Index:  1   2   3   4   5   6   7   8
#           │   │   │   │   │   │   │   │
#   BIT[i]: [1] [12][3][1234][5][56][7][12345678]
#
#   Ranges:
# • BIT[8]: A[1..8]    (length = lowbit(8) = 8) BIT[4]: A[1..4]    (length =
#       lowbit(4) = 4) BIT[6]: A[5..6]    (length = lowbit(6) = 2) BIT[2]: A[1..2]
#       (length = lowbit(2) = 2)
#
# PREFIX SUM QUERY: sum(1..i)
#   Decompose i in binary. Jump from i to i-lowbit(i) to ... to 0.
#   i=7=111₂: sum=BIT[7]+BIT[6]+BIT[4]
#             7→7-1=6→6-2=4→4-4=0 (stop).
#
#   PROOF this covers [1..7]:
#     BIT[7] = A[7]    (covers [7,7])
#     BIT[6] = A[5..6] (covers [5,6])
#     BIT[4] = A[1..4] (covers [1,4])
#     Union: [1..4] ∪ [5..6] ∪ [7] = [1..7]. ✓
#     No overlap: disjoint ranges. ✓
#     Complete coverage: no gaps. ✓
#
# UPDATE: add delta to A[i].
# • All BIT[j] that COVER position i must be updated.
# • These are: i, i+lowbit(i), i+lowbit(i+lowbit(i)), … WHY IT WORKS: BIT[j]
#       covers [j-lowbit(j)+1, j]. Position i is covered iff j-lowbit(j) < i ≤ j
# • Going up by adding lowbit ensures we visit all such j.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY O(log n) FOR BOTH?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • Each lowbit(i) strips the lowest bit of i.
# • An n-bit integer has at most n set bits → at most n = log₂(N) steps.
# • For N positions: at most floor(log2 N) + 1 steps.

# §3. SEGMENT TREE — WHY AT MOST 4 PARTIAL NODES PER LEVEL

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ CLAIM: A range query on the segment tree visits at most O(log n) nodes.  [RANGE]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • PRECISE STATEMENT: At each level of the tree, at most 4 nodes are "partial"
#       (neither fully inside nor fully outside the query range [l, r])
# • Fully inside nodes: returned immediately.
# • Fully outside: pruned immediately.
# Only partial nodes recurse further.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ PROOF SKETCH:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • At the topmost level, there is 1 node (the root).
# • At the next level, we split into at most 2 nodes.
# • A partial node at level k+1 is created from a partial node at level k.
#   At each level, a partial node creates at most 2 children, but:
# • - The leftmost partial node's right child is fully inside.
# • - The rightmost partial node's left child is fully inside.
# • So at each level, there are at most 2 new partial nodes and.
#   the rest are fully inside/outside.
#   Total: O(log n) nodes visited across all levels. ✓
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Query [3, 6] on tree covering [1, 8]:
#
#   Level 0: [1,8] — partial (overlaps query)
#                    /               \
#   Level 1: [1,4] partial     [5,8] partial
#              /       \         /       \
#   Level 2: [1,2] out  [3,4] IN  [5,6] IN  [7,8] out
#
#   "IN" = fully inside query [3,6]. Returned without further recursion.
#   "out" = fully outside. Pruned.
#   "partial" = must recurse.
#   Total nodes visited: 6 = O(log n). ✓

# §4. LAZY PROPAGATION — THEORY OF DEFERRED UPDATES

# PROBLEM: Range update: add δ to all A[l..r]. How to do this efficiently?
#
# NAIVE: Update each element. O(n) per update. With q queries: O(nq). TLE.
#
# LAZY PROPAGATION IDEA:
#   For segments fully inside the update range: mark the segment as "pending update".
#   Don't propagate to children yet.
#   When a query or further update NEEDS to go into the children:
#   PUSH DOWN the lazy tag to children before recursing.
#
# FORMAL INVARIANT:
# • t[v] = correct aggregate for the range of node v, ASSUMING all lazy tags on
#       the PATH FROM v TO ROOT have been applied
# • lazy[v] = pending update to be propagated to v's children.
#
# PUSH DOWN OPERATION:
# • For parent node v with children 2v and 2v+1: 1.
# • Apply lazy[v] to child aggregates: t[2v] += size(2v) * lazy[v], etc.
# • Accumulate lazy: lazy[2v] += lazy[v], lazy[2v+1] += lazy[v].
#   3. Clear parent lazy: lazy[v] = 0.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY CORRECT?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • After push down, t[2v] and t[2v+1] reflect the accumulated updates.
# • Future queries on children use these correct values.
# • The invariant is maintained: t[v] is always correct from v's perspective.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — Range add [2,5] with δ=3 on array [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8]:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Before update:
#   t[root]=[36], covers [1..8]
#   t[left]=[10], covers [1..4]    t[right]=[26], covers [5..8]
#
#   Update [2,5] with +3:
#   Root [1..8] partial → recurse.
#     Left [1..4] partial → recurse.
#       Left [1..2] partial → recurse.
#         Left [1] outside. Skip.
# • Right [2] FULLY inside.
# • t[node_2] += 1*3=3.
# • lazy[node_2]=3.
# • Update t[1..2]: += 1*3 (one element updated).
# • Right [3..4] FULLY inside.
# • t[node_34] += 2*3=6.
# • lazy[node_34]=3.
#     Update t[1..4]: total += (1+2)*3 = 9.
#     Right [5..8] partial → recurse.
#       Left [5..6] FULLY inside. t[node_56] += 2*3=6. lazy[node_56]=3. Done.
#       Right [7..8] outside. Skip.
#     Update t[5..8]: += 2*3=6.
#   Update t[root]: += (1+2+2)*3 = 15.
#   New t[root] = 36+12 = 48. ✓  (4 elements × 3 = 12; 36+12=48 ✓)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Suffix array: sorted array of all suffixes — build in O(n log n), LCP array in O(n)
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "all substrings"
#   - "longest repeated substring"
#   - "lexicographically smallest rotation"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Naive suffix array construction is O(n² log n) — must use O(n log n) doubling or SA-IS
#   ✗ LCP array requires suffix array; kasai's algorithm builds LCP in O(n) from SA
#
