# 🧠 MENTAL MODELS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Prefix Sum   → "Precompute running totals.
# • Range sum in O(1)." BIT (Fenwick) → "Binary-indexed: update one, query prefix
#       in O(log n)" Segment Tree → "Divide and conquer on intervals: O(log n)
#       update & query"
#
#   Decision guide:
# • Static range sum only?         → Prefix sum (simplest) Point update + prefix
#       query?   → BIT (simpler code, same speed as segtree) Range update + range
#       query?    → Lazy segment tree Non-additive function (max)?   → Segment
#       tree (BIT can't do this easily)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Segment tree = binary tree where each node stores f(left child, right child)
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Is this a static range query (no updates)? → prefix sum or sparse table
#   2. Are there point updates? → Binary Indexed Tree (BIT / Fenwick)
#   3. Are there range updates and range queries? → Segment Tree with lazy propagation
#   → Match structure to operation type; segment tree handles every case at O(log n)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "sum/min/max of arbitrary range [l, r]"          → prefix/BIT/segtree
#
#   ► "after each update, query range property"         → BIT or segtree
#
#   ► "count elements smaller than x in prefix a[0..i]" → BIT + coordinate compress
#
#   ► "range assign (set all to v) + range sum query"   → lazy segtree
#
#   ► "count inversions in array"                       → BIT (classic application) ★

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Summing range [l, r] in O(r-l+1) for each query → O(n) per query → O(nq) total
#
#   ✓  Prefix sum: psum[r+1] - psum[l] → O(1) per query after O(n) preprocessing
#
#   ✗  Naive BIT: confusing 1-indexed vs 0-indexed
#
#   ✓  BIT is ALWAYS 1-indexed. Convert: bit array is bit[1..n], a[i] maps to bit[i+1].
#
#   ✗  Segment tree for simple prefix sums (over-engineering)
#
#   ✓  Use BIT for point-update + prefix-query. It's faster and simpler.
#       Use segtree when you need range-update or non-additive operations.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   BIT for point-update + prefix-query O(log n); Seg tree when range-update or non-additive ops are needed
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Is this a static range query (no updates)? → prefix sum or sparse table
#   2. Are there point updates? → Binary Indexed Tree (BIT / Fenwick)
#   3. Are there range updates and range queries? → Segment Tree with lazy propagation
#   → Match structure to operation type; segment tree handles every case at O(log n)
#
