# 🎯 PRE-CHAPTER 10 — BINARY NUMBER THEORY & BITWISE ALGEBRA  [MATH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# §1. BINARY REPRESENTATION AND TWO'S COMPLEMENT

# POSITIONAL NOTATION: An n-bit integer stores a value in base 2.
#   x = bₙ₋₁·2^{n-1} + bₙ₋₂·2^{n-2} + … + b₁·2 + b₀
#   where each bᵢ ∈ {0, 1}.
#
# Examples:
#   1010₂ = 1·8 + 0·4 + 1·2 + 0·1 = 10
#   1111₂ = 8+4+2+1 = 15 = 2⁴ − 1
#   2ⁿ − 1 = 11…1₂ (n ones) — maximum n-bit unsigned value
#
# TWO'S COMPLEMENT (how negative numbers are stored):
#   For a signed n-bit integer:
#   Positive x (0 ≤ x < 2^{n-1}): stored as binary representation.
#   Negative x (-2^{n-1} ≤ x < 0): stored as 2ⁿ + x = 2ⁿ − |x|.
#
#   KEY FORMULA: −x = ~x + 1 (flip all bits, then add 1)
#   This means: x + (~x) = all 1s = -1.
#   And: x + (-x) = 0 ✓ (as 2's complement arithmetic).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY i & (-i) = lowbit(i):
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   -i in two's complement = flip all bits of i, then add 1.
#   i:    …ab10…0  (some bits, then the lowest 1, then k zeros)
#   flip: …ā b̄01…1
#   +1:   …ā b̄10…0  (carry propagates until the lowest 1)
#   i&(-i): …0 0 10…0  (only the lowest 1-bit survives!)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   i = 1100₂ = 12
#   -i: flip(1100) = 0011. Add 1: 0100 = 4.
#   i & (-i) = 1100 & 0100 = 0100 = 4. ✓ (lowest set bit of 12 is 4)

# §2. BOOLEAN ALGEBRA — THE THEORY BEHIND BITWISE OPERATIONS

# Bitwise operations are applied BIT BY BIT independently.
# Each bit follows Boolean algebra laws.
#
# BOOLEAN ALGEBRA AXIOMS:
# • Commutativity:   a & b = b & a,   a | b = b | a Associativity:   (a&b)&c =
#       a&(b&c),   (a|b)|c = a|(b|c) Distributivity:  a&(b|c) = (a&b)|(a&c),
#       a|(b&c) = (a|b)&(a|c) Identity:        a & 1 = a,   a | 0 = a Complement:
#       a & ~a = 0,   a | ~a = all 1s Idempotent:      a & a = a,   a | a = a
#   Double negation: ~~a = a
#
# XOR SPECIFIC LAWS:
#   a ^ a = 0        (self-cancellation — unique to XOR!)
#   a ^ 0 = a        (identity)
#   a ^ b = b ^ a    (commutativity)
#   (a^b)^c = a^(b^c) (associativity)
#   a ^ ~a = all 1s
#   If a ^ b = c, then a ^ c = b and b ^ c = a  (all three are "siblings")
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ CRITICAL XOR APPLICATION — Finding single non-duplicate:  [BIT]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • Given array where every element appears twice except one.
# • XOR all elements: duplicates cancel (x^x=0), unique survives.
# • a[0]^a[1]^…^a[n-1] = 0^0^…^0^unique = unique.

# §3. BITMASKS AS SET REPRESENTATIONS

#   Bit k is set ↔ element k is in S.
#
# 💡 IDEA:
#   • Represent a subset S ⊆ {0,1,…,n-1} as an integer mask.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ OPERATION S:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   ┌─────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────┬──────────────────────┐
#   │ Set operation               │ Integer operation    │ Example (n=4)        │
#   ├─────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┤
#   │ Empty set ∅                 │ 0                    │ 0000                 │
#   │ Universal set {0..n-1}      │ (1<<n) - 1           │ 1111 = 15            │
#   │ Singleton {k}               │ 1 << k               │ 1<<2 = 0100 = {2}    │
#   │ k ∈ S?                      │ (S >> k) & 1         │ (0101>>2)&1 = 1 ✓   │
#   │ S ∪ {k}                     │ S | (1 << k)         │ 0101 | 0100 = 0101  │
#   │ S \ {k}                     │ S & ~(1 << k)        │ 0101 & 1011 = 0001  │
#   │ S ∩ T                       │ S & T                │ 0101 & 0110 = 0100  │
#   │ S ∪ T                       │ S | T                │ 0101 | 0110 = 0111  │
#   │ Complement of S             │ ((1<<n)-1) ^ S       │ 1111 ^ 0101 = 1010  │
#   │ |S| (popcount)              │ bin(S).count('1')    │ bin(5)='101' → 2    │
#   │ S ⊆ T?                      │ (S & T) == S         │                      │
#   │ Lowest element of S         │ lowbit(S) = S&(-S)   │ 0110&1010=0010→bit1 │
#   │ Remove lowest element       │ S & (S-1)            │ 0110&0101=0100      │
#   └─────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────┴──────────────────────┘
#
# ITERATING OVER ALL SUBSETS OF A MASK (key for bitmask DP):
#
#   sub = mask
#   while sub > 0:
#       process(sub)   ← each sub is a non-empty subset of mask
#       sub = (sub - 1) & mask
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY THIS WORKS:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • (sub-1) clears the lowest bit of sub and sets all lower bits.
# • & mask keeps only bits that are in mask.
# • This generates all 2^popcount(mask) subsets exactly once, in decreasing order.
#
# • Total work over ALL masks: Σ_{mask} 2^popcount(mask) = 3^n.
# • Proof: for each of n bits, it can be: in neither mask nor sub (1 way), in mask
#       but not sub (1 way), or in both (1 way)

# §4. BITMASK DP — THE STATE SPACE DESIGN

# whether to include or exclude each element.
#
# • STATE: dp[mask] = best answer when the "selected" or "visited" set = mask.
# • TRANSITION: Try adding element k (not yet in mask) to mask.
# • dp[mask | (1<<k)] = combine(dp[mask], cost(k, mask)).
#
# • PROCESS ORDER: Iterate mask from 0 to 2^n - 1.
# • When processing mask, all subsets of mask (smaller masks) are already computed.
# • Since we add elements (mask grows), all predecessors are computed.
#
# 🚀 USE CASES:
#   • TO USE: Problem involves a small set (n ≤ 20) and decisions about
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ DIAGRAM — TSP (4 cities, start at 0):
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • mask=0001 (only city 0): dp[0001][0]=0.
# • mask=0011 (cities 0,1):  dp[0011][1] = dp[0001][0] + dist[0][1]. mask=0101
#       (cities 0,2):  dp[0101][2] = dp[0001][0] + dist[0][2]
#   ...
#   mask=1111 (all cities):  dp[1111][v] = min over v of (path ending at v visiting all).
#   Answer: min over v of dp[1111][v] + dist[v][0].
#
#   State space: 2⁴ masks × 4 cities = 64 states. For n=20: 20·2²⁰ ≈ 2×10⁷.
#
# 🧠 INTUITION:
#   • for transition direction:
# • We build solutions from smaller subsets to larger subsets.
# • "To visit all cities in mask ending at v, the previous step was at some city u
#       ≠ v with mask without v: dp[mask ^ (1<<v)][u] + dist[u][v]."
#
