# §1. FORMAL GRAPH DEFINITIONS

# • IN SIMPLE TERMS: A graph G = (V, E) is a pair where: V = finite non-empty set
#       of vertices (nodes) E ⊆ V×V = set of edges (pairs of vertices)
#
# For UNDIRECTED graphs: {u,v} ∈ E (unordered pair, edge goes both ways).
# For DIRECTED graphs (digraphs): (u,v) ∈ E (ordered pair, edge goes u->v only).
#
# KEY NOTATIONS:
#   n = |V| = number of vertices
#   m = |E| = number of edges

# §2. THE COMPLETE TAXONOMY OF GRAPHS

# By edge direction:
# • Undirected: edges have no direction.
# • (u,v) = (v,u).
# • Directed (digraph): edges have direction.
# • (u,v) ≠ (v,u).
# • Mixed: some edges directed, some not.
# • (rare in CP).
#
# By edge weights:
#   Unweighted: all edges equal. (w=1 implicit)
#   Weighted: each edge (u,v) has weight w(u,v) ∈ ℝ.
#             Positive weights: Dijkstra applies.
#             Negative weights: Bellman-Ford needed.
#
# By special structure:
# • SIMPLE: no self-loops (edge from v to v), no multi-edges (duplicate edges).
# • COMPLETE (Kₙ): every pair of vertices is connected.
# • m = n(n-1)/2.
# • BIPARTITE: vertices split into sets L and R; all edges go between L and R.
# • PLANAR: can be drawn on a plane without edge crossings.
# • REGULAR: every vertex has the same degree.
#
# By connectivity:
# • CONNECTED (undirected): path exists between every pair of vertices.
# • DISCONNECTED: some vertices unreachable from others.
# • STRONGLY CONNECTED (directed): path exists between every ORDERED pair (u->v AND v→u).
#   WEAKLY CONNECTED (directed): connected if we ignore edge directions.
# • TREE: connected and acyclic (n vertices, n-1 edges).
# • FOREST: acyclic (possibly disconnected).
# • Each component is a tree.
# • DAG: Directed Acyclic Graph.
# • No directed cycles.

# §3. GRAPH TERMINOLOGY — COMPLETE DICTIONARY

# • DEGREE: deg(v) = number of edges incident to v.
# • In directed graphs: in-deg(v) = incoming edges, out-deg(v) = outgoing edges.
# • HANDSHAKING RULE: Sum of all vertex degrees = 2 × (number of edges).
#   Each edge is counted twice (once for each endpoint) — hence the factor of 2.
#   Side effect: the number of vertices with odd degree is always even.
#
# PATH: A sequence of vertices v₀, v₁, …, vₖ where each step (vᵢ → vᵢ₊₁) is an edge.l i.
#   SIMPLE PATH: no vertex repeated.
#   LENGTH: number of edges (= k for path of k+1 vertices).
#   SHORTEST PATH: path with minimum total weight (or minimum edges if unweighted).
#
# • WALK: Like a path but vertices/edges can repeat.
# • TRAIL: Walk with no repeated EDGES (vertices can repeat).
# • EULER TRAIL: Trail using every edge exactly once.
# • HAMILTONIAN PATH: Path using every VERTEX exactly once.
#
# • CYCLE: Path from v back to v (closed path).
# • SIMPLE CYCLE: no repeated vertices (except start=end).
# • ODD/EVEN CYCLE: odd/even number of edges.
#   BIPARTITE ↔ No odd cycles.  (Proof: 2-coloring works if and only if no odd cycle exists.)
#
# • DISTANCE: d(u,v) = length of shortest path from u to v.
# • DIAMETER: max over all pairs (u,v) of d(u,v).
# • ECCENTRICITY of v: max over all u of d(v,u).
# • RADIUS: min over all v of eccentricity(v).
# • CENTER: vertex with minimum eccentricity.
#
# COMPONENT: maximal connected subgraph.
# • BRIDGE: edge whose removal disconnects the graph.
# • ARTICULATION POINT: vertex whose removal disconnects the graph.
# • STRONGLY CONNECTED COMPONENT (SCC): maximal strongly connected subgraph in digraph.

# §4. GRAPH REPRESENTATION — DETAILED ANALYSIS

# REPRESENTATION 1: ADJACENCY LIST
#   adj[u] = list of neighbors (or (neighbor, weight) pairs).
#   Space: O(n + m). Perfect for sparse graphs (m << n²).
#
#   Undirected graph: each edge (u,v) stored twice: in adj[u] and adj[v].
#   COMMON BUG: forgetting to add both adj[u].append(v) AND adj[v].append(u).
#
#   Operations:
#   - Check if edge (u,v) exists: O(deg(u)). [Not O(1)!]
#   - Iterate over neighbors of u: O(deg(u)).
#   - Iterate over all edges: O(n + m).
#
# REPRESENTATION 2: ADJACENCY MATRIX
#   matrix[u][v] = weight of edge u->v (0 or ∞ if no edge).
#   Space: O(n²). ONLY for dense graphs or small n (n ≤ 1000).
#
#   Operations:
#   - Check if edge (u,v) exists: O(1).
#   - Iterate over neighbors of u: O(n). [Even for sparse graphs!]
#   - Floyd-Warshall requires O(n²) space anyway → adjacency matrix fine.
#
# REPRESENTATION 3: EDGE LIST
#   edges = [(u, v, w)] for all edges.
#   Space: O(m).
#   Use for: Kruskal's algorithm (sort edges by weight).
#
# CHOOSING REPRESENTATION:
# • n ≤ 1000 and dense:             adjacency matrix.
# • n ≤ 10⁵, general graph:         adjacency list.
# • Only need to sort/process edges: edge list.

# §5. GRAPH INVARIANTS AND THEOREMS

# • HANDSHAKING RULE: Sum of all degrees = 2 × number of edges.
# • In any graph, the number of vertices with odd degree is always even.
# • Average degree = 2 × edges / vertices.
#
# TREE CHARACTERIZATIONS (all equivalent):
#   (a) Connected and acyclic.
#   (b) Connected and has n-1 edges.
#   (c) Acyclic and has n-1 edges.
# • (d) Any two vertices connected by exactly one path.
# • (e) Connected; removing any edge disconnects it.
# • (f) Acyclic; adding any edge creates exactly one cycle.
#
#   PROOF that (a) → (b): Induction on n.
# • n=1: trivially true (0 edges).
# • n>1: take a leaf (degree 1 vertex, exists in tree).
# • Remaining graph is still connected and acyclic (tree by induction) with n-1
#       vertices and n-2 edges
# • Add back the leaf: n vertices, n-1 edges.
#
# EULER PATH/CIRCUIT CONDITIONS:
# UNDIRECTED:
#     Euler circuit exists ↔ connected AND every vertex has even degree.
#     Euler path exists ↔ connected AND exactly 2 vertices have odd degree.
#   DIRECTED:
# • Euler circuit exists ↔ strongly connected AND in-deg(v)=out-deg(v) for all v.
# • Euler path exists ↔ weakly connected AND in-deg(v)≠out-deg(v) for exactly 2
#       vertices, one with out-deg=in-deg+1 (start) and one with in-deg=out-deg+1
#       (end)
#
# BIPARTITE RULE: A graph is bipartite if and only if it has no odd-length cycles.
# • WHY (→): In a 2-coloring, a cycle must keep alternating colors → even length.
# • WHY (←): If no odd cycles, BFS-coloring works without conflict.
# • If any contradiction arises, there's an odd cycle (the path in BFS tree
#   plus the cross edge forms a cycle).
# • Contrapositive: ✓.
#
# DIAGRAM — Bipartite vs non-bipartite:
#
#   Bipartite (K₂,₃):        Non-bipartite (triangle):
#   L={1,2}, R={3,4,5}            1
#   1-3, 1-4, 1-5              /    \
#   2-3, 2-4, 2-5             2 ─── 3
#   (all edges cross           (odd cycle 1-2-3-1!)
#    L-R boundary)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Brute force + pruning = exponential with smart cutoffs — try all, skip dead branches
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
