# 🎯 GRAPH TAXONOMY — know what type you have before coding  [GRAPH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# A graph G = (V, E) consists of:
# • Vertices (nodes): V = {1, 2, ..., n}
# • Edges: E = set of pairs (u, v) representing connections
#
# TYPES OF GRAPHS:
# • Undirected: edges are symmetric. (u,v) = (v,u).
# • Directed (Digraph): edges have direction. (u,v) ≠ (v,u).
# • Weighted: each edge has a weight/cost.
# • Simple: no self-loops, no multiple edges.
# • Complete: every pair of vertices is connected.
# • Bipartite: vertices split into two groups, edges only between groups.
# • DAG: Directed Acyclic Graph. No cycles.
# • Tree: connected undirected graph with no cycles (n vertices, n-1 edges).
#
# KEY GRAPH PROPERTIES:
# n = |V| = number of vertices
# m = |E| = number of edges
# • Undirected: m ≤ n(n-1)/2.
# • Directed: m ≤ n(n-1).
# • Sparse graph: m = O(n).
# • Dense graph: m = O(n²).
# • Degree of v = number of edges incident to v.
# • Sum of all degrees = 2m (handshaking lemma).

# 11A. GRAPH REPRESENTATIONS

# CHOICE MATTERS for performance:
#
# • ADJACENCY LIST (use this 90% of the time): adj[u] = list of (v, weight) for
#       each edge u->v
# • Space: O(n + m).
# • Perfect for sparse graphs.
#    Iterate over neighbors: O(degree(u)).
#
n_graph=int(input())
m_graph=int(input())
adj=[[] for _ in range(n_graph+1)]
for _ in range(m_graph):
    u, v, w=map(int, input().split())
    adj[u].append((v, w))
    adj[v].append((u, w))
#
# 2. ADJACENCY MATRIX:
# • matrix[u][v] = weight of edge u->v (0 or inf if no edge).
# • Good for dense graphs and Floyd-Warshall.
# • Check edge: O(1).
# • Iterate neighbors: O(n).
# • Use when: n ≤ 1000 and dense graph, or for Floyd-Warshall.
#
# 3. EDGE LIST:
# edges = [(weight, u, v)] for each edge.
# Use for: Kruskal's MST (sort edges by weight).
#
# ⚠ COMMON MISTAKE:
# • - Using 1-indexed but forgetting to size arrays as n+1.
# • - Forgetting to add both directions for undirected graphs.
# • - Using matrix for n=10^5 → O(n²) space = TLE/MLE.
#
