# §1. THE DFS TREE — CLASSIFYING EDGES

# When DFS runs on a graph, it builds a DFS TREE (or DFS FOREST for disconnected graphs).
# The tree consists of TREE EDGES — edges that led to unvisited vertices.
# Non-tree edges are classified into:
#
# In UNDIRECTED graphs (2 types):
# • TREE EDGE: edge to an unvisited vertex.
# • Forms the DFS tree.
# • BACK EDGE: edge to an ancestor in the DFS tree.
# • Indicates a cycle.
# • (There are no forward/cross edges in undirected DFS — every non-tree edge is back.).
#
# In DIRECTED graphs (4 types):
# • TREE EDGE:    (u,v) where v was first discovered via u.
# • BACK EDGE:    (u,v) where v is an ancestor of u in DFS tree.
# • → Cycle indicator.
# • FORWARD EDGE: (u,v) where v is a descendant of u (but not via tree edge).
# • CROSS EDGE:   (u,v) where v is neither ancestor nor descendant of u.
#
# DIAGRAM — DFS on undirected graph with 5 vertices:
#
#   Graph: 1-2, 2-3, 3-4, 4-5, 5-2 (forms a cycle 2-3-4-5-2)
#
#   DFS from 1:
#   Visit 1. Tree edge 1→2.
#   Visit 2. Tree edge 2→3.
#   Visit 3. Tree edge 3→4.
#   Visit 4. Tree edge 4→5.
#   Visit 5. Edge 5-2: 2 is already visited AND is ancestor. → BACK EDGE.
#            Back edge 5→2 indicates cycle 2-3-4-5.
#   Return to 4,3,2,1.
#
#   DFS Tree:
#   1 — 2 — 3 — 4 — 5
#       ↑_____________↑ (back edge 5→2)
#
# KEY RULE:
#   An undirected graph has a cycle if and only if DFS finds a back edge.
#   A directed graph has a cycle if and only if DFS finds a back edge.

# §2. DFS ENTRY/EXIT TIMES — THE EULER TOUR

# • During DFS, assign two timestamps to each vertex: tin[v]  = time when
#       ENTERS vertex v (pre-order time)
# • tout[v] = time when DFS EXITS vertex v (post-order time, after all descendants).
#
# FUNDAMENTAL PROPERTY:
#   For any two vertices u and v in the DFS tree:
#   u is an ancestor of v  ↔  tin[u] ≤ tin[v] AND tout[v] ≤ tout[u]
#
#   In words: the time interval [tin[v], tout[v]] is nested INSIDE [tin[u], tout[u]]
#             if and only if v is a descendant of u.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                   📊 DIAGRAM                              │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

#   Tree:     1
#            / \
#           2   5
#          / \
#         3   4
#
#   tin:  1→0, 2→1, 3→2, 4→4, 5→6
#   (Recomputed cleanly via DFS below.)
#
#   DFS from 1 (preorder: 1,2,3,4,5, postorder: 3,4,2,5,1):
#   tin[1]=0, tin[2]=1, tin[3]=2, tout[3]=3, tin[4]=4, tout[4]=5, tout[2]=6, tin[5]=7, tout[5]=8, tout[1]=9
#
#   Is 3 in subtree of 2? tin[2]=1 ≤ tin[3]=2 ✓ AND tout[3]=3 ≤ tout[2]=6 ✓. YES. ✓
#   Is 5 in subtree of 2? tin[2]=1 ≤ tin[5]=7 ✓ BUT tout[5]=8 > tout[2]=6 ✗. NO. ✓
#
# APPLICATIONS OF EULER TOUR:
# • "Is u an ancestor of v?" → O(1) check using tin/tout.
# • Flatten subtree to array: all vertices in subtree of v are in [tin[v],
#       tout[v]]. This allows range queries on subtrees using BIT or segment tree!
#       3
# • Heavy-Light Decomposition uses this to linearize paths on trees.

# §3. BFS — THE LEVEL STRUCTURE AND SHORTEST PATH PROOF

# BFS LEVELS: Level k = set of vertices at distance exactly k from source.
#
#   Level 0: {source}
#   Level 1: all vertices adjacent to source (not in level 0)
#   Level 2: all vertices adjacent to level 1 (not in levels 0,1)
#   ...
#
# KEY FACT: BFS always finds the shortest path in an unweighted graph.
#
# WHY IT WORKS (by level):
#   Every vertex reached at BFS level k is exactly k hops from the source.
#
#   Base case k=0: source is at level 0, distance 0. ✓
#
# • Inductive step: Assume all vertices at levels 0..k-1 have correct shortest paths.
# • Consider vertex v at level k.
# • It was discovered from some u at level k-1 via edge (u,v).
# • dist[v] = dist[u] + 1 = (k-1) + 1 = k.
# • Is this the shortest? Suppose there's a shorter path of length j < k.
# • That path must pass through some vertex w adjacent to v with dist[w] < j < k.
# • By induction, w is at level dist[w] ≤ k-1. Any vertex adjacent to v and at level < k-1
# • w adjacent to v means w is at level k-1 at most (otherwise v would be discovered earlier).
# • If a path of length j < k reaches v, the vertex before v on this path has distance j-1 < k-1.
# • By induction, this vertex is at level j-1 < k-1.
# • But then v would have been discovered at level j, not k.
# • Contradiction with k being v's level.
#   Therefore dist[v] = k is indeed the shortest distance. □
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   DFS=cycle/topo/components; BFS=shortest path unweighted — both visit every node once O(V+E)
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
#
#
