# the invariant that vertices in the queue are in non-decreasing distance order.
#
# • For 0-1 weights: a 0-weight edge doesn't increase distance → the new vertex
#   should be processed BEFORE vertices at the current distance.
# • Use a DEQUE: 0-weight edges → push FRONT (same distance), 1-weight → push BACK (distance+1).
#
# INVARIANT: Deque always contains vertices ordered by non-decreasing distance.
# • Proof: Popping from front gives min-distance vertex (like Dijkstra's heap).
# • 0-edges: new vertex has same distance → front.
# • ✓ 1-edges: new vertex has distance+1 → back.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                   📊 DIAGRAM                              │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# • Deque: [dist=2, dist=2, dist=3, dist=3, dist=4] Pop front (dist=2).
# • Edge with weight 0: new vertex has dist=2 → push front.
# • Pop front (dist=2).
# • Edge with weight 1: new vertex has dist=3 → push back.
# • Deque: [dist=2, dist=3, dist=3, dist=3, dist=4]  ← still sorted! ✓.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Queue = FIFO; use collections.deque for O(1) popleft — BFS needs this
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "divisible by"
#   - "remainder when divided"
#   - "modulo"
#   - "last K digits"
#   - "periodic pattern"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Doing (a*b)%m without wrapping a,b first → overflow in C++ (fine in Python but slow)
#   ✗ Subtracting mod: (a-b)%m can be negative → use (a-b+m)%m
#   ✗ Division mod p: a/b%p ≠ (a%p)/(b%p) → use modular inverse b^(p-2)%p
#
#
