# ⚡ PRE-CHAPTER 13 — SHORTEST PATH THEORY & RELAXATION PROOFS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# §1. THE TRIANGLE INEQUALITY AND RELAXATION

# • TRIANGLE INEQUALITY FOR SHORTEST PATHS: For any edge (u, v, w): d[s][v] ≤
#       d[s][u] + w(u,v) "The shortest path to v cannot be longer than going
#       through u then using edge (u,v)."
#
# RELAXATION OPERATION: For edge (u, v, w):
#   if d[u] + w < d[v]:
#       d[v] = d[u] + w
#
# • This is the core operation of ALL shortest path algorithms.
# • Dijkstra, Bellman-Ford, and Floyd-Warshall all just differ in THE ORDER
#   and NUMBER of relaxations performed.
#
# CORRECTNESS CONDITION: d[v] is correct if and only if we've performed ALL necessary relaxations.
#   Specifically: d[v] is correct if and only if the shortest path to v has been "relaxed into d[v]."

# §2. WHY DIJKSTRA IS CORRECT — THE GREEDY INVARIANT

# DIJKSTRA'S INVARIANT:
#   When we finalize a vertex v (extract it from the priority queue):
#   d[v] = true shortest distance from source to v.
#
# PROOF by induction on the number of finalized vertices:
#   Base case: source is finalized first with d[source]=0. ✓
#
# • Inductive step: Assume all previously finalized vertices have correct distances.
# • Let v be the next vertex to be finalized with tentative distance d[v].
#   Claim: d[v] is the true shortest distance.
#
# • Suppose not: there exists a shorter path P from source to v.
# • P must pass through some unfinalized vertex w (since all finalized vertices
#   have correct distances by the inductive hypothesis).
# • Let w be the first unfinalized vertex on path P (the "boundary" vertex).
# • The sub-path from source to w is a prefix of P, so its length ≤ length(P) < d[v].
#   *** HERE WE USE: all edge weights ≥ 0. ***
#   Because weights are non-negative, extending the path from w onward cannot
#   decrease its length. Therefore d[w] ≤ length(source→w) ≤ length(P) < d[v].
#   But when w was relaxed its tentative distance was already set ≤ length(source→w),
#   so d[w] ≤ d[v].
# • But we chose v as the vertex with MINIMUM tentative distance!
#   d[w] ≤ d[v] means w should have been chosen before (or instead of) v.
# • Contradiction — w is still unfinalized, yet has tentative distance ≤ d[v].
#   Therefore no such shorter path P can exist, and d[v] is correct. □
#
# • CRUCIAL: This proof requires all edge weights ≥ 0.
#   The key step above fails with a negative edge: a path through an unfinalized
#   vertex could become shorter as we travel further (negative extension), so
#   d[w] ≤ d[v] is no longer guaranteed. Use Bellman-Ford for negative weights.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                   📊 DIAGRAM                              │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

#   Source S. Finalized set F = {S, A, B}. Next to finalize: C with d[C]=7.
#
#   S→A (w=2): A finalized, d[A]=2. ✓
#   S→B (w=5): B finalized, d[B]=5. ✓
#   B→C (w=2): d[C] = d[B]+2 = 7.
#   A→C (w=8): d[C] already = 7 < 2+8=10. No update.
#
# • Finalizing C with d[C]=7: is there a shorter path? Any path must go through S→...→C.
# • The last unfinalized vertex before C would need to have tentative distance < 7.
# • But C has the minimum (7) in the heap.
#   So no such path exists. d[C]=7 is correct. ✓

# §3. WHY BELLMAN-FORD NEEDS V-1 ITERATIONS

# CLAIM: After k iterations of Bellman-Ford, d[v] = shortest distance using ≤ k edges.
#
# PROOF by induction on k:
#   Base case k=0: d[source]=0, d[others]=∞. Shortest path with 0 edges is only source. ✓
#
# • Inductive step: Assume after k-1 iterations, d[v] = shortest path using ≤ k-1
#       edges
# • In iteration k: for every edge (u,v,w), if d[u]+w < d[v], update d[v]. The
#       shortest path using exactly k edges to v ends with some edge (u,v)
# • After k-1 iterations, d[u] = shortest path using ≤ k-1 edges to u (by induction).
# • The relaxation d[u]+w gives the shortest path using ≤ k edges to v.
#
# WHY V-1 IS SUFFICIENT:
# • Any SIMPLE path (no repeated vertices) uses at most V-1 edges.
# • After V-1 iterations, all simple paths are accounted for.
# • If d[v] still improves in the V-th iteration → there's a negative cycle.
# • (A negative cycle allows infinite improvement by going around it.).

# §4. FLOYD-WARSHALL — THE DP DERIVATION

# DEFINE: dist[k][i][j] = shortest path from i to j using only vertices {1..k}
#         as intermediate vertices (not counting i and j themselves).
#
# BASE CASE: dist[0][i][j] = w(i,j) if edge (i,j) exists, else ∞. dist[0][i][i] = 0.
#
# TRANSITION: For intermediate vertex k:
#   dist[k][i][j] = min(dist[k-1][i][j],   ← don't use vertex k
#                       dist[k-1][i][k] + dist[k-1][k][j])  ← use vertex k
#
#   "Either the shortest path doesn't go through k, or it goes through k once
#    (entering from i via optimal path, then leaving to j via optimal path)."
#
# SPACE OPTIMIZATION: Since dist[k][i][j] only depends on dist[k-1][*][*]:
#   Use 2D array and update IN-PLACE!
#   dist[i][j] = min(dist[i][j], dist[i][k] + dist[k][j])
#   for k from 1 to n.
#   (In-place is safe because dist[i][k] and dist[k][j] are not changed when
#    processing row/column k in the k-th iteration.
#    Specifically: dist[i][k] could only decrease via min(dist[i][k], dist[i][k]+dist[k][k]),
#    but dist[k][k]=0 (we assume no negative self-loops), so no change occurs.
#    By the same argument dist[k][j] is unchanged. This means any "stale" read of
#    dist[i][k] or dist[k][j] during iteration k is guaranteed to be the correct
#    value from the previous iteration — so in-place is truly equivalent to using
#    a separate copy.)
#
# DIAGRAM (3 vertices example):
#
#   Initial dist (adjacency matrix + zeros on diagonal):
#   Vertices: 1, 2, 3.  Edges: 1→2 (w=3), 2→3 (w=2), 1→3 (w=10).
#
#        1    2    3
#   1 [  0,   3,  10]
#   2 [  ∞,   0,   2]
#   3 [  ∞,   ∞,   0]
#
#   k=1 (allow going through vertex 1):
#   No improvement (no shortcuts through vertex 1 exist here).
#
#   k=2 (allow going through vertex 2):
#   dist[1][3] = min(10, dist[1][2]+dist[2][3]) = min(10, 3+2) = 5.
#
#   k=3: no further improvement.
#
#   Final: dist[1][3] = 5. (Path: 1→2→3 with cost 3+2=5 < 10.)  ✓
#
# NEGATIVE CYCLE DETECTION:
#   After Floyd-Warshall: if dist[i][i] < 0 for any i, there's a negative cycle through i.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Negative cycle detection: run Bellman-Ford V times — any update in round V → cycle exists
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
