# 🚀 CONNECTIONS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Ch13 → Ch12 : Dijkstra is weighted BFS; same structure, add heap
# • Ch13 → Ch4  : Dijkstra uses min-heap (Ch4 heapq template)
# • Ch13 → Ch15 : Prim's MST uses same "pick minimum" greedy as Dijkstra
# • Ch13 → Ch16 : Shortest path on DAG = linear DP in topo order (faster than Dijkstra)
#
# ⛔ ANTI-PATTERNS (wrong algorithm for wrong situation)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   ✗ Dijkstra on a graph with negative edge weights → incorrect shortest paths.
#       FIX: use Bellman-Ford O(VE) or SPFA. Check for negative cycles.
#   ✗ BFS for weighted graph (non-unit weights) → distances wrong.
#       FIX: use Dijkstra. Use 0-1 BFS only when weights are exactly 0 or 1.
#   ✗ Floyd-Warshall on sparse graph with V=10^4 → O(V³)=10^12, instant TLE.
#       FIX: use Dijkstra from each source for sparse graphs.
#   ✗ Bellman-Ford without negative-cycle detection → infinite loop or wrong dist.
#       FIX: run V-th relaxation round; any change → negative cycle present.
# • Ch13 → Ch15 : MST uses same "pick minimum" greedy as Dijkstra (Prim's)
# • Ch13 → Ch16 : Shortest path on DAG uses topological DP (faster than Dijkstra)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Dijkstra fails on negative edges — use Bellman-Ford; Floyd-Warshall fails for n>500 — use per-source Dijkstra
#   - Edge weights ≥ 0 → Dijkstra; any negative → Bellman-Ford; all-pairs → Floyd
#   - "Shortest time/cost/distance" with weighted edges → shortest path chapter
#   - "Can we guarantee arrival if some edges fail" → check min-cut / connectivity
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Off-by-one in boundary conditions (l vs l-1, r vs r+1)
#   ✗ Not handling n=0 or n=1 edge case
#   ✗ Integer overflow: use // not / for integer division in Python
