# §1. ROOTED TREE STRUCTURE — FORMAL DEFINITIONS

# A ROOTED TREE is a tree with one designated vertex as ROOT.
# Once rooted, every edge has a natural direction: away from root.
#
# DEFINITIONS (for a rooted tree with root r):
#
#   PARENT of v (p(v)): the unique vertex adjacent to v on the path to root.
#                        (The root has no parent.)
# • CHILDREN of v: all vertices w where p(w) = v.
# • ANCESTOR of v: any vertex on the path from v to root (inclusive).
# • DESCENDANT of v: any vertex in the subtree rooted at v (inclusive).
# • SUBTREE of v: the induced subgraph of all descendants of v.
# • DEPTH(v): number of edges from root to v.
# • (depth(root) = 0) HEIGHT of v: longest path from v down to any leaf in subtree(v).
#   LEAF: vertex with no children.
#   SIZE of subtree(v): number of vertices in subtree(v).
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   LCS/Edit distance: dp[i][j] built from dp[i-1][j-1] when chars match, else from neighbors
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Root the tree (node 0 or 1)
#   2. DFS to compute depth, parent, subtree sizes
#   3. What DP state is needed on the subtree?
#   → Tree DP: define dp[v] = best value for subtree of v
#
