# 🧠 THE BIG PICTURE
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • A tree is a graph that is:  connected  AND  has no cycles.
# • With n vertices, it always has exactly n-1 edges.
# • Remove one edge → disconnected.
# • Add one edge → creates exactly one cycle.
#
# Trees are EVERYWHERE in CP. Most graph problems on trees have elegant O(n) solutions
# because there is EXACTLY ONE path between any two nodes.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🔥 TREE ANATOMY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Pick any node as ROOT (usually node 1). Now the tree has hierarchy:
#
#           root(1)
#           /      #        (2)       (3)        ← children of root
#       /   \        #     (4)   (5)      (6)      ← leaves (no children)
#
#   Parent    = node one step closer to root
#   Children  = nodes one step further from root
#   Leaf      = node with no children
# • Depth     = distance from root (root has depth 0) Height    = max depth in the
#       whole tree Subtree   = a node + all its descendants Ancestor  = any node
#       on the path up to root
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Segment tree: range queries + range updates both O(log n) via lazy propagation
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "range update, range query"
#   - "set all in range"
#   - "add to all in range"
#   - "range min/max with updates"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Pushing lazy tag down before accessing children — must propagate laziness before recursing
#   ✗ Wrong merge operation: tree[node] = merge(tree[2*node], tree[2*node+1]) — must match query type
#   ✗ Tree size must be 4*n not n — many nodes needed for internal nodes
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Root the tree (node 0 or 1)
#   2. DFS to compute depth, parent, subtree sizes
#   3. What DP state is needed on the subtree?
#   → Tree DP: define dp[v] = best value for subtree of v
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ⚡ THE GOLDEN RULE FOR TREE PROBLEMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Almost every tree problem is solved with DFS.
# • DFS on a tree naturally processes ALL children of a node before returning.
# • This "process subtree, then propagate result up" pattern solves:.
#   • Subtree sums, sizes, depths
#   • Tree diameter (longest path)
#   • Centroid decomposition
#   • Heavy-light decomposition
#   • LCA (Lowest Common Ancestor)
#
# 💡 KEY INSIGHT:
#   • FOR CP: Most tree problems are solved with DFS.
# Recursive DFS naturally processes subtrees before moving up.
# This "post-order" structure is perfect for aggregating subtree results.

# 14A. TREE DFS — Computing Subtree Information

sys.setrecursionlimit(300000)  # ~300K needed for tree/graph DFS on n=10^5
#
n_tree=int(input())
adj_tree=[[] for _ in range(n_tree+1)]
for _ in range(n_tree-1):
    u, v=map(int, input().split())
    adj_tree[u].append(v)
    adj_tree[v].append(u)
#
depth_tree=[0]*(n_tree+1)
parent_tree=[0]*(n_tree+1)
subtree_size=[1]*(n_tree+1)
tin_tree=[0]*(n_tree+1)
tout_tree=[0]*(n_tree+1)
timer_tree=[0]
#

# ── dfs_tree_full — inline ──
# Time: O(V) | Space: O(V)
stack=[(v,p,False)]
while stack:
    node,parent,post_order=stack.pop()
    if post_order:
        subtree_size[node]=1
        for num_bits,_ in adj[node]:
            if num_bits!=parent:
                subtree_size[node]+=subtree_size[num_bits]
    else:
        depth[node]=(depth[parent]+1 if parent!=-1 else 0)
        parent[node]=parent
        stack.append((node,parent,True))
        for num_bits,_ in adj[node]:
            if num_bits!=parent:
                stack.append((num_bits,node,False))
#
dfs_tree_full(1, 0)
