# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                                                          │
# │  IN THIS CHAPTER                                                         │
# │  • The MST problem: connect all nodes at minimum total edge cost         │
# │  • Cut Property: cheapest edge crossing any cut belongs to the MST       │
# │  • Kruskal's: sort edges globally, Union-Find prevents cycles            │
# │  • Prim's: heap-based greedy expansion — better for dense graphs         │
# │                                                                          │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 THE BIG PICTURE
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# A spanning tree connects ALL n vertices using exactly n-1 edges (no cycles).
# The MINIMUM Spanning Tree (MST) does this with the smallest possible total weight.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ⚡ THE REAL-WORLD PROBLEM
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • You have n cities.
# • You want to connect them all with roads.
# • Each possible road has a cost.
# • What's the cheapest way to connect all cities? Answer: find the MST of the
#       city graph
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 💡 THE KEY INSIGHT — Cut Property
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Split the vertices into ANY two groups S and (V minus S).
# The cheapest edge crossing this cut MUST be in the MST.
#
# • WHY? Suppose it wasn't.
# • The MST must have some other edge crossing this cut.
# • Swap it with the cheaper edge → we get a spanning tree with smaller weight.
# • Contradiction! So the cheapest crossing edge is always in the MST.
#
# This insight powers both Kruskal's (process edges globally cheapest first)
# and Prim's (always expand by cheapest edge from current component).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 💡 KRUSKAL vs PRIM  [GRAPH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Kruskal: sort all edges, add each if it doesn't create a cycle. Uses Union-Find.
#   Best for SPARSE graphs (m ≈ n).
#
# Prim: start anywhere, greedily add cheapest edge to expand. Uses a heap.
#   Best for DENSE graphs (m ≈ n²). Can be O(n²) without heap.
#
# A spanning tree of a connected graph is a SUBGRAPH that:
# • Contains all n vertices
# • Has exactly n-1 edges
# • Is a tree (connected, acyclic)
#
# Minimum Spanning Tree (MST) = spanning tree with minimum total edge weight.
# MST is UNIQUE if all edge weights are distinct.
#
# APPLICATION: Minimum cost to connect all cities, minimum cable network, clustering.

# 15A. UNION-FIND (Disjoint Set Union / DSU) — Nearly O(1) Per Operation

# WHAT: Manages disjoint sets. Supports:
# • find(x): returns the "representative" (root) of x's set. O(α(n)) ≈ O(1).
# • union(x,y): merges x's and y's sets. O(α(n)) ≈ O(1).
# α(n) = inverse Ackermann function. Grows EXTREMELY slowly. α(10^80) < 5.
# So for ALL practical purposes, O(α(n)) = O(1).
#
# TWO OPTIMIZATIONS:
# • PATH COMPRESSION: When finding root, make all nodes on path point DIRECTLY to
#       root
# • This flattens the tree for future queries.
# • UNION BY RANK/SIZE: Always attach smaller tree under larger.
#    This keeps trees shallow.
#
# VISUAL:
# Initially: {1},{2},{3},{4},{5}
# union(1,2): root[2]=1. Tree: 1←2
# union(3,4): root[4]=3. Tree: 3←4
# union(1,3): attach 3 under 1 (or vice versa by rank). Tree: 1←{2,3←4}
# find(4) with path compression: 4→3→1. Then parent[4]=1 (compressed). Tree: 1←{2,3,4}
#
dsu_parent=[]
dsu_rank=[]
dsu_size=[]
#

# ── dsu_init — inline ──
# Time: O(n) build | O(alpha(n)) per operation | Space: O(n)
dsu_parent=list(range(n+1))
dsu_rank=[0]*(n+1)
dsu_size=[1]*(n+1)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   DSU: O(α(n)) ≈ O(1) union/find with path compression + union by rank.
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "connected components"   - "union two groups"   - "are u,v connected?"
#   - Kruskal MST   - offline dynamic connectivity
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Forgetting path compression → O(log n) per find
#   ✗ Forgetting union by rank → degenerate chain → O(n) per find
#   ✗ Not calling find() to get actual roots before union
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. parent[x] = root of x's component.
#   2. Path compression flattens tree on find(). Union by rank keeps it shallow.
#
# CF TAGS: dsu, graphs, data structures  |  Rating: 1000–1600
#

# ── dsu_find — inline ──
while dsu_parent[x]!=x:
    dsu_parent[x]=dsu_parent[dsu_parent[x]]
    x=dsu_parent[x]
# x→root
#

# ── dsu_union — inline ──
# DRY RUN — DSU on 5 nodes, operations: union(1,2), union(3,4), union(2,4):
#   Initial: parent=[0,1,2,3,4,5], rank=[0,0,0,0,0,0]
#
#   union(1,2): root(1)=1, root(2)=2, rank equal -> parent[2]=1, rank[1]=1
#     parent=[0,1,1,3,4,5]
#
#   union(3,4): root(3)=3, root(4)=4, rank equal -> parent[4]=3, rank[3]=1
#     parent=[0,1,1,3,3,5]
#
#   union(2,4): root(2)=find(2)=1, root(4)=find(4)=3
#     rank[1]=1=rank[3] -> parent[3]=1, rank[1]=2
#     parent=[0,1,1,1,3,5]
#
#   Now: 1,2,3,4 all in one component. 5 alone.
#   Components: {1,2,3,4}, {5}
# DEBUG CHECKLIST — DSU Union-Find:
#   1. Always call find() before union to get actual roots.
#   2. Path compression modifies parent[] — don't cache find() results.
#   3. Union by rank: attach smaller-rank tree under larger-rank root.
#   4. Count components = number of nodes where dsu_parent[i] == i initially.
#   5. For weighted DSU (parity problems), track relation in separate array.
root_x=x
while dsu_parent[root_x]!=root_x:
    dsu_parent[root_x]=dsu_parent[dsu_parent[root_x]]
    root_x=dsu_parent[root_x]
root_y=y
while dsu_parent[root_y]!=root_y:
    dsu_parent[root_y]=dsu_parent[dsu_parent[root_y]]
    root_y=dsu_parent[root_y]
if root_x!=root_y:
    if dsu_rank[root_x]<dsu_rank[root_y]:
        root_x,root_y=root_y,root_x
    dsu_parent[root_y]=root_x
    dsu_size[root_x]+=dsu_size[root_y]
    if dsu_rank[root_x]==dsu_rank[root_y]:
        dsu_rank[root_x]+=1
#
# dsu_same(x,y): find roots of x and y; return root_x==root_y
# dsu_size_of(x): find root of x; return dsu_size[root]

# 15B. KRUSKAL'S ALGORITHM — O(E log E)

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                  ⚡ ALGORITHM                             │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# 1. Sort ALL edges by weight ascending.
# 2. For each edge (u,v,w) in order:
#    • If u and v are in DIFFERENT components: add to MST, merge.
#    • If SAME component: skip (would create cycle).
# 3. MST is complete when n-1 edges are added.
#
# WHY GREEDY IS CORRECT: Cut Property.
# • When we add edge (u,v,w): u and v are in different components.
# • The edge (u,v,w) is the minimum-weight edge crossing the cut (u's component vs
#       rest)
# • By the Cut Property, it must be in some MST.
#
# TIME: O(E log E) for sort + nearly O(E) for DSU operations.
#
n_kruskal, m_kruskal=map(int, input().split())
edges_kruskal=[]
for _ in range(m_kruskal):
    u, v, w=map(int, input().split())
    edges_kruskal.append((w, u, v))
edges_kruskal.sort()
#
dsu_init(n_kruskal)
mst_cost=0
mst_edges=0
for w, u, v in edges_kruskal:
    if dsu_union(u, v):
        mst_cost += w
        mst_edges += 1
    if mst_edges == n_kruskal-1:
        break
#
if mst_edges == n_kruskal-1:
    print(mst_cost)
else:
    print(-1)

# 15C. PRIM'S ALGORITHM — O((V+E) log V)

# ALGORITHM: Like Dijkstra, but track min edge weight to MST (not total distance).
# Start from vertex 1. At each step, add the cheapest edge connecting a new vertex.
# Uses min-heap for efficiency.
#
# WHEN TO PREFER OVER KRUSKAL:
# Prim is better for DENSE graphs (E = O(V²)).
# Kruskal is better for SPARSE graphs.
# In practice on CF: Kruskal is usually simpler to code → prefer Kruskal.
#
n_prim, m_prim=map(int, input().split())
adj_prim=[[] for _ in range(n_prim+1)]
for _ in range(m_prim):
    u, v, w=map(int, input().split())
    adj_prim[u].append((w, v))
    adj_prim[v].append((w, u))
#
INF=float('inf')
key=[INF]*(n_prim+1)
key[1]=0
in_mst=[False]*(n_prim+1)
h_prim=[(0, 1)]
mst_total=0
#
while h_prim:
    w, v=heappop(h_prim)
    if in_mst[v]:
        continue
    in_mst[v]=True
    mst_total += w
    for cw, u in adj_prim[v]:
        if not in_mst[u] and cw < key[u]:
            key[u]=cw
            heappush(h_prim, (cw, u))
print(mst_total)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Kruskal: sort edges by weight, add edge if it connects different components → MST
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimum spanning tree"
#   - "MST"
#   - "connect all nodes minimum cost"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Sorting descending for maximum spanning tree is valid; ascending for minimum
#   ✗ Not using Union-Find → O(E²) cycle checking instead of O(E α(V))
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║            CHAPTER 15 ENHANCEMENT  —  ELITE TRAINING ADDENDUM            ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Build adjacency list from input
#   2. Which traversal: BFS (shortest path) or DFS (structure)?
#   3. What to compute during traversal?
#   → Mark visited on enqueue (BFS) or entry (DFS)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 MENTAL MODELS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MST (Minimum Spanning Tree):
# • "Connect all n nodes with exactly n-1 edges, minimizing total weight." Kruskal
#       → "Sort edges, add if no cycle (greedy + DSU)" Prim    → "Grow MST from
#       any node, always adding cheapest edge out (heap)"
#
# • Cut property: The minimum weight edge crossing any cut is in EVERY MST.
# • Cycle property: The maximum weight edge in any cycle is in NO MST.
# • These two properties PROVE why both Kruskal and Prim are correct.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   MST cut property: minimum-weight edge crossing any cut is in some MST (proves Kruskal/Prim)
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Sort edges by weight (Kruskal) or use a min-heap from the source (Prim)
#   2. Use Union-Find to check and merge components in O(α(n)) per edge (Kruskal)
#   3. Add an edge only if it connects two different components; stop at n-1 edges
#   → Kruskal = sort + union-find; Prim = Dijkstra-shaped but minimises edge weight
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "connect all nodes at minimum cost"          → MST (Kruskal)
#
#   ► "make graph connected, minimize max edge"    → MST (minimax path = MST edge)
#
#   ► "dynamic connectivity" (add/remove edges)   → offline DSU or Link-Cut Tree
#
#   ► "are u and v in same component?"            → DSU find(u) == find(v)
#
#   ► "after some merges, how many components?"   → DSU.components counter
#
#   ► "second MST"                                → find replacement edge for each MST edge

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
