#
# §1. WHY DIRECTED GRAPHS NEED SPECIAL TREATMENT

# • In an undirected graph, an edge {u,v} means "u and v can communicate freely."
#       In a directed graph, edge (u->v) means "u can send to v, but v cannot send
#       back to u unless there is a separate edge (v→u)."
#
# This asymmetry breaks many undirected-graph assumptions:
#   • "Reachable from u" ≠ "u is reachable from."
#   • Connected components split into weakly and strongly connected.
#   • Cycles now have direction — you can have 1→2→3→1 but NOT 1→2→3 with 1←2.
#   • DFS now produces 4 edge types instead of 2 (see §2).
#
# • INTUITION: Think of directed graphs as one-way streets.
# • BFS/DFS from a city tells you where you CAN drive to, not where you can receive deliveries from.
# • These are completely different questions.

# §2. DAG — DIRECTED ACYCLIC GRAPH: THE MOST IMPORTANT SPECIAL CASE

# A DAG has no directed cycles. This single property makes DAGs extremely
# powerful because it guarantees a topological ordering exists.
#
# REAL-WORLD DAGS:
#   • Course prerequisites (can't take Advanced Algorithms before Algorithms)
#   • Build systems (compile A before B before C)
#   • Git commit history (each commit points to its parents)
#   • Recipe dependencies (cook sauce before adding to pasta)
#   • DP state transitions (dp[i] always depends on smaller i)
#
# 🔍 PATTERN RECOGNITION — DAG signals in problem statements:
#   "Task A must complete before task B"
#   "Process in valid order"
# • "Count paths from source to destination" "Longest/shortest path in a
#       dependency graph" "All dp transitions go in one direction"

# §3. TOPOLOGICAL SORT — THE COMPLETE PICTURE

# IN SIMPLE TERMS: A topological ordering of a DAG is a linear arrangement of
# all vertices such that for every directed edge u->v, vertex u appears
# before vertex v in the arrangement.
#
# KEY FACTS:
#   • Every DAG has AT LEAST ONE topological ordering.
#   • If the DAG has a Hamiltonian path (visits every node once), then
#     the topological ordering is UNIQUE.
#   • If multiple valid orderings exist, the problem may ask for
#     lexicographically smallest → use min-heap instead of regular queue.
#   • If any cycle exists, topological sort is IMPOSSIBLE.
#     This is a cycle detection method for directed graphs!
#
# TWO ALGORITHMS — WHEN TO USE WHICH:
#
#   KAHN'S (BFS-based):
#   ✓ Detects cycles naturally (processed < n vertices → cycle exists)
#   ✓ Easier to get lexicographically smallest ordering (use min-heap)
#   ✓ More intuitive for most people
#   ✓ Better for problems needing "process in dependency order"
#
#   DFS-based (postorder reverse):
#   ✓ Easier to implement recursively
#   ✓ Naturally pairs with SCC algorithms (Tarjan's uses DFS)
#   ✓ Better when you need DFS timestamps anyway
#
# DIAGRAM — Kahn's Algorithm Step by Step:
#
#   Graph: 5→2, 5→0, 4→0, 4→1, 2→3, 3→1
#
#   in-degree: {0:2, 1:2, 2:1, 3:1, 4:0, 5:0}
#
#   Step 1: Queue = [4, 5] (in-degree 0)
#   Step 2: Process 4 → decrease in-deg of 0,1 → {0:1, 1:1}
#            Queue = [5]
#   Step 3: Process 5 → decrease in-deg of 2,0 → {0:0, 2:0}
#            Queue = [0, 2]
# • Step 4: Process 0 → no outgoing.
# • Queue = [2] Step 5: Process 2 → decrease in-deg of 3 → {3:0}. Queue = [3] Step
#       6: Process 3 → decrease in-deg of 1 → {1:0}. Queue = [1]
#   Step 7: Process 1 → done.
#
#   Result: [4, 5, 0, 2, 3, 1]  ← valid topological order ✓

# §4. DAG DP — THE MOST POWERFUL APPLICATION

# • Processing vertices in topological order enables DP on DAGs.
# • For every edge u->v: when we process v, ALL predecessors u are already done.
# • This is exactly the DP ordering requirement!.
#
# PATTERN: dp[v] = some_function(dp[u] for all u with edge u->v)
#
# COMMON DAG DP PROBLEMS:
#
#   1. LONGEST PATH IN DAG:
#      dp[v] = 1 + max(dp[u] for u->v)
#      O(V+E). Cannot use Dijkstra (negative-style relaxation needed).
#
#   2. COUNT PATHS FROM S TO T:
#      dp[v] = sum(dp[u] for u->v), dp[source] = 1
#      O(V+E).
#
#   3. SHORTEST PATH IN DAG (any weights, including negative):
#      dp[v] = min(dp[u] + w(u,v) for u->v)
#      O(V+E). BEATS Dijkstra for DAGs because no priority queue needed!
#
# DIAGRAM — DAG DP for Longest Path:
#
#   DAG:  1→2 (w=3), 1→3 (w=2), 2→4 (w=1), 3→4 (w=5)
#
#   Topo order: [1, 2, 3, 4]
#
#   dp[1] = 0 (start)
#   dp[2] = dp[1] + 3 = 3
#   dp[3] = dp[1] + 2 = 2
#   dp[4] = max(dp[2]+1, dp[3]+5) = max(4, 7) = 7
#
#   Longest path = 7  (via 1→3→4: 2+5=7)  ✓

# §5. DFS-BASED TOPOLOGICAL SORT — THE POSTORDER TRICK

# • DFS visits all descendants of a vertex before marking it "done." When we
#       finish processing vertex v (all its descendants done), we push v to a
#       stack
# • Reversing this stack gives topological order.
#
# WHY POSTORDER?
# When v is pushed, all vertices reachable from v are already pushed.
# So v comes BEFORE all its successors in the reversed stack. ✓
#
#   def dfs_topo(v, adj, visited, stack):
#       visited[v] = True
#       for u in adj[v]:
#           if not visited[u]:
#               dfs_topo(u, adj, visited, stack)
#       stack.append(v)   ← pushed AFTER all descendants
#
#   for v in range(n):
#       if not visited[v]: dfs_topo(v, adj, visited, stack)
#   topo_order = stack[::-1]  ← reverse = topological order

# §6. DIRECTED CYCLE DETECTION — THREE-COLOR DFS

# • For undirected graphs: any non-tree edge is a back edge → cycle.
# • For directed graphs: only BACK EDGES (to an ancestor in current DFS path) indicate cycles.
# • Forward/cross edges do NOT.
#
# THREE-COLOR DFS:
#   WHITE (0): unvisited
#   GRAY  (1): in current DFS path (currently being explored)
#   BLACK (2): fully finished
#
# Back edge: encountering a GRAY vertex → cycle in directed graph.
# Cross edge: encountering a BLACK vertex → NOT a cycle.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                   📊 DIAGRAM                              │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

#   Graph: 1→2→3→1 (cycle), 2→4 (no cycle from 4)
#
#   DFS from 1:
#   Visit 1 (GRAY). Visit 2 (GRAY). Visit 3 (GRAY).
#   3→1: 1 is GRAY → BACK EDGE → CYCLE DETECTED!
#
#   Graph: 1→2→4, 1→3→4 (no cycle)
#
#   DFS from 1:
#   Visit 1 (GRAY). Visit 2 (GRAY). Visit 4 (GRAY→BLACK). 2 BLACK.
#   Visit 3 (GRAY). 3→4: 4 is BLACK → CROSS EDGE → no cycle. 3 BLACK. 1 BLACK.
#   No cycle detected. ✓

# §7. COMPETITIVE PROGRAMMING PATTERNS FOR DIRECTED GRAPHS

# PATTERN 1: "Minimum/Maximum steps to reach all nodes"
#   → Topological sort + BFS/DP
#
# PATTERN 2: "Is there a valid ordering?"
#   → Topological sort; if result has n nodes → yes, else → cycle exists
#
# PATTERN 3: "Lexicographically smallest topological order"
#   → Kahn's with min-heap (priority queue) instead of regular queue
#
# PATTERN 4: "Number of paths in a directed graph"
#   → Check for cycles. If DAG → topological DP. If cycles → infinite paths!
#
# • PATTERN 5: "Shortest path in DAG with negative weights" → Topological sort +
#       relaxation (no Dijkstra needed!) → O(V+E), handles negative weights,
#       faster than Bellman-Ford O(VE)
#
# ⚠ COMMON MISTAKE:
# • Using Dijkstra for directed graphs with negative weights → WRONG.
# • Dijkstra requires non-negative weights.
# • Use Bellman-Ford or DAG-DP.
# • Applying topological sort to a graph with cycles → undefined behavior.
# • Always check: if processed_count < n → cycle exists.
# • Treating cross edges in directed DFS as cycles → WRONG.
# • Only back edges (to GRAY vertices) indicate cycles.
# • Forgetting that topological order is not unique (multiple valid orderings).
# • If problem asks for "the" order, clarify if any valid order is accepted.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 💡 PRO TIPS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# 🧠 THE BIG PICTURE
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Directed graphs have one-way edges: u → v means you can go FROM u TO v, but
# not necessarily the other way. This asymmetry creates rich structure.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🎯 DAG (Directed ACYCLIC Graph)  [GRAPH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# A directed graph with NO cycles. No way to start at a node and return to it.
#
# Why DAGs are special:
#   • They have a TOPOLOGICAL ORDER — a ranking where all edges go "left to right"
#   • DP on DAGs is always valid and efficient
#   • Course prerequisites, recipe steps, build systems are all DAGs
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Graph = vertices + edges; representation: adjacency list for sparse, matrix for dense
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "nodes and edges"
#   - "connected"
#   - "network"
#   - "path from"
#   - "reachable"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Adjacency matrix for sparse graph → O(V²) space → MLE for V=10^5
#   ✗ Forgetting to add both directions for undirected graph: adj[u].append(v); adj[v].append(u)
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Build adjacency list from input
#   2. Which traversal: BFS (shortest path) or DFS (structure)?
#   3. What to compute during traversal?
#   → Mark visited on enqueue (BFS) or entry (DFS)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🚀 TOPOLOGICAL SORT — THE MOST USEFUL DAG TOOL  [GRAPH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# A topological order lists ALL vertices such that for every edge u->v,
# u appears BEFORE v in the list.
#
# ANALOGY: You have 5 courses to pass (A, B, C, D, E) with prerequisites:
# • B requires A.
# • C requires A.
# • D requires B and C.
# • E requires D.
# • Topological order: A → B → C → D → E  (or A → C → B → D → E).
# • This tells you the order to take courses with NO unsatisfied prerequisites.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🔥 KAHN'S ALGORITHM (BFS-based)  [GRAPH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Start with all nodes that have NO prerequisites (in-degree = 0).
# • Process one, remove its outgoing edges, add newly zero-in-degree nodes to queue.
# • If you process all n nodes → valid DAG.
# • If stuck → there's a cycle.
#
# TOPOLOGICAL ORDER: ordering of vertices where for every edge u->v, u comes before v.
# Valid if and only if the graph is a DAG.

# 16A. KAHN'S ALGORITHM — BFS-Based Topological Sort

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                  ⚡ ALGORITHM                             │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# 1. Compute in-degree (incoming edges) for each vertex.
# 2. Add all vertices with in-degree 0 to queue.
# 3. While queue not empty:
# • Add to topological order.
# • For each v→u: decrement in-degree[u]. If in-degree[u]=0: add to queue.
# • If order has n vertices: valid DAG.
# • Else: cycle exists.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY IS THIS CORRECT? If in-degree is 0, all its prerequisites are done. We can process it.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# When we process v, all v's successors have one fewer prerequisite. ✓
#
# CYCLE DETECTION: If at the end, some vertices are unprocessed, they form a cycle
# (each depends on something in the cycle — in-degree never reaches 0).
#
n_topo, m_topo=map(int, input().split())
adj_topo=[[] for _ in range(n_topo+1)]
indeg_topo=[0]*(n_topo+1)
for _ in range(m_topo):
    u, v=map(int, input().split())
    adj_topo[u].append(v)
    indeg_topo[v] += 1
#
q_topo=deque(v for v in range(1, n_topo+1) if indeg_topo[v] == 0)
topo_order=[]
while q_topo:
    v=q_topo.popleft()
    topo_order.append(v)
    for u in adj_topo[v]:
        indeg_topo[u] -= 1
        if indeg_topo[u] == 0:
            q_topo.append(u)
#
if len(topo_order) == n_topo:
    print(*topo_order)
else:
    print("CYCLE DETECTED")

# 16B. DAG DP — Longest Path in a DAG

# DP on DAG: process vertices in topological order.
# Each vertex uses results from its predecessors (already computed).
#
# LONGEST PATH: dp[v] = length of longest path ENDING at v.
# dp[v] = 1 + max(dp[u]) for all u → v.
# Process in topological order to ensure dp[u] is computed before dp[v].
#
# This generalizes to many problems: max/min cost path, count paths, etc.
#
dp_dag=[1]*(n_topo+1)
for v in topo_order:
    for u in adj_topo[v]:
        dp_dag[u]=max(dp_dag[u], dp_dag[v]+1)
print(max(dp_dag[1:n_topo+1]))
#
# COUNT paths from 1 to n in DAG (modular):
#
#
count_dp=[0]*(n_topo+1)
count_dp[1]=1
for v in topo_order:
    for u in adj_topo[v]:
        count_dp[u]=(count_dp[u]+count_dp[v])%MOD

# 16C. CYCLE DETECTION IN DIRECTED GRAPH — DFS with Colors

# Three-color DFS:
# WHITE (0): unvisited.
# GRAY (1): currently in DFS stack (processing, not done).
# BLACK (2): fully processed.
#
# A BACK EDGE (edge to a GRAY vertex) indicates a cycle.
# We detect cycles when we encounter a GRAY vertex during DFS.
#
col=[0]*(n_topo+1)
has_cycle=[False]

# ── dfs_cycle_detect — inline ──
color=[0]*(n+1)
has_cycle=False
for start in range(1,n+1):
    if color[start]!=0:
        continue
    cycle_stk=[(start,False)]
    while cycle_stk and not has_cycle:
        v,leaving=cycle_stk.pop()
        if leaving:
            color[v]=2
        else:
            if color[v]==1:
                has_cycle=True
            break
            if color[v]==2:
                continue
            color[v]=1
            cycle_stk.append((v,True))
            for u,_ in adj[v]:
                if color[u]!=2:
                    cycle_stk.append((u,False))
# result→_has_cycle
#
for v in range(1, n_topo+1):
    if col[v] == 0:
        dfs_cycle_detect(v)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   DAG cycle detection: 3-colour DFS — white→unvisited, grey→in-stack, black→done
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "prove BFS shortest"
#   - "why not DFS"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ DFS can reach a node via a long winding path before finding the short direct path
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Can I write a check(x) function: "is x achievable?"
#   2. Is check(x) monotone? (if x works, x+1 works too?)
#   → Yes → binary search on x, call check(mid) inside
#
