# 🧠 MENTAL MODEL
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • "Topological Sort = linearize a partial order." DAG DP = DP where state
#       transitions follow topo order (no future depends on past)
# • Cycle detection in directed graphs = 3-color DFS (white → gray → black).
# • Mental check: if a problem has dependencies, ordering, or scheduling → think DAG.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Topological order = process nodes only after all their dependencies
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Does the graph have cycles? → SCC decomposition (Tarjan or Kosaraju) first
#   2. Is it a DAG? → Topological sort with Kahn's BFS or DFS post-order
#   3. After condensing SCCs into a DAG, apply DP on the condensation
#   → DAGs → topo sort; cyclic → SCCs first, condense to DAG, then DP
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "prerequisites", "dependencies", "must come before"     → topological sort
#
#   ► "longest path in a graph with no cycles"                → DAG DP
#
#   ► "count paths from source to sink"                       → DAG DP (count_dp)
#
#   ► "is there a cycle in a directed graph?"                 → 3-color DFS or Kahn's
#
#   ► "task scheduling with deadlines"                        → topo sort + greedy
#
#   ► "reachability queries on DAG"                           → topo order + DP
#
#   ► "minimum/maximum cost to reach all nodes"               → DAG shortest/longest path

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Using Dijkstra on a DAG for shortest/longest path.
#       Dijkstra is O((V+E) log V) and doesn't leverage DAG structure.
#
#   ✓  Topological sort + DP: O(V+E), cleaner, handles negative weights too.
#
#   ✗  Recursive DFS for topo sort with large n (Python recursion limit ~1000).
#       Will crash on chains of length > 1000.
#
#   ✓  Kahn's BFS-based algorithm — iterative, no recursion limit issues.
#
#   ✗  Running topo sort on a graph that might have cycles (crashes or wrong).
#
#   ✓  Always check: if len(topo_order) < n → cycle exists. Handle gracefully.
#
#   ✗  Forgetting that topo sort is NOT unique — multiple valid orderings exist.
#       If a problem requires a specific one, use a priority queue (lexicographic).
#
#   ✓  Replace deque with heapq in Kahn's to get lexicographically smallest order.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Topological sort: Kahn's BFS gives lex-smallest; DFS reverse-finish gives any valid order
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Does the graph have cycles? → SCC decomposition (Tarjan or Kosaraju) first
#   2. Is it a DAG? → Topological sort with Kahn's BFS or DFS post-order
#   3. After condensing SCCs into a DAG, apply DP on the condensation
#   → DAGs → topo sort; cyclic → SCCs first, condense to DAG, then DP
#
