# PRE-CHAPTER 18 — TREE QUERIES: HLD, CENTROID, SMALL-TO-LARGE

# §1. HEAVY-LIGHT DECOMPOSITION (HLD) — THE CORE IDEA

# • PROBLEM: Answer range queries (sum, max, update) on tree paths.
# • A path from u to v passes through their LCA.
# • On a linear array, range queries are easy (segment tree).
# • But tree paths are not contiguous.
#
# • HLD INSIGHT: Decompose the tree into "heavy chains" so that any
#   root-to-leaf path passes through at most O(log n) chains.
# • Map chains to contiguous array positions.
# • Now path queries become O(log n) segment tree range queries.
#
# HEAVY CHILD: For each node v, the child with the LARGEST subtree is "heavy."
#   All other children are "light."
#   Heavy edge = edge to heavy child. Light edge = all others.
#
# HEAVY CHAIN: Maximal path of consecutive heavy edges.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ KEY INSIGHT: Any path from root to a leaf in an HLD tree crosses at most O(log n)  [TREE]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# "light" edges (edges where you switch to a smaller subtree).
# WHY: Each light edge means the subtree at least doubles in size. Since the tree
#   has at most n nodes, you can double at most log(n) times.. So ≤ log n light edges. ✓
#
# Since a path u->v goes through LCA and has ≤ 2*log(n) light edges,
# it spans ≤ 2*log(n) + 1 chains → ≤ O(log n) segment tree queries.

# §2. CENTROID DECOMPOSITION — DIVIDE AND CONQUER ON TREES

# CENTROID of a tree: a node whose removal leaves all components of size ≤ n/2.
#   Every tree has a centroid (and at most 2). Finding it: O(n).
#
# CENTROID DECOMPOSITION: Build a tree of centroids.
#   1. Find centroid c of the current tree.
#   2. Process all paths THROUGH c.
#   3. Remove c and recurse on each component.
#
# • Depth of centroid decomposition tree: O(log n).
# • Every pair of nodes (u, v) has their path processed exactly once —
#   at the centroid of the minimal subtree containing both.
#
# USED FOR: Counting/optimizing paths by decomposing into "paths through centroid."
# Classic: "Count pairs of nodes with distance exactly k."

# §3. SMALL-TO-LARGE MERGING (DSU ON TREE)

# "DSU on tree" or "small-to-large": For each node, maintain a set of values
# in its subtree. Merge children's sets into the parent.
#
# KEY: Always merge the SMALLER set into the LARGER set.
# Total work: each element moves at most O(log n) times (each merge at least doubles).
# Total time: O(n log n).
#
# USED FOR: Subtree queries involving distinct values, "k-th distinct element in subtree."
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   cross(O,A,B) = (A-O)×(B-O) > 0: left turn; = 0: collinear; < 0: right turn
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "range update, range query"
#   - "set all in range"
#   - "add to all in range"
#   - "range min/max with updates"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Pushing lazy tag down before accessing children — must propagate laziness before recursing
#   ✗ Wrong merge operation: tree[node] = merge(tree[2*node], tree[2*node+1]) — must match query type
#   ✗ Tree size must be 4*n not n — many nodes needed for internal nodes
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Can I write a check(x) function: "is x achievable?"
#   2. Is check(x) monotone? (if x works, x+1 works too?)
#   → Yes → binary search on x, call check(mid) inside
