# 🧠 MENTAL MODEL
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   "HLD = flatten a tree into an array to use segment tree on paths."
# • Heavy-Light Decomposition: every root-to-leaf path has O(log n) heavy chains.
# • So O(log n) segment tree queries per path → O(log² n) per path query.
# • Centroid Decomp: split tree at centroid → every path passes through at most.
#   O(log n) centroids. Ideal for distance/path counting problems.
#   Small-to-Large: merging smaller set INTO larger → O(n log n) total merges.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "update/query on path u->v in tree"                      → HLD + segment tree
#
#   ► "update/query on subtree"                               → Euler tour + segment tree
#
#   ► "count pairs (u,v) with dist(u,v) = k"                  → centroid decomposition
#
#   ► "merge sets/multisets up the tree"                      → small-to-large (DSU on tree)
#
#   ► "most frequent color in subtree"                        → DSU on tree (small-to-large)
#
#   ► "weighted path queries with updates"                    → HLD
#
#   ► "paths passing through a specific node"                 → centroid decomposition

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Answering tree path queries with O(n) per query (walk the path).
#       For q queries: O(nq) = O(n²) → TLE for n,q = 10^5.
#
#   ✓  HLD + Segment Tree: O((n+q) log² n). Worth the implementation complexity.
#
#   ✗  Using centroid decomp for subtree queries.
#       Centroid is for PATH queries. Subtree → Euler tour.
#
#   ✓  Match the technique to the query type:
#       PATH queries → HLD or centroid decomp
#       SUBTREE queries → Euler tour (DFS in/out times)
#
#   ✗  Small-to-Large without swapping (always merge into first set regardless of size).
#       O(n²) worst case (degenerate chain).
#
#   ✓  ALWAYS merge the smaller into the larger. Guarantees O(n log n) total.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Small-to-large: always merge smaller set into larger — each element changes group at most log n times
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Path query u->v? → HLD decomposes into O(log n) chains, each queried with segtree
#   2. Subtree query? → Euler-tour flattens tree to array; segtree handles range queries
#   3. 'Paths through a common point'? → Centroid decomposition on centroid tree
#   → HLD for path queries; Euler tour for subtree; centroid for path counting
#
