# §1. FLOW NETWORKS

# A flow network G=(V,E) has:
#   • Source s, sink t
#   • Capacity c(u,v) ≥ 0 on each edge
#   • Flow f(u,v) subject to:
#       Capacity: f(u,v) ≤ c(u,v)
#       Skew symmetry: f(u,v) = -f(v,u)
#       Conservation: for all v ≠ s,t: sum of outflow = sum of inflow
#
# Value of flow = net flow out of source = net flow into sink.
#
# RESIDUAL GRAPH: G_f where residual capacity r(u,v) = c(u,v) - f(u,v).
#   We can "undo" flow on edge (u,v) by sending flow on (v,u) in residual graph.
#
# AUGMENTING PATH: Any s→t path in residual graph with positive capacity.
#   Sending flow along it increases total flow.
#
# MAX-FLOW MIN-CUT THEOREM (Ford-Fulkerson):
#   max flow = min cut
# where a CUT (S, T) partitions V into s∈S, t∈T and its CAPACITY =
# sum of capacities of edges from S to T.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ PROOF SKETCH:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • When no augmenting path exists, define S = nodes reachable from s in residual.
# • The cut (S,T) has capacity = current flow value
#   (all S→T edges are saturated, all T→S edges carry no flow).
# • So max flow = capacity of this cut.

# §2. WHY DINIC'S BEATS EDMONDS-KARP — FULL DERIVATION

# EDMONDS-KARP: O(VE²)
# • Edmonds-Karp sends one BFS shortest augmenting path at a time.
# • Each such path is found in O(E).
# • After augmentation, the BFS distance from s to t never decreases
#   (it is monotonically non-decreasing across augmentations).
# • Since distances can be at most V-1, there are at most O(V) "distance levels."
#   Within each level, at most O(E) augmentations occur (because at least one
#   edge gets saturated per augmentation).
# can't be used again until the distance increases). Total: O(V×E) phases,
# O(E) per phase → O(VE²). Slow for dense graphs.
#
# THE CORE PROBLEM: One augmenting path per BFS call wastes the level graph
# structure. Most of it gets rebuilt identically for the next path.
#
# • DINIC'S KEY INSIGHT: Within one BFS phase, exhaustively send flow along
#   ALL shortest paths simultaneously, producing a BLOCKING FLOW.
# • Then the distance strictly increases, so we need at most O(V) total BFS phases.
#
# • LEVEL GRAPH L_f: Subgraph of the residual graph G_f containing only edges
#   (u, v) where level[v] = level[u] + 1 (BFS-layered).
# • Every s→t path in L_f has exactly the same length = BFS distance from s to t.
#
# BLOCKING FLOW IN L_f — O(VE) via DFS with current-edge pointer:
#   Maintain a "current edge" pointer iter[v] for each node v.
#   • ADVANCE: if the current edge (v → w) has positive capacity and
#     level[w] = level[v]+1, move to w.
#   • AUGMENT: when t is reached, push flow back along the path. Saturated
#     edges are implicitly removed (capacity drops to 0).
#   • RETREAT: if no current edge works from v (all saturated or wrong level),
#     increment iter[v] and backtrack to parent. Each edge is visited at most
#     twice (once to advance, once to retreat after saturation) → O(E) total.
#   • PATH TRACE: O(V) per augmentation (path length ≤ V). At most O(E)
#     augmentations per phase (each saturates ≥ 1 edge) → O(VE) per phase.
#
# TOTAL PHASES BOUND — at most V-1:
# • After each blocking flow, every s→t path in L_f has at least one saturated edge.
# • In the NEW residual graph G_f', the shortest s→t path must be STRICTLY LONGER than before.
# • Reason: any path in G_f' that reuses a non-saturated forward edge is still
#   a valid path in the old L_f of the same length.
# • Any path in G_f' using a new reverse edge (that.
# • didn't exist before) must travel "backward" relative to BFS levels, adding ≥ 2
#       to the path length
# • So shortest path grows by ≥ 1 each phase.
# • Since shortest path ≤ V-1, we have at most V-1 phases.
#
# TOTAL: O(V-1) phases × O(VE) per phase = O(V²E). ✓
#
# UNIT-CAPACITY SPECIAL CASE → O(E√V):
#   For unit-capacity graphs (e.g., bipartite matching), the blocking flow
#   in each phase consists of edge-disjoint augmenting paths. After √V phases,
# • the remaining max flow value F' satisfies: each augmenting path has length > √V, so F' ≤ V / √V = √V.
# • These remaining F' ≤ √V augmentations each cost O(E) to find → O(E√V) remaining work.
# • Before the cutoff: √V phases × O(E) per phase = O(E√V).
# • Total: O(E√V).
# • This is the Hopcroft-Karp bound.

# §3. MIN-COST MAX-FLOW — BRIEF ORIENTATION

# (Full MCMF implementation is in Bonus Chapter I. This pointer keeps you
# oriented when the Chapter 19 TOC mentions it.)
#
# PROBLEM: Each directed edge has a cost per unit of flow. Find the max flow
# with minimum total cost. Applications: optimal assignment problems, cheapest
# routing, resource allocation.
#
# • ALGORITHM (Successive Shortest Paths): 1.
# • Find the minimum-cost augmenting path using Bellman-Ford or SPFA (Dijkstra
#       requires Johnson's reweighting via potentials to handle negative-cost
#       edges that arise from reverse edges in the residual graph)
# • Augment along this path.
# • The path cost gives the "price" of this unit.
# • Repeat until no augmenting path exists.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# JOHNSON'S POTENTIAL-BASED REWEIGHTING (enabling Dijkstra on negative edges)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# PROBLEM: Dijkstra requires non-negative edge weights. Negative edges (e.g. from
#          reverse arcs in residual graphs, or genuinely negative-cost arcs) break it.
#
# JOHNSON'S TRICK:
#   1. Add a virtual node s₀ with zero-cost edges to every vertex. Run Bellman-Ford
#      (or SPFA) from s₀ to compute potential h[v] = shortest-path distance to v.
#   2. Reweight each edge (u->v, cost c) as:  w'(u,v) = c + h[u] - h[v]
#      By the triangle inequality h[v] ≤ h[u] + c, so w'(u,v) ≥ 0. ✓
#   3. Run Dijkstra on the reweighted graph. The shortest path in the reweighted
#      graph from s to t has length d'. The true shortest path length is:
#          d_true = d' + h[t] - h[s]
#   4. After each augmentation in MCMF, update potentials:
#          h_new[v] = h[v] + d'[v]   (where d' comes from the Dijkstra just run)
#      This keeps potentials consistent for the next iteration without re-running
#      Bellman-Ford — only one Bellman-Ford call total, then Dijkstra each round.
#
# WHY IT WORKS: w'(u,v) = c(u,v) + h[u] - h[v] is a telescoping transformation.
#   Any path u→...→v has reweighted cost = original cost + h[u] - h[v], so
#   relative ordering of paths is preserved. Shortest path is the same path; only
#   the absolute distances change.
#
# BENEFIT FOR MCMF: O(E log V) per augmentation instead of O(VE). For large flows
#   this can be the difference between AC and TLE.
#
# KEY DIFFERENCE from pure max flow:
#   Max flow: any augmenting path in the residual graph.
#   MCMF: only the SHORTEST-COST path, to maintain cumulative optimality.
#
# WHY SUCCESSIVE SHORTEST PATHS IS OPTIMAL:
# • Each augmentation saturates the cheapest available "unit" of flow first.
# • By induction, the total cost is minimized because we never "overpay" for an
#   earlier unit when a cheaper option would have served the later unit better —
#   exchanging augmentations would only increase cost.
#
# → See Bonus Chapter I for the full MCMF class.

# §4. MAX-FLOW = MAX BIPARTITE MATCHING

# Create source s, sink t.
# • For each left node L: add edge s→L capacity
# • For each right node R: add edge R→t capacity
# • For each edge L-R: add edge L→R capacity 1.
# Max flow = maximum matching.
#
# König's theorem: In bipartite graphs, max matching = min vertex cover.
#
