# 💡 PRE-CHAPTER 20 — COMPUTATIONAL GEOMETRY: THEORY  [GEO]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# §1. THE CROSS PRODUCT — THE FUNDAMENTAL TOOL

# Cross product of 2D vectors A=(ax,ay) and B=(bx,by):
#   A × B = ax*by - ay*bx
#
# GEOMETRIC MEANING:
#   |A × B| = |A||B|sin(θ) = area of parallelogram spanned by A and B
#   Sign: positive if B is counterclockwise from A, negative if clockwise.
#
# CRITICAL APPLICATIONS:
# • TURN DIRECTION: Given points P, Q, R in order: cross((Q-P), (R-P)) > 0 → left
#       turn (counterclockwise) cross((Q-P), (R-P)) < 0 → right turn (clockwise)
#    cross = 0 → collinear
#
# 2. POLYGON AREA: Shoelace formula.
#    Area = |sum over edges of (x_i * y_{i+1} - x_{i+1} * y_i)| / 2
#
# 3. POINT IN TRIANGLE: Check that point is on same side of all 3 edges.
#
# 4. SEGMENT INTERSECTION: Two segments intersect if and only if they straddle each other.
#
# INTEGER VS FLOAT ARITHMETIC:
# • Cross products with integer coordinates produce EXACT integer results.
# • Python's arbitrary-precision integers handle coordinates up to 10^9 without
#   overflow: cross product can be up to 2 × (10^9)² = 2 × 10^18, which fits in
#   a 64-bit int (Java/C++) or Python int (unlimited).
# • Float arithmetic accumulates errors — use integers wherever possible.
# • Float is acceptable only when computing distances or angles explicitly.

# §2. CONVEX HULL — CORRECTNESS OF ANDREW'S MONOTONE CHAIN

# CONVEX HULL = smallest convex polygon containing all points.
#
# ANDREW'S MONOTONE CHAIN:
# • Sort points by x-coordinate, breaking ties by y.
# • Build LOWER hull left to right: process each point p and pop the top of the
#       stack while the last two stack points + p form a non-left turn
# • Build UPPER hull right to left: same procedure on reversed point order.
# • Concatenate (excluding duplicated endpoints).
#
# • INVARIANT WHY IT WORKS: The stack always forms a convex chain pointing rightward.
# • When we add point p and find a clockwise (right) turn with the top two points
#   A, B, p — the middle point B lies to the right of line A→p.
# • Since the hull wraps counterclockwise, B is strictly INSIDE the hull.
# • It can never contribute to the convex boundary, so we discard it.
# By induction, the final stack is a convex chain. ✓
#
# • COLLINEAR HANDLING: Using strict < in the cross product comparison (cross ≤ 0
#       → pop) EXCLUDES collinear points from the hull boundary
# • Using cross < 0 → pop INCLUDES them.
# • Check the problem: "strictly convex" means collinear points should not be on
#       the hull

# §3. ROTATING CALIPERS — DERIVATION AND APPLICATIONS

# • THE SETUP: Many geometric optimization problems over a convex polygon can be
#   solved by maintaining a pair of ANTIPODAL points — points that are "as far
#   apart as possible in a given direction" — and rotating both around the hull.
# • This is the rotating calipers method.
#
# ANTIPODAL PAIRS:
# • For a convex polygon with n vertices in CCW order, two vertices i and j are
#       ANTIPODAL if there exist parallel supporting lines, one through each
#       vertex
# • As we rotate a "direction" from 0° to 360°, the antipodal pair (i, j) changes
#       monotonically — j advances around the polygon as i advances
# • Total pointer movement: O(n).
# • This allows O(n) algorithms for problems.
# that naively take O(n²).
#
# DIAMETER OF CONVEX HULL (maximum distance between any two points):
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │                                  ⚡ ALGORITHM                             │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

#     j = 1  (start j at the "opposite" vertex from 0)
#     for i in 0..n-1:
#         max_d2 = max(max_d2, dist2(hull[i], hull[j]))
#         max_d2 = max(max_d2, dist2(hull[i+1], hull[j]))   # check adjacent too
#         # Advance j while rotating increases the "width" in direction i→i+1
#         while cross(hull[i+1]-hull[i], hull[(j+1)%n]-hull[j]) > 0:
#             j = (j+1) % n
#             max_d2 = max(max_d2, dist2(hull[i], hull[j]))
#
# WHY THE CROSS PRODUCT CONDITION WORKS:
# • The "width" in the direction perpendicular to edge i→i+1 is maximized when
#   the projection of hull[j] onto that direction is maximized.
# • cross(edge_i, hull[j+1]-hull[j]) > 0 means advancing j increases the
#   projection (the antipodal vertex hasn't been reached yet).
# • When the cross.
#   product becomes ≤ 0, j is at the antipodal point for edge i.
#
#   COMPLEXITY: Each of i and j advances monotonically around the hull → O(n) total.
#
# OTHER ROTATING CALIPERS APPLICATIONS (all O(n) given convex hull):
#   • Minimum-width bounding rectangle: rotate calipers with 4 pointers
#     (left, right, top, bottom extremes of each edge direction).
#   • Closest pair of points on convex hull: advance the other pointer.
#   • Maximum distance between two convex polygons: merge both hulls.

# §4. SWEEP LINE — THEORY AND EVENT DESIGN

# SWEEP LINE PARADIGM:
# • Imagine a vertical line sweeping from x = -∞ to x = +∞. As it sweeps, it
#   encounters EVENTS (segment endpoints, point coordinates, etc.).
# • We process these events in sorted x order, maintaining a DATA STRUCTURE
#   representing the "active" objects currently intersected by the sweep line.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY IT WORKS: Many 2D geometric problems decompose into: at each x, what
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# is the state of the y-structure? The sweep converts a 2D problem into a
# sequence of 1D updates, each answerable efficiently.
#
# KEY DESIGN DECISIONS:
#
# 1. WHAT ARE THE EVENTS?
# • For segments: "segment starts" (left endpoint) and "segment ends" (right).
# • For points: just the point's x-coordinate.
# • For rectangles: "rectangle opens" and "rectangle closes." Events processed in
#       x order; ties broken by event type (opens before closes, or vice versa,
#       depending on whether endpoints count as intersecting)
#
# 2. WHAT IS THE ACTIVE STRUCTURE?
# • A sorted set (e.g., Python's SortedList or a balanced BST) keyed by the
#   y-coordinate of each active segment AT THE CURRENT SWEEP LINE X.
# • Segments are ordered by their current y-value as x progresses.
#
# 3. WHAT CHANGES AT EACH EVENT?
#    • Segment start: INSERT into sorted set. Check neighbors for intersection.
#    • Segment end: REMOVE from sorted set. Check new neighbors for intersection.
#    • Intersection: SWAP the order of two segments in the set (they cross).
#
# SHAMOS-HOEY — Does any pair of n segments intersect? O(n log n):
# • Process start/end/intersection events.
# • If any swap event occurs → YES.
# • Maintain sorted set; check only ADJACENT segments in the set.
# • Correctness: adjacent segments in the set are the only candidates.
#   for being the "next" intersection (no segment can jump over another
#   without intersecting the segments between them first).
#
# BENTLEY-OTTMANN — Report all k intersections: O((n+k) log n):
# • Same framework.
# • When segments swap, add the new crossing event to a priority queue.
# • Careful: some events may become invalid (a swap is cancelled by an earlier swap) → use lazy deletion.
#
# AREA OF UNION OF RECTANGLES — O(n log n) using coordinate compression:
#   For each rectangle [x1,x2] × [y1,y2]:
#     Event at x1: "add interval [y1,y2] to active set."
#     Event at x2: "remove interval [y1,y2] from active set."
# • Between events at x_prev and x_next: the y-active structure tells us the
#   total covered length of the y-axis.
# • Multiply by (x_next - x_prev).
# • Maintain covered y-length in a segment tree with lazy "add/remove" counts.
#
# • WHEN TO USE EXACT INTEGER ARITHMETIC vs FLOAT: Cross products, orientation
#       tests, segment intersection existence: INTEGER
# • Python's int is exact; use it for all yes/no geometry tests.
# • Actual intersection COORDINATES: rational arithmetic or float + epsilon.
# • For Bentley-Ottmann: intersection is at rational x = (b2-b1)/(m1-m2).
# • In most CP problems you only need existence, not coordinates → stay integer.
# • Float acceptable for: computing areas, distances, angles in problems that
#   give float input or require float output.
#   RULE: if you find yourself comparing two floats with ==, switch to integers.

# §5. SELECTION GUIDE

#   ┌──────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┐
#   │ Problem Type                         │ Algorithm                        │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ Convex hull of n points              │ Andrew's monotone chain, O(n log n)│
#   │ Diameter of point set                │ Hull + rotating calipers, O(n log n)│
#   │ Point in convex polygon              │ Binary search on hull, O(log n)  │
#   │ Polygon area                         │ Shoelace formula, O(n)           │
#   │ Do any two segments intersect?       │ Shamos-Hoey sweep, O(n log n)   │
#   │ Report all k intersections           │ Bentley-Ottmann, O((n+k) log n) │
#   │ Area of union of rectangles          │ Sweep + segtree, O(n log n)     │
#   │ Segment intersection coordinates     │ Cross product / parametric line  │
#   └──────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────┘
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Bipartite matching = max flow with unit capacities; König's theorem: max matching = min vertex cover
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "prove BFS shortest"
#   - "why not DFS"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ DFS can reach a node via a long winding path before finding the short direct path
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Represent points as (x, y); use cross product for orientation and signed area
#   2. Cross product sign = left/right turn; dot product = angle between vectors
#   3. Convex hull → Andrew's monotone chain O(n log n); rotating calipers for diameter
#   → Cross product is the core primitive: it powers orientation, hull, and intersection
#
