# 🧠 MENTAL MODEL
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   "Combinatorics = structured counting of arrangements."
#   nCr = n! / (r! * (n-r)!) — precompute factorials for O(1) queries.
# • Pascal's triangle: nCr = (n-1)C(r-1) + (n-1)C(r) — builds modularly.
# • Catalan numbers: count binary trees, balanced parentheses, non-crossing partitions.
# • Inclusion-Exclusion: |A∪B| = |A| + |B| - |A∩B| — generalize to n sets.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Counting = factorials + inclusion-exclusion; always work mod prime
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Count the dominant operations in the brute-force approach
#   2. Identify which loop or recursion is the bottleneck
#   3. Find a structure or property that eliminates that bottleneck
#   → Express the improved complexity in Big-O; verify it fits n ≤ 10^6 in 2 s
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "how many ways to choose k items from n"                → nCr
#
#   ► "how many ways to arrange n items"                      → n! (with conditions: DP)
#
#   ► "count binary trees with n nodes"                       → Catalan(n)
#
#   ► "count sequences satisfying some property"              → include-exclude or DP
#
#   ► "at least k out of n conditions hold"                   → inclusion-exclusion
#
#   ► "distribution of n identical balls into k distinct boxes" → stars and bars: C(n+k-1, k-1)
#
#   ► "number of derangements (no fixed points)"              → D(n) = (n-1)*(D(n-1)+D(n-2))

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Computing nCr naively: n! / (r! * (n-r)!) with huge factorials.
#       Overflow issues and slow for large n.
#
#   ✓  Precompute fact[] and inv_fact[] modulo MOD up to MAXN.
#       C(n,r) = fact[n] * inv_fact[r] * inv_fact[n-r] % MOD → O(1) per query.
#
#   ✗  Inclusion-exclusion with 2^n subsets: exponential.
#       Only feasible for n ≤ 20.
#
#   ✓  Use structure: often inclusion-exclusion simplifies due to symmetry.
#       Or use DP to compute the same count in O(n²) instead.
#
#   ✗  Forgetting that C(n, r) = 0 when r < 0 or r > n.
#       Index out of bounds or wrong answer.
#
#   ✓  Add guard: if r < 0 or r > n: return 0.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Inclusion-exclusion: |A∪B∪C| = Σ|Aᵢ| − Σ|Aᵢ∩Aⱼ| + |A∩B∩C| — alternating sum over subsets
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Precompute factorials and inverse-factorials mod p for O(1) nCr queries
#   2. Apply inclusion-exclusion for 'at least one' / 'none of' counting
#   3. Use Burnside's lemma for problems symmetric under rotation or reflection
#   → Precompute fact[]/inv_fact[] first; all counting reduces to nCr arithmetic
