#
# §1. MATRIX MULTIPLICATION — THE CORE OPERATION

# (A × B)[i][j] = sum over k of A[i][k] * B[k][j]
# A is m×p, B is p×n → C = A×B is m×n. Time: O(m*p*n).
#
# KEY PROPERTY: Matrix multiplication is ASSOCIATIVE: (AB)C = A(BC).
# This allows fast exponentiation: M^n in O(k³ log n) where k = matrix size.

# §2. WHEN TO USE MATRIX EXPONENTIATION

# Any LINEAR RECURRENCE of fixed order can be expressed as:
#   [f(n), f(n-1), ..., f(n-k+1)] = M × [f(n-1), f(n-2), ..., f(n-k)]
# So f(n) = M^(n-1) × initial_vector.
#
# RECOGNIZING THE PATTERN:
# • "Compute the n-th term of a recurrence for n up to 10^18" → matrix exp.
# • "Count paths of length n in a graph" → adjacency matrix^n.
# • "Number of tilings of 2×n board" → DP recurrence → matrix exp.
# • Any DP where state transition is linear and n is huge.

# §3. FIBONACCI AS MATRIX EXPONENTIATION

# F(n)   = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
# [F(n), F(n-1)] = [[1,1],[1,0]] × [F(n-1), F(n-2)]
#
# So [F(n+1), F(n)] = [[1,1],[1,0]]^n × [F(1), F(0)] = M^n × [1, 0].
# Compute M^n in O(2³ × log n) = O(log n).
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Fibonacci matrix: [[F(n+1)],[F(n)]] = [[1,1],[1,0]]^n × [[1],[0]] — derive by induction
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "nth Fibonacci"
#   - "linear recurrence"
#   - "large n"
#   - "state transition"
#   - "counting paths of length n"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Matrix multiplication is O(k³) per multiply; total O(k³ log n) — k must be small
#   ✗ Not initializing the identity matrix correctly for matrix power
#   ✗ Applying this to non-linear recurrences → doesn't work; only linear recurrences
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Can I write a check(x) function: "is x achievable?"
#   2. Is check(x) monotone? (if x works, x+1 works too?)
#   → Yes → binary search on x, call check(mid) inside
#
