#
# • "Expected value = weighted average of all outcomes by their probabilities."
#       Linearity of expectation: E[X+Y] = E[X] + E[Y] always (even if X,Y
#       dependent)
# • This is the most powerful tool — split complex random variable into simple
#       indicators
# • Geometric distribution: expected number of trials until success = 1/p.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "expected number of operations/moves/steps"             → E[X] = linearity
#
#   ► "probability that condition C holds"                    → P(C) = sum of cases
#
#   ► "random process, many independent trials"               → geometric / binomial
#
#   ► "expected value on a graph/tree (random walk)"          → set up E[v] equations
#
#   ► "coupon collector problem"                              → E = n * H(n) ≈ n ln n
#
#   ► "probability DP"                                        → dp[state] = probability

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Computing E[X] by enumerating ALL outcomes (exponential).
#
#   ✓  Use linearity of expectation: write X = X1 + X2 + ... + Xn (indicator variables).
#       E[X] = sum of E[Xi] = sum of P(Xi=1). Often O(n) instead of O(2^n).
#
#   ✗  Confusing P(A and B) = P(A)*P(B) — only valid for INDEPENDENT events.
#
#   ✓  Check independence first. If events depend on shared randomness, use conditional.
#
#   ✗  Probability DP without normalizing — working with exact fractions.
#       Fractions are slow. Use modular arithmetic instead.
#
#   ✓  Work modulo MOD. Probability p/q mod MOD = p * pow(q, MOD-2, MOD) % MOD.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Expected value is linear even for dependent events — E[X+Y]=E[X]+E[Y] always holds
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
