# 🚀 THE SETUP — WHAT KIND OF GAMES?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# We only study games where:
#   • Two players take turns.
#   • Both have the same available moves from any position.
#   • The player who can't move LOSES (normal play convention).
#   • Both play PERFECTLY (no luck, no hidden information).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🔥 P-POSITIONS vs N-POSITIONS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Label every game position as one of two types:
#
#   P-position (you will LOSE if you're here with optimal opponent):
#     → every move you make puts your opponent in an N-position (they win from there).
#
#   N-position (you will WIN if you're here):
#     → at least ONE move takes your opponent to a P-position (they lose from there).
#
#   Base case: no moves available → P-position (you lose because you can't move).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ⚡ NIM — THE SIMPLEST GAME WITH DEEP MATH  [MATH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# k piles of stones. Your turn: pick ANY pile, remove ANY number (≥1) from it.
# The player who empties the LAST pile wins (takes the last stone).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ THE XOR RULE (most important fact in CP game theory):  [BIT]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   XOR of all pile sizes = 0  →  P-position  →  current player LOSES
#   XOR of all pile sizes ≠ 0  →  N-position  →  current player WINS
#
# WHY XOR?
#   From XOR≠0: you can ALWAYS reduce one pile to make XOR=0. (Optimal move.)
#   From XOR=0: ANY move you make creates XOR≠0 for your opponent. (They win.)
#
# Example: piles [3, 5, 6]. XOR = 3^5^6 = 0 → P-position → first player LOSES.
#          piles [3, 5, 7]. XOR = 3^5^7 = 1 → N-position → first player WINS.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 GRUNDY VALUES — Generalizing to Any Game
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • For ANY game position, assign a Grundy value g: g = mex of {Grundy values of
#       all positions reachable in one move} mex = the smallest non-negative
#       integer NOT in the set
#
# Examples:
# • Terminal position (no moves): g = mex({}) = 0  → P-position.
# • Reaches only g=0 positions: g = mex({0}) = 1   → N-position.
# • Reaches g=0 and g=1: g = mex({0,1}) = 2        → N-position.
#
# g=0 → P-position (lose). g>0 → N-position (win).
#
# • SPRAGUE-GRUNDY POWER: ANY impartial game position with Grundy value g is
#       EQUIVALENT to a single Nim pile of size g
# • So for compound games: g(combined) = XOR of g(each sub-game)   ← reduces
#       everything to Nim!
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Grundy(state) = MEX{Grundy(next_states)} — compound game XOR of individual Grundy numbers
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "nim"
#   - "take stones"
#   - "game theory"
#   - "first player wins"
#   - "optimal play"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ XOR=0 only tells you current position is losing IF both players play optimally
#   ✗ Misère Nim: if all piles ≤ 1, XOR rule reverses; otherwise same as normal Nim
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Can I write a check(x) function: "is x achievable?"
#   2. Is check(x) monotone? (if x works, x+1 works too?)
#   → Yes → binary search on x, call check(mid) inside
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
