# ── nim_winner — inline ──
# result→_nim_win (True=first player wins)
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Nim: XOR of all pile sizes ≠ 0 ↔ first player wins — foundation of combinatorial game theory.
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "take from piles, last move wins (normal play)"
#   - "Nim / stone removal game"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Confusing normal play (last move wins) with misère (last move loses)
#   ✗ Applying Nim XOR to games not equivalent to Nim — check Sprague-Grundy first
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. XOR=0 → every move creates XOR≠0 → second player always counters.
#   2. XOR≠0 → first player can always move to XOR=0.
#   3. Proof: induction on total stones.
#
# CF TAGS: game theory, math  |  Rating: 1200–1800

#

# ── nim_winning_move — inline ──
xor_val=0
for prime in piles:
    xor_val^=prime
winning_move=None
for i,prime in enumerate(piles):
    target=prime^xor_val
    if target<prime:
        winning_move=(i,target)
    break
# result→_nwm
