# COMMON GAME THEORY PATTERNS IN CONTESTS:
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
#
# │ Problem type                         │ Approach                          │
# ├──────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┤
# │ Remove from single pile              │ nim_winner / Grundy values        │
# │ Multiple independent piles           │ XOR of Grundy values              │
# │ Game on graph, moves along edges     │ Grundy = mex of neighbor Grundy   │
# │ Grid game, move left/down            │ Grundy[i][j] = mex of reachable   │
# │ "Last player wins on sum/product"    │ Often just parity check           │
# │ "Optimal score, not just win/loss"   │ minimax DP, not Grundy            │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# GAME THEORY COMMON MISTAKES:
# 1. Applying Sprague-Grundy to NON-IMPARTIAL games (where players have different moves).
# 2. Confusing normal play (last move wins) and misère (last move loses).
# 3. For compound games: XOR only works when sub-games are INDEPENDENT.
# 4. Grundy period: many games have periodic Grundy values — find and exploit.
# 5. "First player always wins" or "second always wins" — test small cases first.
