# 🧠 MENTAL MODEL
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • "Game theory = who wins when both players play optimally?" Sprague-Grundy
#       theorem: every impartial game position has a Grundy number (nimber)
# • Grundy(pos) = mex({Grundy(child) for each move}) — mex = minimum excludant.
# • Combined game: XOR of all individual Grundy values.
# • If XOR ≠ 0 → first player wins.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Grundy value 0 = losing position; non-zero = winning — compute bottom-up
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Count the dominant operations in the brute-force approach
#   2. Identify which loop or recursion is the bottleneck
#   3. Find a structure or property that eliminates that bottleneck
#   → Express the improved complexity in Big-O; verify it fits n ≤ 10^6 in 2 s
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "two players, take turns, last to move wins (normal play)"  → Sprague-Grundy
#
#   ► "multiple piles, each turn reduce one pile"                 → Nim (XOR of sizes)
#
#   ► "game on graph, move token, can't move = lose"             → Grundy on graph
#
#   ► "coin row game, both take optimally"                        → minimax DP
#
#   ► "sum of independent games"                                  → XOR Grundy numbers
#
#   ► "Grundy = 0 → losing position for player to move (P-position)"
#
#   ► "last player to move LOSES (misère nim)"                    → XOR rule with twist

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Simulating all game trees with brute force memoization.
#       O(state space) — fine for small games, impossible for n=10^9 pile sizes.
#
#   ✓  Recognize Nim structure: Grundy(pile of size n) = n. XOR all piles.
#       No simulation needed. O(number of piles).
#
#   ✗  Confusing normal play (last move wins) with misère play (last move loses).
#       The XOR rule changes for misère!
#
#   ✓  Misère Nim: same as normal EXCEPT when all piles have size ≤ 1.
#       If max pile size > 1: XOR ≠ 0 → first player wins (same as normal).
#       If all piles ≤ 1: odd number of piles → second player wins.
#
#   ✗  Computing mex by scanning all non-negative integers from 0 upward every time.
#       Slow if mex value is large.
#
#   ✓  Use a set for occupied values, scan from 0: O(moves) per state. Fine in practice.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Grundy(state)=mex{Grundy(moves)}; compound game Grundy = XOR of components — compute bottom-up
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Compute Grundy (nimber) values: G(state) = mex({G(reachable states)})
#   2. For Nim: XOR all pile sizes — if XOR = 0 second player wins, else first player wins
#   3. Sum of independent games: XOR their individual Grundy values
#   → Sprague-Grundy: every impartial game is equivalent to a Nim heap
#
