# §1. THE STRING PROBLEM LANDSCAPE

# String problems fall into several major categories:
#
#   1. PATTERN MATCHING: Does pattern P appear in text T?
#      → KMP, Z-algorithm, Rabin-Karp hashing
#
#   2. SUBSTRING QUERIES: What is hash/length/count of substring s[l..r]?
#      → Polynomial hashing (O(1) after O(n) build)
#
#   3. PALINDROME PROBLEMS: Longest palindromic substring, count palindromes.
#      → Manacher's algorithm (O(n))
#
#   4. STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS: Periods, borders, repeated substrings.
#      → Z-function, KMP failure function
#
#   5. MULTIPLE PATTERNS: Match many patterns simultaneously.
#      → Aho-Corasick automaton (KMP generalization)
#
#   6. ALL SUBSTRINGS / SUFFIX STRUCTURE:
#      → Suffix array + LCP array (O(n log n) build, many O(n) applications)

# §2. POLYNOMIAL HASHING — THE THEORY BEHIND RANDOMIZED MATCHING

# MATHEMATICAL FOUNDATION:
# View a string s = s[0]s[1]...s[n-1] as a polynomial evaluated at base p:
#   H(s) = s[0]×p^(n-1) + s[1]×p^(n-2) + ... + s[n-1]×p^0  (mod M)
#
# SUBSTRING HASH via prefix:
#   Define: h[i] = H(s[0..i-1]) = s[0]×p^(i-1) + ... + s[i-1]×p^0
#   Then: H(s[l..r]) = (h[r+1] - h[l]×p^(r-l+1)) mod M
#
# WHY DOES THIS WORK?
#   h[r+1] = s[0]×p^r + s[1]×p^(r-1) + ... + s[r]×p^0
#   h[l]×p^(r-l+1) = s[0]×p^r + s[1]×p^(r-1) + ... + s[l-1]×p^(r-l+1)
#   Their difference = s[l]×p^(r-l) + ... + s[r]×p^0 = H(s[l..r]) ✓
#
# • COLLISION PROBABILITY: With a random base p and large modulus M, the
#       probability that two different strings have the same hash is ≈ 1/M
# • With M ≈ 10^18 and 10^5 comparisons: P(any collision) ≈ 10^5/10^18 = 10^-13.
#
# • ANTI-HACK PROTECTION: Some CF problems are designed to break specific hashes.
# • Use DOUBLE HASHING with two different (base, mod) pairs: (base₁=131,
#       mod₁=10⁹+7) and (base₂=137, mod₂=10^9+9) Store hash as a tuple
# • Equal hashes = same string (with astronomically high probability).

# §3. Z-FUNCTION — DEEP DERIVATION AND ANALYSIS

# IN SIMPLE TERMS: z[i] = length of the longest common prefix of s and s[i:].
# Equivalently: the longest string that is BOTH a prefix of s AND starts at position i.
#
# WHY IS THIS USEFUL?
# Once we know z[i] ≥ k, we know that s[i..i+k-1] = s[0..k-1].
# This tells us where copies of prefixes appear in the string.
#
# COMPUTATION IN O(n) — THE Z-BOX TRICK:
# Maintain the Z-box [l, r]: the rightmost interval where a match was found.
# Invariant: s[l..r] = s[0..r-l].
#
# For position i:
# • Case 1: i > r (outside Z-box): compute z[i] naively by comparing.
# • Case 2: i ≤ r (inside Z-box): we know s[i..r] = s[i-l..r-l].
#   Sub-case 2a: z[i-l] < r-i+1  →  z[i] = z[i-l]  (entirely within Z-box).
# • Sub-case 2b: z[i-l] ≥ r-i+1 → z[i] ≥ r-i+1, try to extend naively.
#   Update Z-box if i+z[i]-1 > r.
#
# WHY O(n)? The right boundary r of the Z-box only moves RIGHTWARD.
# Each character is compared at most twice (once to compute z, once as part of Z-box).
# Total comparisons = O(n). ✓
#
# DIAGRAM — Z-Function Computation on s="aabaaab":
#
#   s: a  a  b  a  a  a  b
#   i: 0  1  2  3  4  5  6
#
#   i=1: s[1:]="abaaab". Compare with "aabaaab". s[1]='a'=s[0], s[2]='b'≠s[1]. z[1]=1.
#        Z-box: l=1, r=1.
#   i=2: s[2]='b'≠s[0]='a'. z[2]=0. Z-box unchanged.
#   i=3: i≤r? No (r=1). s[3:]="aaab". Compare: s[3]='a'=s[0], s[4]='a'=s[1], s[5]='a'≠s[2]='b'. z[3]=2.
#        Z-box: l=3, r=4.
# • i=4: i≤r (r=4).
# • z[1]=1 ≥ r-i+1=1, so z[4] ≥ 1.
# • Try extend: s[4+1]='a'? s[1]='a'. Match! z[4] ≥ 2.
# • s[4+2]='b'? s[2]='b'. Match! s[4+3] out of bounds.
# • Z-box: l=4, r=6.
# • z[1]=1 < r-i+1=2.
# • z[2]=0 < r-i+1=1.
#
#   z = [0, 1, 0, 2, 3, 1, 0]

# §4. KMP FAILURE FUNCTION — DEEP UNDERSTANDING

# IN SIMPLE TERMS: π[i] = length of the longest PROPER prefix of s[0..i]
# that is ALSO a suffix of s[0..i]. ("Proper" means not the full string itself.)
#
# 🧠 INTUITION:
#   • π[i] tells us: "if we fail matching at position i+1 in the pattern,
# we don't restart from scratch. Instead, we fall back to position π[i],
# because s[0..π[i]-1] still matches the end of what we've matched so far."
#
# CONNECTION TO Z-FUNCTION:
# • π and z encode similar information differently.
# • z[i] = longest prefix starting at i.
# • π[i] = longest border of prefix 0..i.
# • They can be converted to each other in O(n).
#
# COMPUTING π IN O(n):
# • Key: π[i] ≤ π[i-1] + 1 (can grow by at most 1 each step).
# • If s[π[prev]] == s[i]: π[i] = π[prev] + 1.
# • Otherwise: fall back via π chain: π[prev] = π[π[prev]-1], repeat.
# • Each fall-back strictly decreases the value → total O(n) falls.
#
# IMPORTANT USES OF π:
#
#   1. PATTERN MATCHING: Build failure function for pattern.
#      Use it to skip redundant comparisons during text scanning.
#      O(n+m) total.
#
# • MINIMUM PERIOD: period(s) = n - π[n-1]. If n divisible by period → s is a
#       perfect repetition
# • Example: "abababab" has π[7]=6.
# • Period = 8-6 = 2.
# • "ab" repeated 4 times.
#
#   3. COUNT DISTINCT BORDERS: The borders of s are s[0..π[n-1]-1],
#      s[0..π[π[n-1]-1]-1], etc. (follow the π chain).

# §5. SUFFIX ARRAYS — THE SWISS ARMY KNIFE FOR HARD STRING PROBLEMS

# IN SIMPLE TERMS: SA (suffix array) is a sorted permutation of all suffix starting
# positions. SA[i] = starting position of the i-th lexicographically smallest suffix.
#
# BUILDING IN O(n log n):
# • Use the prefix doubling technique (Kasai's or DC3 algorithm).
# • Iteratively sort suffixes by their 2^k-length prefixes.
# • After O(log n) rounds, all suffixes are sorted.
#
# THE LCP ARRAY:
# lcp[i] = length of longest common prefix of SA[i-1]-th and SA[i]-th suffixes.
# LCP gives the "overlap" between adjacent suffixes in sorted order.
#
# KEY APPLICATIONS:
#
#   1. COUNT DISTINCT SUBSTRINGS:
#      Total substrings - Σ lcp[i] = n(n+1)/2 - Σ lcp[i].
#      Each entry lcp[i] accounts for duplicate substrings between adjacent suffixes.
#
#   2. LONGEST REPEATED SUBSTRING:
#      max(lcp[i]) over all i.
#
# • LONGEST COMMON SUBSTRING of two strings: Concatenate with separator '$', build
#       SA+LCP
# • Find maximum lcp[i] where SA[i] and SA[i-1] come from different strings.
#
# • STRING MATCHING (find pattern P in text T): Binary search on SA to find range
#       where suffixes start with P
# • O(m log n) per query after O(n log n) build.

# §6. STRING ALGORITHM SELECTION GUIDE

#   ┌──────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┐
#   │ Problem Type                         │ Best Algorithm                     │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ Single pattern in text               │ KMP or Z-function, O(n+m)         │
#   │ Multiple patterns in text            │ Aho-Corasick, O(n+Σm)             │
#   │ Substring comparison (many queries)  │ Polynomial Hashing, O(1)/query    │
#   │ Longest repeated substring           │ Suffix Array + LCP, O(n log n)    │
#   │ Count distinct substrings            │ Suffix Array + LCP, O(n log n)    │
#   │ String period/border structure       │ KMP failure function, O(n)        │
#   │ Z-values for all positions           │ Z-algorithm, O(n)                 │
#   │ Palindromes (longest/count)          │ Manacher's algorithm, O(n)        │
#   │ Lexicographic rotation minimum       │ Booth's algorithm, O(n)           │
#   └──────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────┘

# COMMON STRING MISTAKES:
#   1. Naive O(n²) hashing when O(n) KMP would suffice.
#   2. Single hashing on CF problems with deliberate anti-hash tests.
#      Always use double hashing for safety.
# • Off-by-one in Z-array (z[0] is conventionally 0 or n — be consistent).
# • KMP separator '$' must NOT appear in either pattern or text.
# • Use a character outside the alphabet (e.g., '$' when input is lowercase letters).
# • Comparing substrings with == in Python is O(n) — use hashing for O(1).
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Z[i] = length of longest substring starting at i that matches prefix of s — O(n) construction
