# Game theory in CP = two-player perfect-information games where both players
# play OPTIMALLY. Your job: determine who wins given an initial position.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 💡 THE KEY CONCEPT — P-positions and N-positions
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Every position in a combinatorial game is either:
# • P-position (Previous player wins): the player who just MOVED wins.
# • Equivalently: the player whose TURN it is will LOSE (with optimal play).
# • N-position (Next player wins): the player whose TURN it is will WIN.
#
# Computing P/N positions:
# • Base case: no moves available → LOSE (P-position for the player to move).
# • If ANY move leads to a P-position → this is an N-position (take that move!).
# • If ALL moves lead to N-positions → this is a P-position (you're going to lose).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🎯 NIM — THE FUNDAMENTAL GAME  [MATH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Several piles of stones. Each turn: pick any pile, remove any number (at least 1).
# The player who takes the LAST stone WINS.
#
# THEOREM: Position is a LOSING position (P-position) if and only if XOR of all pile sizes = 0.
#
# • WHY XOR? Because XOR has the perfect property: If XOR ≠ 0: you can ALWAYS make
#       a move to reach XOR = 0
# • If XOR = 0: ANY move you make creates XOR ≠ 0 (opponent wins next).
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Sprague-Grundy: any impartial game position with Grundy=0 is a loss for the player to move
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What does brute force look like?
#   2. What is the complexity bottleneck?
#   3. What structure or property enables optimization?
#   → Code the optimized approach
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🚀 GRUNDY VALUES (Sprague-Grundy Theory)  [MATH]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • Every game position gets a "Grundy value" (g): g = mex({g of all positions
#       reachable in one move}) mex = minimum excludant = smallest non-negative
#       integer NOT in the set
#
# g = 0 → losing position (P-position)
# g > 0 → winning position (N-position)
#
# • For COMPOUND games (multiple independent sub-games played simultaneously):
#       g(total) = XOR of all individual g values
# • This reduces ANY compound game to a Nim-like analysis!.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ STRING ALGORITHMS — OVERVIEW
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# String algorithms deal with pattern matching, substring problems, and string
# structure. Naive pattern matching: O(n×m). All efficient algorithms: O(n+m) or O(n log n).

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# 26A. POLYNOMIAL HASHING — O(1) Substring Comparison After O(n) Preprocessing

# WHAT: Map strings to integers using polynomial evaluation.
# hash(s) = s[0]×p^(n-1) + s[1]×p^(n-2) + ... + s[n-1] where p is a prime base.
#
# Prefix hash array lets us compute hash of any substring in O(1):
# hash(s[l..r]) = (h[r+1] - h[l] × p^(r-l+1)) mod M
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ WHY IT WORKS: Two equal strings → same hash. Two different strings → almost always
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# different hashes (collision probability ≈ 1/M per comparison).
#
# TO REDUCE COLLISION RISK: Use double hashing (two different (p, M) pairs).
# With M ≈ 10^18 and double hashing: collision probability ≈ 1/10^18 per test.
#
# ANTI-HASH TESTS: Some CF problems are specifically designed to break single
# polynomial hashing. Always use double hashing or Z-function/KMP for critical problems.
#

# ── build_string_hash — inline ──
count_n=len(s)
pw=[1]*(count_n+1)
h=[0]*(count_n+1)
for i in range(count_n):
    pw[i+1]=pw[i]*base%mod
    h[i+1]=(h[i]*base+ord(s[i]))%mod
# get(l,r): (h[r+1]-h[l]*pw[r-l+1])%mod  (0-indexed, inclusive)
#
    def get(l, r):
        return (h[r+1] - h[l] * pw[r-l+1]) % mod
#
    # return get
#
#   get = build_string_hash("abcabc")
#   get(0, 2) == get(3, 5)   # True — both are "abc"

# 26B. Z-ALGORITHM — Pattern Matching + Structure Discovery in O(n+m)

# WHAT IS Z-ARRAY?
# z[i] = length of the longest string starting at s[i] that is also a PREFIX of s.
# z[0] is undefined (conventionally 0 or n).
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ EXAMPLE: s = "aabxaaab"
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# z[0] = 0 (undefined)
# z[1] = 1 (s[1..1]="a" = prefix "a") — checking: s[1]='a', s[0]='a' ✓, s[2]='b' ≠ s[1] → z[1]=1
# z[2] = 0 (s[2]='b' ≠ s[0]='a')
# z[3] = 0 (s[3]='x' ≠ 'a')
# z[4] = 3 (s[4..6]="aaa" matches s[0..2]="aab"? No. "aaa" vs "aab": match 2, then a≠b. → z[4]=2?)
# z[4]=2: s[4..5]="aa" matches prefix s[0..1]="aa"; s[6]='a'≠s[2]='b' → stop. z[4]=2.
# z[5]=0: s[5]='a', s[6]='a', s[7]='b' → s[0..2]="aab"; matches! z[5]=3? Check: s="aabxaaab".
#         s[5]='a'=s[0], s[6]='a'=s[1], s[7]='b'=s[2]. All match → z[5]=3.
# z[6]=1: s[6]='a'=s[0], s[7]='b'≠s[1]='a' → z[6]=1.
# z[7]=0: s[7]='b'≠s[0]='a' → z[7]=0.
#
# ALGORITHM: O(n). Maintain a window [l,r] that is the rightmost Z-box matched so far.
# For each position i: if i < r, z[i] >= min(z[i-l], r-i).
# Then extend naively from z[i] forward (each extension is amortized O(1) because r only advances).
#

# ── z_function — inline ──
# result→z
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Z-function: z[i] = length of longest prefix of s matching s[i..] — O(n) construction.
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "find pattern in text" (concatenate pattern+"#"+text)
#   - "longest prefix that also appears at position i"
#   - "minimum period" (= n - fail[n-1] or n - z-based)
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ z[0] = n by convention; some code sets it to 0 → check your implementation
#   ✗ Off-by-one: r = i + z[i], not i + z[i] - 1
#   ✗ Forgetting "#" separator when pattern-matching → false matches
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Maintain Z-box [l,r] = rightmost known match window.
#   2. If i < r: initialise z[i] from mirror z[i-l].
#   3. Extend naively; update [l,r] if exceeded.
#
# CF TAGS: strings, z-function  |  Rating: 1600–2100

#
# PATTERN MATCHING with Z-algorithm:
# Build string: pattern + '$' + text. Compute Z-array.
# Positions where z[i] >= len(pattern) indicate occurrences of pattern in text.
#

# ── z_pattern_match — inline ──
combined=pattern+"#"+text
n_cols=len(combined)
z_combined=[0]*n_cols
z_left=z_right=0
for i in range(1,n_cols):
    if i<z_right:
        z_combined[i]=min(z_right-i,z_combined[i-z_left])
    while i+z_combined[i]<n_cols and combined[z_combined[i]]==combined[i+z_combined[i]]:
        z_combined[i]+=1
    if i+z_combined[i]>z_right:
        z_left=i
    z_right=i+z_combined[i]
pat_len=len(pattern)
positions=[i-pat_len-1 for i in range(pat_len+1,n_cols) if z_combined[i]>=pat_len]
# result→positions
#
# Returns list of starting indices of pattern in text.

# 26C. KMP ALGORITHM — Failure Function + Pattern Matching in O(n+m)

# WHAT: Efficient pattern matching. Avoids redundant comparisons by remembering
# how much of the prefix we've already matched when a mismatch occurs.
#
# • FAILURE FUNCTION (prefix function) π[i]: π[i] = length of longest proper
#       prefix of s[0..i] that is also a SUFFIX
# • "Proper" = not the full string itself.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ EXAMPLE: s = "aabaaab"
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# • π[0] = 0 (no proper prefix/suffix of single character) π[1] = 1 ("a" is both
#       prefix and suffix of "aa") π[2] = 0 ("aab": no proper prefix that's also a
#       suffix)
# π[3] = 1 ("aaba": "a" matches)
# π[4] = 2 ("aabaa": "aa" matches)
# π[5] = 2 ("aabaaa": "aa" matches... let me check: prefix "aa"="aa" which is last 2 chars)
# π[6] = 3 ("aabaaab": prefix "aab" = suffix "aab" ✓)
#
# HOW KMP USES π:
# When pattern[j] ≠ text[i], fall back to pattern[π[j-1]].
# We don't reset j to 0 — we skip to the longest prefix that is still valid.
#

# ── kmp_failure — inline ──
# DRY RUN — KMP Failure Function on pattern = "ababab":
#   i:     0  1  2  3  4  5
#   pat:   a  b  a  b  a  b
#   fail:  0  0  1  2  3  4
#
#   i=1: pat[0]='a' != pat[1]='b', k stays 0 -> fail[1]=0
#   i=2: pat[0]='a' == pat[2]='a', k=1 -> fail[2]=1
#   i=3: pat[1]='b' == pat[3]='b', k=2 -> fail[3]=2
#   i=4: pat[2]='a' == pat[4]='a', k=3 -> fail[4]=3
#   i=5: pat[3]='b' == pat[5]='b', k=4 -> fail[5]=4
#   Reading: fail[5]=4 means "ababab" has a prefix of length 4 ("abab")
#   that also appears as a suffix. The minimum period = 6-4 = 2.
# Time: O(m) | Space: O(m)
m=len(pattern)
fail=[0]*m
match_len=0
for i in range(1,m):
    while match_len>0 and pattern[match_len]!=pattern[i]:
        match_len=fail[match_len-1]
    if pattern[match_len]==pattern[i]:
        match_len+=1
    fail[i]=match_len
# result→fail
#

# ── kmp_search — inline ──
# result→positions
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   KMP: failure function enables O(n+m) matching without backtracking.
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "find all occurrences of pattern in text"
#   - "minimum period of string"
#   - "is one string a rotation of another"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ After match: reset q=fail[q-1] not q=0 → misses overlapping matches
#   ✗ Building failure function on the wrong string (must be on pattern only)
#   ✗ Forgetting "#" separator when checking rotation (pattern#doubled)
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. fail[i] = longest proper prefix of pattern[0..i] that is also suffix.
#   2. On mismatch: jump q = fail[q-1] instead of q=0.
#   3. Each char matched or skipped at most once → O(n+m).
#
# CF TAGS: strings, string matching  |  Rating: 1600–2100

# 26D. SUFFIX ARRAY — Advanced String Structure

# • Suffix array = sorted array of all suffixes of s.
# • Enables O(m log n) search for any pattern m in text n (after O(n log n) build).
# • Also: longest repeated substring, number of distinct substrings, etc.
# • Advanced technique (Div.1 D/E level).
# • Build using O(n log n) doubling algorithm.
#

# ── suffix_array — inline ──
# Time: O(n log^2 n) (can be O(n log n) with radix sort) | Space: O(n)
# O(n log n) suffix array via prefix doubling
count_n=len(s)
suffix_arr=list(range(count_n))
coord_rank=[ord(c) for c in s]
tmp_val=[0]*count_n
match_len=1
while match_len<count_n:
    def sort_key(i): return (coord_rank[i],coord_rank[i+match_len] if i+match_len<count_n else -1)
    suffix_arr.sort(key=sort_key)
    tmp_val[suffix_arr[0]]=0
    for i in range(1,count_n):
        prev_key = sort_key(suffix_arr[i-1])
        curr_key = sort_key(suffix_arr[i])
        tmp_val[suffix_arr[i]] = tmp_val[suffix_arr[i-1]] + (1 if curr_key != prev_key else 0)
    coord_rank=tmp_val[:]
    if coord_rank[suffix_arr[-1]]==count_n-1:
        break
    match_len*=2
# result→_sa (suffix array)
#
# For n up to 10^6, use O(n log n) construction (DC3 or prefix doubling).
# This is an advanced algorithm — implement only when needed.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Suffix array + LCP array: sort O(n log n), then longest repeated substring = max LCP in O(n)
#   - "Longest repeated substring", "number of distinct substrings" → suffix array + LCP
#   - Pattern appears in multiple strings simultaneously → Aho-Corasick or suffix automaton
#   - "How many occurrences of pattern p in text t" → KMP or Z-function O(n+m)
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Off-by-one in boundary conditions (l vs l-1, r vs r+1)
#   ✗ Not handling n=0 or n=1 edge case
#   ✗ Integer overflow: use // not / for integer division in Python
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. What does brute force look like?
#   ✗ Naive O(n²) suffix array construction: TLE for n>10⁴ — use doubling O(n log n)
#   ✗ Suffix array indices are 0-based positions in s — off-by-one when mapping to 1-indexed
#   ✗ LCP array requires suffix array to be built first — cannot compute LCP independently
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🎯 PRACTICE PROBLEMS — STRING ALGORITHMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# PROBLEM 26-1 [Easy]: Check if string is a rotation of another
# s1 is rotation of s2 if and only if s1 appears in s2+s2. Use KMP or hashing.
#

# ── is_rotation — inline ──
if len(s1)!=len(s2):
    is_rotation=False
else:
    doubled=s1+s1
    m=len(s2)
    n3=len(doubled)
    kmp_fail=[0]*m
    match_len=0
    for i in range(1,m):
        while match_len>0 and s2[match_len]!=s2[i]:
            match_len=kmp_fail[match_len-1]
        if s2[match_len]==s2[i]:
            match_len+=1
        kmp_fail[i]=match_len
    match_pos=0
    is_rotation=False
    for i in range(n3):
        while match_pos>0 and s2[match_pos]!=doubled[i]:
            match_pos=kmp_fail[match_pos-1]
        if s2[match_pos]==doubled[i]:
            match_pos+=1
        if match_pos==m:
            is_rotation=True
        break
# result→_ir
#
# PROBLEM 26-2 [Medium]: Longest Repeated Substring
# Build Z-function of s. Max z[i] = length of longest repeat starting at position i.
#

# ── longest_repeated_substring — inline ──
count_n=len(s)
suffix_arr=list(range(count_n))
coord_rank=[ord(c) for c in s]
tmp_val=[0]*count_n
match_len=1
while match_len<count_n:
    def sort_key(i): return (coord_rank[i],coord_rank[i+match_len] if i+match_len<count_n else -1)
    suffix_arr.sort(key=sort_key)
    tmp_val[suffix_arr[0]]=0
    for i in range(1,count_n):
        prev_key = sort_key(suffix_arr[i-1])
        curr_key = sort_key(suffix_arr[i])
        tmp_val[suffix_arr[i]] = tmp_val[suffix_arr[i-1]] + (0 if curr_key == prev_key else 1)
    coord_rank=tmp_val[:]
    if coord_rank[suffix_arr[-1]]==count_n-1:
        break
    match_len*=2
# LCP via Kasai
lcp_arr=[0]*count_n
inv_count=[0]*count_n
for i in range(count_n):
    inv_count[suffix_arr[i]]=i
height=0
for i in range(count_n):
    if inv_count[i]>0:
        j=suffix_arr[inv_count[i]-1]
        while i+height<count_n and j+height<count_n and s[i+height]==s[j+height]:
            height+=1
        lcp_arr[inv_count[i]]=height
        if height:
            height-=1
lrs_len=max(lcp_arr) if lcp_arr else 0
lrs_start=suffix_arr[lcp_arr.index(lrs_len)] if lrs_len else 0
longest_rep_sub=s[lrs_start:lrs_start+lrs_len]
# result→_lrs
#
# PROBLEM 26-3 [Medium]: Minimum Period of a String
# Period p of string s: s[i] = s[i+p] for all valid i.
# 💡 KEY INSIGHT:
#   • minimum period = n - π[n-1] (from KMP failure function).
# If n is divisible by (n - π[n-1]), that's the minimum period.
#

# ── min_period — inline ──
count_n=len(s)
period_fail=[0]*count_n
match_len=0
for i in range(1,count_n):
    while match_len>0 and s[match_len]!=s[i]:
        match_len=period_fail[match_len-1]
    if s[match_len]==s[i]:
        match_len+=1
    period_fail[i]=match_len
period=count_n-period_fail[count_n-1]
min_period=period if count_n%period==0 else count_n
# result→_min_period
#
# • PROBLEM 26-4 [Hard]: Count Distinct Substrings Using hashing: generate all
#       O(n²) substrings and add to a set
# • O(n²) with hashing → OK for n ≤ 5000.
# • For n ≤ 10^5, use suffix array.
#

# ── count_distinct_substrings_hash — inline ──
seen_map=set()
for i in range(len(s)):
    for j in range(i+1,len(s)+1):
        seen_map.add(s[i:j])
distinct_subs=len(seen_map)
# result→_cdsh (naive O(n^3); for large n use suffix array LCP method)
#
# • PROBLEM 26-5 [CF-Style]: Find All Occurrences of Pattern in Text Solution:
#       z_pattern_match(text, pattern)  or  kmp_search(text, pattern) KMP is
#       usually slightly faster in practice for single searches
#
# • PROBLEM 26-6 [Hard]: Anagram Check / Sliding Anagram Window
#   Problem: Does any substring of t of length len(s) equal an anagram of s?
#   Solution: sliding window + frequency array comparison.
# • O(n×alphabet).
#

# ── has_anagram_window — inline ──
from collections import Counter as _Ctr2
tc=_Ctr2(t)
wc=_Ctr2()
has_anagram=False
lo3=0
for r_idx,c in enumerate(s):
    wc[c]+=1
    if r_idx-lo3+1>len(t):
        lc=s[lo3]
        wc[lc]-=1
        if wc[lc]==0:
            del wc[lc]
        lo3+=1
    if wc==tc:
        has_anagram=True
    break
# result→_found_aw
# 💡 PRO TIP:
#   • For string problems on CF, the hierarchy is:
# • Try hashing first (easiest to code).
# • If anti-hash tests are possible, use Z-algorithm or KMP.
# • For advanced problems (Div.1 D/E): suffix array + LCP array.
# • For prefix/pattern structure: always think Z-array or KMP failure function.
#
# COMMON STRING MISTAKES:
# • Using single hashing on CF problems with anti-hash tests.
# • Use DOUBLE hashing.
# • Off-by-one in Z-array indexing (z[0] is often left as 0, not n).
# • Forgetting that KMP returns all occurrences including overlapping ones.
# • Building string as "pattern$text" for KMP — the '$' separator MUST be a
#       character that doesn't appear in either string (or any unique separator)
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Choose base (131 or 10⁹+7) and MOD (large prime)
#   2. prefix[i] = prefix[i-1]*base + ord(s[i])
#   3. hash(l,r) = (prefix[r] - prefix[l-1]*pow(base,r-l+1)) % MOD
#   → Double hash: use two different (base,MOD) pairs
#
