# ║                       BONUS F — XOR / LINEAR BASIS                       ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# • WHAT: A set of vectors over GF(2) (i.e.
# • bitstrings under XOR) that spans the same XOR-space as a given set S.
# • The basis has at most log₂(max_val) ≈ 30–60 elements.
# • Core operation: insert a new number, maintain reduced row-echelon form.
#
# WHY IT MATTERS:
# • "Maximum XOR of any subset of A" → greedily build basis, then query max xor.
# • "Count subsets with XOR = k"     → basis + free variables → 2^(n-rank) subsets.
# • "XOR of any path in a graph"     → reduce to basis on cycle-space.
#
# CORE TEMPLATE:
#
# class LinearBasis:
#     def __init__(self, bits=30):
#         self.b = [0] * bits   # b[i] = basis vector with leading bit i
#
#     def insert(self, x):
#         for i in range(self.b.__len__() - 1, -1, -1):
#             if not (x >> i & 1): continue
#             if not self.b[i]: self.b[i] = x; return True
#             x ^= self.b[i]
#         return False  # x is linearly dependent (already in span)
#
#     def max_xor(self, cur=0):
#         for v in reversed(self.b):
#             cur = max(cur, cur ^ v)
#         return cur
#
# COMPLEXITY: O(log(max_val)) per insert and query.
# SPACE:      O(log(max_val)) — at most 60 basis vectors for 64-bit integers.
#
# KEY PROBLEMS:
#   CF 895C  — Maximum XOR Secondary                     [1900]
#   CF 1336F — Journey                                   [2200]  XOR on tree paths
#   CF 1101G — (Zero XOR Subset bases)                   [2400]  basis over GF(2)
#
# TRAINING:
#   DAY 1: Implement LinearBasis. Insert [3,5,6]; verify max_xor() = 7.
#   DAY 2: Solve CF 895C. Then extend to XOR on paths in a tree.
#   GOAL:  Recognize "maximize/count XOR of subset" → linear basis in < 1 min.
#
