# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║          §M0  GLOBAL PROBLEM-TYPE DECISION FLOWCHART                     ║
# ║          Use this FIRST when you read a new problem.                     ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STEP 1 — Read constraints first (before the problem body)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   n ≤ 10        → O(n!) — brute force / all permutations (Ch5)
#   n ≤ 20        → O(2ⁿ·n) — bitmask DP (Ch10)
#   n ≤ 400       → O(n³) — Floyd-Warshall, interval DP (Ch13, Ch7)
#   n ≤ 5000      → O(n²) — quadratic DP, brute force (Ch7)
#   n ≤ 10⁵       → O(n log n) — seg tree, sort, D&C (Ch9, Ch3)
#   n ≤ 10⁶       → O(n) or O(n log n) — BFS/DFS, linear sieve (Ch12, Ch21)
#   n ≤ 10¹⁸      → O(log n) or O(√n) — fast exp, primality (Ch21)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STEP 2 — Identify the problem TYPE
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
#   │ "find minimum/maximum X such that condition holds"                       │
#   │   → BINARY SEARCH ON ANSWER  (Ch3) — write feasible(mid) predicate      │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "count/enumerate all subsets/permutations"                               │
#   │   n ≤ 20   → BITMASK DP (Ch10)                                          │
#   │   n ≤ 8    → BRUTE FORCE / BACKTRACK (Ch5)                              │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "range query: sum / min / max over [l..r]"                               │
#   │   static, idempotent (min/max/GCD)  → SPARSE TABLE O(1)/query (BonusA)  │
#   │   point updates                     → BIT/Fenwick O(log n) (Ch9)        │
#   │   range updates + range queries     → LAZY SEG TREE O(log n) (Ch9)      │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "graph problem"                                                          │
#   │   shortest path, non-negative weights → DIJKSTRA (Ch13)                 │
#   │   shortest path, negative weights    → BELLMAN-FORD (Ch13)              │
#   │   shortest path, unit weights        → BFS (Ch12)                       │
#   │   all-pairs shortest paths           → FLOYD-WARSHALL (Ch13)            │
#   │   connectivity / cycle detection     → DSU or DFS (Ch15, Ch12)          │
#   │   minimum spanning tree              → KRUSKAL / PRIM (Ch15)            │
#   │   DAG dependencies / ordering        → TOPOLOGICAL SORT (Ch16)          │
#   │   strongly connected components      → KOSARAJU / TARJAN (Ch17)         │
#   │   max flow / bipartite matching      → DINIC / HOPCROFT-KARP (Ch19)     │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "sequence / subarray"                                                    │
#   │   max subarray sum                  → KADANE'S O(n) (Ch7 / Ch8)        │
#   │   count pairs / inversions          → BIT + coord compress (Ch9/Ch3)    │
#   │   longest increasing subsequence   → PATIENCE SORT O(n log n) (Ch7)    │
#   │   fixed-size window stat            → SLIDING WINDOW / DEQUE (Ch8)      │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "tree problem"                                                           │
#   │   path queries / updates on tree   → HLD + seg tree (Ch18)              │
#   │   lowest common ancestor           → BINARY LIFTING (Ch14)              │
#   │   subtree queries                  → EULER TOUR + BIT (Ch14)            │
#   │   centroid-based problems          → CENTROID DECOMP (Ch18)             │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "string problem"                                                         │
#   │   single pattern match             → KMP or Z-FUNCTION (Ch26)           │
#   │   multi-pattern match              → AHO-CORASICK (Ch28)                │
#   │   substring equality               → STRING HASHING (Ch26)              │
#   │   longest palindrome               → MANACHER'S (BonusG)                │
#   │   lexicographic / suffix queries   → SUFFIX ARRAY (Ch28)                │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "counting / combinatorics"                                               │
#   │   nCr mod p                        → PRECOMPUTED FACTORIALS (Ch22)      │
#   │   count integers [L,R] with prop   → DIGIT DP (Ch27)                    │
#   │   count subsets with sum X         → SOS DP (Ch27)                      │
#   │   expected value / probability     → LINEARITY OF EXPECTATION (Ch24)    │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "game / nim"                                                             │
#   │   impartial game, last move wins   → GRUNDY / SPRAGUE (Ch25)            │
#   │   nim sum                          → XOR of pile sizes (Ch25)           │
#   ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
#   │ "math / number theory"                                                   │
#   │   primes up to n                   → SIEVE OF ERATOSTHENES (Ch21)       │
#   │   GCD, divisors, totient           → EULER'S PHI, EXT-GCD (Ch21)        │
#   │   fast Fibonacci / recurrences     → MATRIX EXPONENTIATION (Ch23)       │
#   └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STEP 3 — If still stuck, ask these 4 questions in order:
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   Q1: What is the brute force? Write it. What is its complexity? What is slow?
#   Q2: Is there monotonicity? (sorted order, prefix, suffix, shrinkable window)
#       If yes → binary search or two pointers eliminates one dimension.
#   Q3: Is there overlapping subproblems? (same state reachable multiple ways)
#       If yes → DP. What is the state? What is the transition?
#   Q4: Is there a key algebraic property? (associativity → segtree; linearity →
#       prefix sum; exchange arg → greedy; XOR cancel → XOR basis)
#
# ▶ §4. GRAPH PROBLEM CLASSIFICATION FLOWCHART
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

#   Is there a CYCLE STRUCTURE?
#   ├── YES, directed → SCC + condensation. 2-SAT if yes/no variables.
#   ├── YES, undirected → bridges, articulation points, biconnected components.
#   └── NO (tree or DAG) →
#       ├── DAG: topological sort + DP on DAG.
#       └── Tree: DFS, LCA, HLD, centroid decomposition.
#
#   Is it a SHORTEST PATH problem?
#   ├── All weights = 1 → BFS, O(V+E).
#   ├── Weights = 0 or 1 → 0-1 BFS (deque), O(V+E).
#   ├── All weights ≥ 0 → Dijkstra, O((V+E)log V).
#   ├── Negative weights exist → Bellman-Ford, O(VE).
#   └── All-pairs, n ≤ 500 → Floyd-Warshall, O(V³).
#
#   Is it a CONNECTIVITY problem?
#   ├── Static connectivity → Union-Find, O(α(n)) per operation.
#   ├── Online insertion → Union-Find.
#   ├── Online deletion → Use offline + reverse-time Union-Find.
#   └── Is the graph bipartite? → BFS 2-coloring.
#
#   Is it a FLOW / MATCHING problem?
#   ├── Max bipartite matching → Hopcroft-Karp, O(E√V).
#   ├── Max flow → Dinic's algorithm, O(V²E) or O(E√V) for unit capacities.
#   └── Min cut → equivalent to max flow by Max-Flow-Min-Cut theorem.

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ §5. THE UPSOLVING METHODOLOGY — HOW EXPERTS LEARN FROM CONTESTS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║                   CONTEST TIMER PROTOCOL  (2-hour round)                ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 0–5: TRIAGE  (read every problem, code nothing)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → Read ALL problems in order, 30–60 sec each.
#   → Tag each as: A=trivial / B=easy / C=medium / D=hard / E=skip
#   → Write constraints: n=?, q=?, limits. Map to complexity tier immediately.
#   → DO NOT open your editor yet. No code until you have read every problem.
#   → Goal: know which problem you solve first, second, third.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 5–20: SOLVE PROBLEM A (target: AC by minute 15)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → Paste contest header (0A template). Think 2 min before typing.
#   → Verify on examples manually. Submit.
#   → If WA: read problem statement again word-by-word. Most A WAs are misreads.
#   → If not AC by minute 20: skip A, move to B, return later.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 20–60: SOLVE PROBLEM B (target: AC by minute 50)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → Write brute force first in your head. What is slow? What is the structure?
#   → Think on paper (sketch), not in code. Code is for implementation, not design.
#   → After AC on B: quick scan on C before committing to it.
#   → If stuck at minute 40: write a partial solution, submit for early penalty
#     avoidance (in CF scoring, first WA penalty < never submitting).
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 60–100: SOLVE PROBLEM C (target: AC by minute 90)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → Apply the 4-question framework (Step 3 of global flowchart above).
#   → After 20 minutes stuck: write down what you know and what you don't.
#     Often writing it forces the key observation.
#   → Implement cleanly. A fast-and-buggy solution is slower than a slow one.
#   → If WA: add asserts, print intermediate state on examples.
#     Never guess-and-check. Understand the bug before resubmitting.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 100–115: PROBLEM D (or strengthen C if not AC)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → If C is AC: start D. Read, apply flowchart, think 10 min.
#     If no idea in 10 min → let it go and optimise lower problems.
#   → If C is NOT AC: return to C. One more WA submit is fine; two blind
#     guesses waste penalty and attention. Understand the bug.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MINUTES 115–120: FINAL SWEEP
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   → Submit any partial solutions that are at least correct on examples.
#   → Double-check problem constraints: did you handle T test cases? Edge n=1?
#   → Never submit a solution you haven't tested on the sample cases.
#   → Do NOT start a new approach with < 5 minutes left.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# MENTAL RULES FOR DURING-CONTEST
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   Rule 1: Penalty is time, not WA. One more WA with 5 min left costs you
#           more than it saves. Verify before submitting.
#   Rule 2: "Thinking faster" is not the goal. Choosing the right algorithm
#           in 3 minutes beats coding the wrong one for 40 minutes.
#   Rule 3: If you've coded for 30+ minutes and it's not working, stop.
#           Re-read the problem. The bug is usually conceptual, not syntactic.
#   Rule 4: Track time explicitly. Set a timer for each problem. The timer
#           overrides your feeling of "almost done."
#   Rule 5: Problems A and B are the rating floor. Missing them costs rating.
#           Never skip A/B to chase C before they're AC.
#
# AFTER CONTEST (MANDATORY FOR IMPROVEMENT):
#   Step 1: Try every unsolved problem for 30-60 more minutes. Fresh eyes help.
# • Step 2: Read editorial.
# • Don't just skim — understand EVERY step.
# • Step 3: IMPLEMENT the solution yourself from scratch (don't copy).
# • Step 4: Test against the examples AND your own edge cases.
# • Step 5: Document the PATTERN in your notes.
# • What was the key insight?.
#
# MISTAKE LOG (keep this):
#   For every WA, note: what was wrong? What did you miss?
#   Categories: wrong algorithm choice, off-by-one, overflow, wrong edge case,
#               wrong formula, misread problem. Track which category you fail most.
#
# THE LEARNING CURVE:
# • 0-100 problems: Basics.
# • Every problem teaches a new idea.
# • 100-300 problems: Pattern recognition improves dramatically.
# • 300-1000 problems: Speed improves.
# • Standard problems feel automatic.
#   1000+ problems: Intuition for novel problems. Creative solutions emerge.
#   There are no shortcuts. Volume × quality of upsolving = rating gain.
#
# THE 5-MINUTE PROBLEM ANALYSIS FRAMEWORK (use this EVERY contest):

# • n = ?   q = ?   T = ?   sum of n = ?   value range = ?
# • Map constraints to complexity tier BEFORE reading the problem body.
# • "n ≤ 10^5" → you need O(n log n) or better.
# "n ≤ 20" → bitmask DP or backtracking.

# • Is it: Construction? Optimization? Counting? Yes/No? Decision?
#   Construction: build an example satisfying conditions.
# • Optimization: maximize or minimize some quantity.
# Counting: count valid configurations.
# Decision: can we achieve X?

# Sorting → greedy probably works. What sort key?
# "Range queries" → BIT or Segment Tree.
# "Shortest path" → Dijkstra / BFS.
# "Trees" → DFS, LCA, tree DP.
# • "Intervals" → sort by endpoint, sweep line.
# • "Subsequences" → DP (LIS, LCS, knapsack).
# • "Counts mod p" → combinatorics (nCr, inclusion-exclusion).
# • "Large n, dependency" → linear recurrence → matrix exponentiation.

# Always know the brute force solution.
# It gives you: test cases, sanity checks, partial score on systems.
# Then ask: "What's slow? Can I precompute it? Can I find a monotone structure?"

# Reduce O(n²) to O(n log n) with a data structure or cleverness.
# Reduce O(n log n) to O(n) with a mathematical insight.
# If stuck: try small cases, look for patterns, think about the inverse problem.

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ STEP 6: MASTER PATTERN RECOGNITION TABLE
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ n (constraint) │ Maximum viable complexity                               │
# ├────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
# │ n ≤ 10         │ O(n!) — all permutations, brute force                   │
# │ n ≤ 18-20      │ O(2^n·n) — bitmask DP                                   │
# │ n ≤ 400        │ O(n^3) — Floyd-Warshall, interval DP                    │
# │ n ≤ 5,000      │ O(n^2) — quadratic DP, brute force                      │
# │ n ≤ 10^5       │ O(n log n) — segment tree, sorting, divide & conquer    │
# │ n ≤ 10^6       │ O(n log n) or O(n) — BFS/DFS, linear sieve              │
# │ n ≤ 10^7       │ O(n) only — prefix sums, linear scan                    │
# │ n ≤ 10^18      │ O(log n) or O(√n) — fast exp, trial division            │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

# ARRAYS & SEQUENCES:
#   subarray sum = k                     → prefix sums + hashmap
#   max subarray sum                     → Kadane's O(n)
#   count subarrays with property        → two pointers (if monotone) / D&C
#   longest increasing subsequence       → patience sort DP O(n log n)
#   count inversions                     → merge sort or BIT
#   range sum, point update              → BIT (Fenwick tree)
#   range sum, range update              → lazy segment tree
#   range min/max, no update             → sparse table O(1) query
#   range min/max with update            → segment tree
#   nearest greater element              → monotone stack
#   histogram max rectangle              → monotone stack
#   k-th smallest in range [l,r]         → persistent segment tree
#
# STRINGS:
#   single pattern matching              → KMP or Z-function
#   multiple pattern matching            → Aho-Corasick
#   substring equality check             → string hashing
#   longest palindromic substring        → Manacher's O(n)
#   count distinct substrings            → suffix array + LCP
#   string DP (avoid pattern)            → Aho-Corasick automaton DP
#   string matching with wildcards       → FFT convolution
#
# GRAPHS:
#   shortest path, non-negative weights  → Dijkstra O((V+E) log V)
#   shortest path, negative weights      → Bellman-Ford O(VE)
#   shortest path, all pairs             → Floyd-Warshall O(V^3)
#   shortest path, unit weights          → BFS O(V+E)
#   shortest path, 0-1 weights           → 0-1 BFS (deque) O(V+E)
#   MST                                  → Kruskal or Prim
#   SCC                                  → Kosaraju's or Tarjan's
#   2-SAT                                → SCC + implication graph
#   max flow                             → Dinic's O(V^2·E)
#   bipartite matching                   → Hopcroft-Karp or max flow
#   bridges / articulation points        → Tarjan's bridge finding
#
# TREES:
#   LCA (lowest common ancestor)         → binary lifting O(n log n / log n)
#   path query on tree                   → HLD + segment tree
#   subtree query / update               → Euler tour + BIT/seg tree
#   tree distance queries                → LCA + depth
#   k-th ancestor                        → binary lifting
#   distinct values in subtree           → small-to-large merging O(n log n)
#   re-rooting DP                        → two DFS (down-up technique)
#
# DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING:
#   count paths in grid                  → 2D DP
#   0/1 knapsack                         → DP O(nW)
#   interval / range DP                  → dp[l][r] = f(dp[l][k], dp[k][r])
#   DP on subsets (n ≤ 20)              → bitmask DP
#   sum of all subsets                   → SOS DP O(n·2^n)
#   DP transition is a line (CHT form)   → Convex Hull Trick / Li Chao Tree
#   DP with monotone opt (k-partition)   → D&C DP optimization
#   count integers in [L,R] with prop   → Digit DP
#   matrix recurrence                    → matrix exponentiation
#
# MATH:
#   large power mod p                    → fast exponentiation O(log n)
#   modular inverse                      → Fermat: a^(p-2)%p, or ext-GCD
#   all primes up to n                   → linear sieve or Eratosthenes
#   combinatorics nCr mod p              → precompute factorials + inv_fact
#   XOR sum over all subsets             → Walsh-Hadamard transform
#   polynomial multiplication            → FFT / NTT

# STRUCTURE 1: "minimum maximum" / "maximum minimum" / "at most k"
#   → BINARY SEARCH ON ANSWER
#   → lo, hi = bounds; while lo<hi: mid=(lo+hi)//2; if feasible(mid): hi=mid else lo=mid+1
#
# STRUCTURE 2: "path queries on tree"
#   → HLD + segment tree, OR centroid decomposition
#
# STRUCTURE 3: "count subarrays/substrings with property X"
#   → prefix sums (additive), two pointers (monotone), divide & conquer (rest)
#
# STRUCTURE 4: "maximize over subset (n ≤ 20)"
#   → bitmask DP
#
# STRUCTURE 5: "queries on static array"
#   → sparse table if idempotent (RMQ); segment tree otherwise
#
# STRUCTURE 6: "count integers in [L,R] with digit property"
#   → Digit DP: state = (pos, tight, leading_zero, accumulated_property)
#
# STRUCTURE 7: "DP transitions look like: dp[j] + a[j]*x[i] + b[j]"
#   → Convex Hull Trick (monotone) or Li Chao Tree (arbitrary)
#
# STRUCTURE 8: "count strings of length L not containing pattern P"
#   → Aho-Corasick automaton + DP on states

# Tag: "constructive algorithms"
#   → Build greedily. What invariant must the answer satisfy?
#   → n often small enough for O(n^2). Try small cases for the pattern.
#
# Tag: "interactive"
#   → Binary search on answer space. Budget queries carefully.
#   → Queries typically O(log n) or O(n).
#
# Tag: "math"
#   → Compute small cases (n=1,2,3,4,5), find pattern, check OEIS.
#   → Modular arithmetic: precompute factorials + inverses.
#
# Tag: "two pointers"
#   → Both pointers advance forward. What invariant holds when each pointer moves?
#
# Tag: "flows"
#   → Source on "supply", sink on "demand". Min cut = max flow (König, Hall).
#   → Feasibility: does max flow equal total supply?
#
# Tag: "probabilities"
#   → E[X+Y] = E[X]+E[Y] always (linearity of expectation).
#   → DP over states: dp[state] = expected cost/time to reach goal.
#
# Tag: "divide and conquer"
#   → Split at midpoint, solve halves, merge O(n) → O(n log n) total.
#   → OR: binary search on answer + feasibility check.
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║            SECTION M1.5 — PROBLEM → ALGORITHM DECISION TREES             ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# HOW TO USE THESE TREES:
# • Read each question top-down.
# • The first "leaf" that matches your problem tells you the algorithm.
# • The complexity estimate helps you verify against the constraint table
#   before writing a single line of code.
#
#   Rating impact: mastering this alone is worth ~200 CF rating points because
#   it eliminates the "what do I even try?" paralysis at the start of every
#   problem.  Pattern recognition at read-time is the #1 separator between
#   1600 and 2200 players.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 1 — ARRAY / SEQUENCE PROBLEMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Is the problem about a CONTIGUOUS subarray?
#   │
#   ├─ Sum / average / count?
#   │    ├─ Static (no updates)?          → PREFIX SUM     O(1)/query
#   │    ├─ Point updates?                → BIT (Fenwick)  O(log n)/op
#   │    └─ Range updates + range query?  → LAZY SEG TREE  O(log n)/op
#   │
#   ├─ Maximum subarray sum?              → KADANE'S       O(n)
#   │
#   ├─ Maximum / minimum in range?
#   │    ├─ No updates?                   → SPARSE TABLE   O(1)/query
#   │    └─ With point updates?           → SEGMENT TREE   O(log n)/op
#   │
#   ├─ Fixed-length window (size k)?      → SLIDING WINDOW / MONOTONE DEQUE  O(n)
#   │
#   └─ Variable-length window with
#      monotone property?                 → TWO POINTERS   O(n)
#
# Is the problem about the ENTIRE SEQUENCE (not just subarrays)?
#   │
#   ├─ Longest Increasing Subsequence?    → LIS patience sort  O(n log n)
#   ├─ Count inversions?                  → MERGE SORT / BIT   O(n log n)
#   ├─ K-th smallest / largest?           → QUICKSELECT (avg O(n)) / HEAP O(n log k)
#   ├─ Nearest greater/smaller element?  → MONOTONE STACK     O(n)
#   └─ Median after each insert?          → TWO HEAPS          O(log n)/insert
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 2 — GRAPH PROBLEMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# What kind of graph traversal / query?
#   │
#   ├─ REACHABILITY / CONNECTIVITY?
#   │    ├─ One-time check?               → DFS or BFS         O(V+E)
#   │    └─ Dynamic (edges added)?        → DSU / Union-Find   O(α(n))/op
#   │
#   ├─ SHORTEST PATH?
#   │    ├─ Unweighted?                   → BFS                O(V+E)
#   │    ├─ 0-1 weights?                  → 0-1 BFS (deque)    O(V+E)
#   │    ├─ Non-negative weights?         → DIJKSTRA           O((V+E) log V)
#   │    ├─ Negative weights (no neg cycle)? → BELLMAN-FORD    O(VE)
#   │    └─ All pairs?                    → FLOYD-WARSHALL     O(V³)
#   │
#   ├─ SPANNING TREE?
#   │    ├─ Minimum spanning tree?        → KRUSKAL / PRIM     O(E log E)
#   │    └─ All spanning trees / count?   → Kirchhoff's theorem
#   │
#   ├─ DIRECTED GRAPH STRUCTURE?
#   │    ├─ Topological order?            → KAHN'S BFS / DFS   O(V+E)
#   │    ├─ DAG shortest/longest path?    → TOPO SORT + DP     O(V+E)
#   │    ├─ Strongly connected components? → KOSARAJU'S        O(V+E)
#   │    └─ 2-SAT?                        → SCC on implication graph
#   │
#   ├─ FLOW / MATCHING?
#   │    ├─ Max flow?                     → DINIC'S            O(V² · E)
#   │    ├─ Bipartite matching?           → HOPCROFT-KARP / max flow
#   │    └─ Min cost max flow?            → MCMF (SPFA-based)
#   │
#   └─ TREE-SPECIFIC QUERIES?
#        ├─ LCA?                          → BINARY LIFTING      O(n log n / log n)
#        ├─ Path queries (sum/min/max)?   → HLD + SEG TREE      O(log² n)
#        ├─ Subtree queries?              → EULER TOUR + BIT    O(log n)
#        └─ Centre / decompose?           → CENTROID DECOMP     O(n log² n)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 3 — DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING PROBLEMS  [DP]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# What is the DP STATE SPACE?
#   │
#   ├─ Linear (1D): dp[i] depends on dp[i-1], dp[i-j]?
#   │    ├─ Recurrence known?             → BOTTOM-UP DP        O(n) or O(n·k)
#   │    └─ Transition is matrix-friendly? → MATRIX EXPONENT.   O(k³ log n)
#   │
#   ├─ 2D: dp[i][j] (grid / two sequences)?
#   │    ├─ Grid paths?                   → 2D GRID DP          O(n·m)
#   │    ├─ LCS / edit distance?          → 2D STRING DP        O(n·m)
#   │    └─ Knapsack variants?            → KNAPSACK DP         O(n·W)
#   │
#   ├─ INTERVAL: dp[l][r] over ranges?    → INTERVAL / RANGE DP O(n³)
#   │
#   ├─ BITMASK: subsets of small n (≤20)?
#   │    ├─ Standard bitmask DP?          → O(2ⁿ · n)
#   │    └─ Sum over subsets?             → SOS DP              O(n · 2ⁿ)
#   │
#   ├─ DIGIT: count integers [L,R] with property?  → DIGIT DP
#   │    State: (position, tight_flag, leading_zero, running_property)
#   │
#   ├─ TREE: dp on tree nodes?
#   │    ├─ Subtree-based?                → TREE DP (single DFS)
#   │    └─ Re-rooting needed?            → TWO-PASS DFS (down + up)
#   │
#   └─ DP TRANSITION OPTIMISATION?
#        ├─ Transition = min(dp[j] + m*x + b)?  → CONVEX HULL TRICK / LI CHAO
#        ├─ Monotone decision property?           → DIVIDE AND CONQUER DP
#        └─ k groups with cost function?          → ALIENS TRICK (λ-optimisation)
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 4 — STRING PROBLEMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# What is the primary string operation?
#   │
#   ├─ EXACT PATTERN MATCHING?
#   │    ├─ One pattern in one text?       → KMP or Z-FUNCTION   O(n+m)
#   │    └─ Many patterns in one text?    → AHO-CORASICK         O(n + Σ|pᵢ| + matches)
#   │
#   ├─ SUBSTRING EQUALITY / HASHING?
#   │    ├─ Check equality of substrings? → POLYNOMIAL HASHING   O(1)/query
#   │    └─ Distinct substrings count?    → SUFFIX ARRAY + LCP   O(n log n)
#   │
#   ├─ PALINDROME related?
#   │    ├─ Longest palindromic substr?   → MANACHER'S           O(n)
#   │    └─ Count palindromic substrings? → MANACHER'S or HASHING
#   │
#   ├─ PREFIX / DICTIONARY queries?       → TRIE                 O(|word|)/op
#   │    └─ XOR maximisation?             → BINARY TRIE          O(log maxval)
#   │
#   └─ STRING DP (count / recognise)?
#        ├─ Avoid one pattern?            → KMP automaton DP
#        └─ Avoid many patterns?          → AHO-CORASICK DP
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 5 — MATHEMATICS / COUNTING PROBLEMS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Is the answer a COUNT?
#   │
#   ├─ Integers in [L,R] with property?   → DIGIT DP
#   ├─ Subsets with property?             → INCLUSION-EXCLUSION or BITMASK DP
#   ├─ Arrangements / permutations?       → COMBINATORICS (nCr mod p)
#   ├─ Paths in a DAG?                    → DP on DAG
#   └─ Perfect matchings in bipartite?    → PERMANENT (small n) / MATRIX DET mod p
#
# Is the answer about PRIMES / DIVISORS?
#   │
#   ├─ All primes up to n?                → SIEVE                O(n log log n)
#   ├─ Factorisation of many numbers?     → SPF SIEVE + LOOKUP   O(n log log n) + O(log n)
#   ├─ GCD / LCM of many numbers?        → reduce(gcd, lst)
#   └─ Count divisors of n?              → factorise → prod(eᵢ+1)
#
# Is the answer MODULAR ARITHMETIC?
#   │
#   ├─ Large power?                       → pow(x, n, MOD)       O(log n)
#   ├─ Modular inverse?                   → pow(x, MOD-2, MOD)   (MOD prime)
#   └─ Combination nCr mod p?            → PRECOMPUTE fact, inv_fact
#
# Is it a GAME THEORY problem?
#   │
#   ├─ Nim or Nim-equivalent?             → XOR of pile sizes
#   ├─ Composite game (sum of games)?     → SPRAGUE-GRUNDY (XOR Grundy values)
#   └─ Staircase Nim?                     → XOR of odd-indexed piles
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 6 — GEOMETRIC / COMPUTATIONAL GEOMETRY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# What is the geometric query?
#   │
#   ├─ Convex hull of n points?           → GRAHAM SCAN / ANDREW'S MONOTONE  O(n log n)
#   ├─ Diameter of convex hull?           → ROTATING CALIPERS    O(n)
#   ├─ Area of polygon?                   → SHOELACE FORMULA     O(n)
#   ├─ Point inside polygon?              → RAY CASTING          O(n)
#   ├─ Segment intersection?              → CROSS PRODUCT check  O(1)
#   ├─ Closest pair of points?            → DIVIDE AND CONQUER   O(n log n)
#   ├─ Half-plane intersection?           → SORT + DEQUE         O(n log n)
#   └─ Lattice points inside polygon?     → PICK'S THEOREM: I = A - B/2 + 1
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 7 — "WHAT DATA STRUCTURE DO I NEED?"
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Need fast INSERT + DELETE + LOOKUP?
#   ├─ Ordered (rank/order queries)?      → SORTED LIST (SortedList / BIT + coord compress)
#   └─ Unordered?                         → HASH SET / dict
#
# Need STACK / QUEUE / DEQUE?
#   ├─ LIFO?                              → STACK (list with .append/.pop)
#   ├─ FIFO?                              → QUEUE (deque with .append/.popleft)
#   ├─ Monotone (prev/next greater)?      → MONOTONE STACK
#   └─ Sliding window min/max?            → MONOTONE DEQUE
#
# Need HEAP?
#   ├─ Always want the minimum?           → heapq (min-heap)
#   ├─ Always want the maximum?           → heapq with negated values
#   ├─ Two-sided (median)?                → TWO HEAPS (lo max-heap, hi min-heap)
#   └─ Priority with updates/deletes?     → LAZY DELETION heap
#
# Need RANGE QUERIES?
#   ├─ Point update + prefix query?       → BIT (Fenwick tree)
#   ├─ Point update + range query?        → SEGMENT TREE
#   ├─ Range update + range query?        → LAZY SEGMENT TREE
#   └─ Static range min/max?             → SPARSE TABLE O(1) query
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ TREE 8 — "IS BINARY SEARCH THE ANSWER?"  (a.k.a. the most underused trick)  [BS]

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Your problem says one of:
#   "minimum possible MAXIMUM of..."     → YES, binary search on answer
#   "maximum possible MINIMUM of..."     → YES, binary search on answer
#   "minimum X such that condition Y"    → YES, binary search on answer
#   "at most K operations to achieve X"  → YES, binary search on K
#
# The feasibility function check takes O(f(n)).
# Your total complexity becomes O(f(n) · log(answer_range)).
#
#   Aggressive cows (min dist ≥ d)?    → binary search on d,  feasible = greedy O(n)
#   Painter's partition (≤ k painters)? → binary search on max work, feasible = scan O(n)
#   Kth smallest in matrix?            → binary search on value, feasible = count O(n log n)
#   Cutting wood of height h?          → binary search on h, feasible = sum O(n)
#
# Template:
#   lo, hi = <lower_bound>, <upper_bound>
#   while lo < hi:
#       mid = (lo + hi) // 2
#       if feasible(mid):
#           hi = mid          # (or lo = mid+1 for maximum version)
#       else:
#           lo = mid + 1
#   answer = lo
#
