# │ STRING ALGORITHMS                                                                                │
# ├─────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
# │ String hashing (rolling)        │ O(n) build       │ O(n)       │ Birthday collision (use double) │
# │ Z-function                      │ O(n)             │ O(n)       │ Multi-pattern → Aho-Corasick   │
# │ KMP (failure function)          │ O(n + m)         │ O(m)       │ –                              │
# │ Manacher's (palindromes)        │ O(n)             │ O(n)       │ –                              │
# │ Aho-Corasick (multi-pattern)    │ O(n + Σ|pat|)    │ O(Σ|pat|·Σ)★│ Large alphabet → trie MLE   │
# │ Suffix array (SA-IS)            │ O(n)             │ O(n)       │ Complex implementation         │
# │ Suffix automaton                │ O(n)             │ O(n)       │ –                              │
# ├─────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
# │ MATH & NUMBER THEORY                                                                             │
# ├─────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┼────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
# │ Sieve of Eratosthenes           │ O(n log log n)   │ O(n)       │ n > 10^8 → MLE (use bitset)    │
# │ Linear sieve                    │ O(n)             │ O(n)       │ –                              │
# │ Fast exponentiation             │ O(log n)         │ O(1)       │ –                              │
# │ Extended GCD                    │ O(log n)         │ O(1)       │ –                              │
# │ Matrix exponentiation           │ O(k³ log n)      │ O(k²) ★   │ k > 100 → slow                 │
# │ FFT / NTT                       │ O(n log n)       │ O(n)       │ NTT requires prime mod         │
# │ Factorial precompute (nCr)      │ O(n) build       │ O(n)       │ n > MAXN → resize              │
# └─────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────┴────────────┴───────────────────────────────┘
#
#   † Use O(1) space by only keeping the last 1–2 states; only when values
#     don't need to be reconstructed.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# MLE SURVIVAL GUIDE — the most common space traps
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   Trap 1: Adjacency matrix for large graphs.
#             V=10^5 → V²=10^10 entries → instant MLE. Always use adjacency list.
#   Trap 2: 2D DP array when O(n²) is n=10^4 → 10^8 cells × 8 bytes = 800MB.
#             FIX: roll array to 1D if only last row is needed.
#   Trap 3: Sparse table on huge n. n=10^6, LOG=20 → 2×10^7 entries = 160MB.
#             FIX: acceptable; but don't allocate larger than needed.
#   Trap 4: Persistent seg tree overcount. Each update adds O(log n) nodes.
#             For n=10^5, q=10^5 → 10^5 × 17 = 1.7×10^6 nodes. Plan ahead.
#   Trap 5: Bitmask DP with n=25 → 2^25 = 3.3×10^7 states × 8 bytes = 267MB.
#             FIX: n ≤ 20 is safe; 20 < n ≤ 23 with small state values may work.
#   Trap 6: Recursive DFS on chain graph → call stack O(n) = 10^5 frames.
#             FIX: sys.setrecursionlimit(300000) or rewrite iteratively.
#

# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║                  SECTION M4 — RATING PROGRESSION GUIDE                   ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: < 1200  (Newcomer → Pupil boundary)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  Input/output mechanics, integer arithmetic, modular math,
#            sorting, linear scans, prefix sums.
#   PROBLEMS: Div.2 A, easy Div.2 B.
#   TYPICAL RATING-LIMITING MISTAKES at this level:
#     ✗ Misreading problem constraints (n vs 1..n indexing)
#     ✗ Using float for integer problems (precision errors)
#     ✗ Not handling T test cases (global state bleeds between cases)
#     ✗ print() inside loop instead of accumulating → TLE on heavy I/O
#   WHAT 1200 SEES THAT <1200 MISSES:
#     • The formula is in the constraint. "n ≤ 10^9" → O(1) or O(log n) only.
#     • Test cases share nothing. Re-initialise every variable each case.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: 50–100 Div.2 A problems. Solve in < 5 minutes each.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: 1200–1400  (Pupil → Specialist boundary)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  Two pointers, sliding window, basic greedy (proof not required),
#            binary search on sorted arrays, basic graph BFS/DFS.
#   PROBLEMS: Div.2 B, C.
#   TYPICAL RATING-LIMITING MISTAKES at this level:
#     ✗ Coding before thinking 10 minutes — WA from wrong approach
#     ✗ Not recognising "binary search on answer" pattern (≥ 30% of C problems)
#     ✗ Greedy guess without verifying on edge cases
#     ✗ BFS on a weighted graph (should be Dijkstra)
#   WHAT 1600 SEES THAT 1400 MISSES:
#     • Any "min of max" or "max of min" → binary search on answer instantly.
#     • Graph with "fewest steps" → BFS. Graph with "min cost" → Dijkstra.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: 100–200 problems. Upsolve every Div.2 D you fail.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: 1400–1600  (Specialist → Expert boundary)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  BIT/Fenwick tree, segment tree (point update), DP (knapsack, LIS,
#            coin change), Dijkstra, DSU, topological sort.
#   PROBLEMS: Div.2 C, D. Div.3 E.
#   TYPICAL RATING-LIMITING MISTAKES at this level:
#     ✗ Writing O(n²) DP when O(n log n) is needed (LIS without patience sort)
#     ✗ No memoisation → exponential recursion on overlapping subproblems
#     ✗ Using adjacency matrix for V = 10^5 → MLE
#     ✗ Forgetting to check for disconnected graph components
#   WHAT 1800 SEES THAT 1600 MISSES:
#     • "Range query + point update" → BIT. "Range query + range update" → lazy segtree.
#     • Bitmask DP activates for n ≤ 20 problems, not just "subset" keywords.
#     • Greedy only works after proving exchange argument; otherwise DP.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: 200+ problems. For every TLE: diagnose complexity first.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: 1600–1900  (Expert → Candidate Master boundary)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  Lazy segment tree, HLD, LCA, bitmask DP, digit DP, SCC, 2-SAT,
#            advanced DP (interval, tree DP), string hashing, KMP.
#   PROBLEMS: Div.2 D, E. Div.1 B.
#   TYPICAL RATING-LIMITING MISTAKES at this level:
#     ✗ Not reducing hard problems to known structure
#       (e.g., "assign values to satisfy AND" → 2-SAT)
#     ✗ Forgetting that SCC condensation turns a directed graph into a DAG
#     ✗ Lazy segtree push_down missing → subtle wrong answers on range updates
#     ✗ Tree DP re-rooting missing the "up" DFS pass
#   WHAT 2000 SEES THAT 1800 MISSES:
#     • Problem reduction: hard problem → classical problem in disguise.
#     • "Connectivity on intervals" or "2-coloring with constraints" → 2-SAT.
#     • Offline processing: sort queries, answer monotonically, avoid recomputation.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: Virtual contests 3×/week. Read every editorial, implement all.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: 1900–2200  (Candidate Master → Master boundary)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  Centroid decomp, persistent segtree, CHT, D&C DP, FFT/NTT,
#            Aho-Corasick, suffix arrays, max flow, min-cost flow.
#   PROBLEMS: Div.1 B, C.
#   TYPICAL RATING-LIMITING MISTAKES at this level:
#     ✗ Implementing wrong variant of CHT (monotone vs Li Chao Tree)
#     ✗ Confusing suffix array with suffix automaton — different use cases
#     ✗ Building Aho-Corasick incorrectly (fail link != parent link)
#     ✗ Max flow wrong edge capacity (capacity ≠ 0 for reverse edges if needed)
#   WHAT 2400 SEES THAT 2000 MISSES:
#     • Original algebraic observation specific to the problem.
#     • Offline + divide & conquer to avoid heavy data structure.
#     • Generating function / combinatorial identity as a shortcut.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: Div.1 A–C in every round. Solve at least 1 Div.1 D per week.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ◈ RATING BAND: 2200+  (Master → Grandmaster)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   MASTER:  Novel constructions, randomised algorithms, advanced math
#            (Burnside, Möbius inversion, Berlekamp-Massey, Treap, HLPP flow).
#   FOCUS:   Original insight. Templates help but are never sufficient.
#   WHAT SEPARATES GM FROM MASTER:
#     • Speed: GMs need < 15 min on problems Masters solve in 45 min.
#     • Reading the problem once → immediately know the technique.
#     • Constructive proofs: can prove the greedy / construction is optimal.
#   PRACTICE TARGET: Div.1 A–D. Upsolve E. Read IOI/ICPC editorial archives.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# UNIVERSAL ADVICE (every level)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   • Upsolve:   Solve every problem you failed during the contest, after.
#   • Implement: Read editorial → close it → implement from memory.
#   • Mistake log: Track WA causes. The pattern reveals your specific gap.
#   • Participate live: Contest pressure is a separate trainable skill.
#   • Don't skip levels: A 1400 trying to learn FFT wastes time on sugar
#     while still making 1200-level mistakes in every round.
#
# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║              SECTION M3 — BRUTE → OPTIMAL TRANSITION ATLAS               ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# PHILOSOPHY:
#   Every optimal algorithm was once a brute force with a key observation.
#   Knowing the full chain — Brute → Better → Best — lets you arrive at the
#   optimal idea incrementally instead of all at once.  Under contest pressure,
#   this incremental view saves you.
#
#   For each problem type below, the chain is always the same pattern:
#     Brute  = correct but too slow
#     Better = eliminate one nested loop / redundant recomputation
#     Best   = exploit monotonicity / precomputation / algebraic structure
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Level         │ Approach                                │ Complexity     │
# ├───────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────┤
# │ Brute         │ Recompute sum(a[l..r]) each query       │ O(n) / query   │
# │ Better        │ Prefix sum array, no updates            │ O(1) / query   │
# │ Best          │ BIT (Fenwick) with point updates        │ O(log n) / op  │
# │ Best+         │ Lazy seg tree with range updates        │ O(log n) / op  │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: sum(a[l..r]) = pre[r] - pre[l-1].  One subtraction, no loop.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Try every pair (l, r), compute sum      │ O(n³)          │
# │ Better        │ Prefix sum: sum(l,r) = pre[r]-pre[l-1] │ O(n²)           │
# │ Best          │ Kadane's: extend or restart at each i  │ O(n)            │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (Kadane): if current_sum < 0, restarting from i is always
#   better than extending — a negative prefix never helps a future subarray.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Bubble sort (swap adjacent if wrong)    │ O(n²)          │
# │ Better        │ Merge sort (divide & conquer)           │ O(n log n)     │
# │ Best          │ Count sort (when values bounded by k)  │ O(n + k)        │
# │ Best (gen.)   │ Python sorted() / Timsort               │ O(n log n) fast│
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: comparison sort has Ω(n log n) lower bound.  Bypass it only
#   when value range k is small (count/radix sort).
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Linear scan                             │ O(n)           │
# │ Better        │ Binary search (bisect_left/right)       │ O(log n)       │
# │ Best          │ Binary search on ANSWER (not in array)  │ O(log R · f(n))│
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: anything with a monotone feasibility function can be binary-
#   searched.  This reduces "optimisation" to "decision".
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ All pairs (i,j), check property         │ O(n²)          │
# │ Better        │ Sort + two pointers (if sum ≤ or ≥)    │ O(n log n)      │
# │ Best          │ Prefix hash: count[K - a[i]] seen so far│ O(n)           │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: storing "complements seen so far" turns O(n²) into O(n).
#   Two pointers works when the condition is monotone (more/less as pointer moves).
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Generate all subsequences, check each   │ O(2ⁿ)          │
# │ Better        │ dp[i] = max(dp[j]+1) for j<i, a[j]<a[i]│ O(n²)           │
# │ Best          │ Patience sort: maintain tails with bisect│ O(n log n)    │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: only the SMALLEST tail of each length matters.  Replacing
#   a tail never hurts future extensions (greedy exchange argument).
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Scan [l..r] every query                 │ O(n) / query   │
# │ Better        │ Segment tree                            │ O(log n) / quer│
# │ Best (static) │ Sparse table (idempotent: min/max/GCD)  │ O(1) / query   │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (sparse table): min(a[l..r]) = min(lookup[l][k], lookup[r-2ᵏ+1][k])
#   where k = floor(log2(r-l+1)).  Overlapping intervals are fine for idempotent ops.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Try all paths (DFS exhaustive)          │ O(V!)          │
# │ Better        │ Bellman-Ford (general weights)          │ O(VE)          │
# │ Better        │ BFS (unit weights only)                 │ O(V+E)         │
# │ Best          │ Dijkstra + min-heap (non-neg weights)   │ O((V+E) log V) │
# │ Best (dense)  │ Floyd-Warshall (all pairs)              │ O(V³)          │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (Dijkstra): once a node is "settled" (popped from heap), its
#   shortest distance is final — because all future paths through it are longer
#   (non-negative weights guarantee this).
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Try all spanning trees, pick lightest   │ O(2^E)         │
# │ Better        │ Prim's (dense graphs, adjacency matrix) │ O(V²)          │
# │ Best          │ Kruskal (sort edges + DSU)              │ O(E log E)     │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# • KEY OBSERVATION (Kruskal / cut property): the lightest edge crossing any cut always belongs to some MST.
# • So greedily adding the cheapest edge that joins two different components is always safe.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ BFS/DFS from each node                  │ O(V(V+E))      │
# │ Better        │ Single BFS/DFS over entire graph        │ O(V+E)         │
# │ Best (dynamic)│ DSU with path compression + union rank  │ O(α(n)) ≈ O(1) │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (DSU): path compression ensures that repeated find() calls
#   amortize to near-O(1).  Use DSU any time edges are added incrementally.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ All pairs (i,j) with i<j, a[i]>a[j]    │ O(n²)           │
# │ Better        │ Merge sort (count during merge step)    │ O(n log n)     │
# │ Best          │ BIT on coordinate-compressed values     │ O(n log n)     │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: during merge sort, when we pick from the RIGHT half, all
#   remaining elements in the LEFT half are greater → batch count inversions.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ All 2ⁿ subsets                          │ O(2ⁿ)          │
# │ Better        │ Meet in the middle (n ≤ 40)             │ O(2^(n/2) log n│
# │ Best          │ 0/1 knapsack DP: dp[w]                  │ O(n · W)       │
# │ Best (unbound)│ Unbounded knapsack: iterate w inner     │ O(n · W)       │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: optimal substructure — "best selection for weight w using
#   first i items" depends only on "weight w-wᵢ using first i-1 items."
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Try pattern at every text position      │ O(n · m)       │
# │ Better        │ Z-function or KMP failure function      │ O(n + m)       │
# │ Best (many P) │ Aho-Corasick automaton                  │ O(n + Σ|Pᵢ|)   │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (KMP): when a mismatch occurs, the failure function tells you
#   the longest proper prefix that is also a suffix — skip directly there.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Compare characters one by one           │ O(min(len_a, le│
# │ Better        │ Precompute suffix hash + pow table      │ O(1) / query   │
# │ Best          │ Double hash (two mod values)            │ O(1) / query, ≈│
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: h(s[l..r]) = (h[r+1] - h[l]*p^(r-l+1)) % mod.
#   Equal hash ≈ equal string.  Use two mods to reduce collision probability.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Iterate n steps                         │ O(n)           │
# │ Better        │ Memoised recursion (still O(n))         │ O(n)           │
# │ Best          │ Matrix exponentiation                   │ O(k³ log n)    │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# • KEY OBSERVATION: [F(n+1), F(n)] = [[1,1],[1,0]]^n · [F(1), F(0)].
#   Any linear recurrence of order k has a k×k transition matrix.
# • Fast exponentiation reduces the exponent from n to log n.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Factorize each number                   │ O(n · √n)      │
# │ Better        │ GCD via Euclidean algorithm             │ O(n · log(max))│
# │ Best          │ Sparse table of GCDs (idempotent)       │ O(n log n) buil│
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: GCD is idempotent (GCD(a,a)=a), so sparse table applies.
#   range GCD query becomes O(1) with O(n log n) preprocessing.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Try all permutations, check validity    │ O(V! · E)      │
# │ Better        │ DFS with post-order stack               │ O(V+E)         │
# │ Best          │ Kahn's BFS (in-degree decrement)        │ O(V+E)         │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: a node is "ready" when all its prerequisites are done
#   (in-degree = 0).  Kahn's processes exactly these nodes — no backtracking.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ All O(n²) subarrays, count distinct     │ O(n³)          │
# │ Better        │ Sliding window + hashmap                │ O(n²) worst    │
# │ Best          │ f(≤k) - f(≤k-1)  (atMost trick)        │ O(n)            │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: "exactly k" = "at most k" - "at most k-1".
#   "at most k distinct" is solvable in O(n) with a two-pointer window.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ All O(n²) pairs, compute XOR            │ O(n²)          │
# │ Better        │ XOR basis (linear basis) for max XOR    │ O(n · 30)      │
# │ Best          │ Binary Trie: for each element, greedily │ O(n · 30)      │
# │               │ pick opposite bit at each level         │                │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: to maximise a XOR b, for each bit (MSB first) try to set it
#   to 1.  This is a greedy that binary trie enables efficiently.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ Process each query naively              │ O(n) / query   │
# │ Better        │ Sort queries by right endpoint (offline)│ O((n+q) log n) │
# │ Best          │ Mo's algorithm (block decomposition)    │ O((n+q)√n)     │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION (Mo's): sort queries by (block(l), r), then add/remove one
#   element at a time.  Total pointer movement is O((n+q)√n) by block analysis.
#
# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ Brute         │ dp[i] = min over all j of dp[j]+cost(j,i)│ O(n²)         │
# │ Better        │ Recognise cost = m[j]*x[i]+b[j] form   │ O(n log n) (Li C│
# │ Best          │ Monotone slopes + queries → deque CHT   │ O(n)           │
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
# KEY OBSERVATION: when DP transitions form a family of lines, the minimum over
#   all lines at each query point traces the lower convex hull.
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶ THE META-PATTERN (applies to ALL of the above)
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Brute → Better: find REPEATED WORK and precompute or cache it.

#   Better → Best:   find MONOTONE STRUCTURE and exploit it greedily or
#                    with a specialised data structure.
#
# At every step, ask:
#   "What am I recomputing that I already know?"  → eliminate with precomputation
#   "What constraint is monotone here?"           → exploit with binary search / deque / CHT
#   "What invariant can I maintain cheaply?"      → exploit with stack/heap/trie
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ▶
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
# ║                   THE MASTER ALGORITHM SELECTION GUIDE                   ║
# ╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# │ CONSTRAINT          │ COMPLEXITY ALLOWED       │ TYPICAL ALGORITHMS      │
# ├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
# │ n ≤ 10              │ Any                      │ Brute force             │
# │ n ≤ 20              │ O(2^n) or O(n!)          │ Bitmask DP, backtracking│
# │ n ≤ 40              │ O(2^(n/2))               │ Meet in the middle      │
# │ n ≤ 100             │ O(n³)                    │ Floyd-Warshall, cubic DP│
# │ n ≤ 500             │ O(n³) tight              │ Floyd-Warshall, interval│
# │ n ≤ 3000            │ O(n²)                    │ 2D DP, O(n²) graph algor│
