# 🧠 MENTAL MODEL
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   "String algorithms = preprocessing the string to answer queries in O(1) or O(log n)."
# • Hashing: map a string to a number.
# • Two strings equal ↔ hashes equal (with high prob).
# • Z-array: Z[i] = length of longest substring starting from i that matches a prefix.
# • KMP: failure function = longest proper prefix-suffix.
# • Enables O(n+m) pattern matching.
#   Trie: prefix tree — O(length) insert/search, used for prefix queries.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Preprocess the string once (KMP / Z / hash) → answer queries in O(n+m)
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to think"
#   - "visualize"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Trying to code without a clear mental model → wrong implementation
#   ✗ Mental model doesn't match actual algorithm → subtle bugs
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Count the dominant operations in the brute-force approach
#   2. Identify which loop or recursion is the bottleneck
#   3. Find a structure or property that eliminates that bottleneck
#   → Express the improved complexity in Big-O; verify it fits n ≤ 10^6 in 2 s
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 HOW TO THINK — PATTERN RECOGNITION SIGNALS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#   ► "find all occurrences of pattern P in text T"           → KMP (O(n+m))
#
#   ► "compare substrings in O(1)"                           → polynomial hashing
#
#   ► "count distinct substrings"                            → suffix array
#
#   ► "longest repeated substring"                           → suffix array + LCP array
#
#   ► "words with same prefix grouped"                       → Trie
#
#   ► "does string s have s itself as a period?"              → KMP failure function
#
#   ► "palindrome queries"                                    → Manacher's algorithm
#
#   ► "string compression / periods"                         → Z-algorithm or KMP

# ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
# └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
#
#   ✗  Checking if P is a substring of T with T.find(P) in Python.
#       O(nm) worst case — TLE for n=10^5, m=10^5.
#
#   ✓  KMP: O(n+m) preprocessing + matching. Or Z-function approach.
#
#   ✗  String hashing with single base/mod → hash collisions cause WA.
#
#   ✓  Double hashing: use two different (base, mod) pairs → collision prob ≈ 1/10^18.
#
#   ✗  Suffix array built naively in O(n²) or O(n² log n).
#
#   ✓  O(n log n) suffix array using comparison sort on pairs. Or O(n) with SA-IS.
#       For CP, O(n log n) is usually sufficient.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Z[i]=longest match of s[i:] with prefix of s; KMP failure[i]=longest proper border of s[:i+1]
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "how to approach"
#   - "strategy"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Starting with complex algorithm when simple O(n²) passes within time limit
#   ✗ Not checking if brute force is fast enough before optimizing
#
#
# 🧠 THINKING:
#   1. Single pattern in text? → KMP / Z-function O(n + m)
#   2. Many patterns simultaneously? → Aho-Corasick O(n + Σ|patterns| + matches)
#   3. Substring structure / longest repeated? → Suffix array + LCP array
#   → KMP for one pattern; Aho-Corasick for many; suffix array for substring queries
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
