# §1. WHY PYTHON IS SLOW AND WHAT TO DO ABOUT IT

# Python is ~50-100x slower than C++ for tight loops. On Codeforces:
#   • Time limits are usually 2s (C++ baseline).
#   • Python gets 3x multiplier on most judges = 6s effective.
#   • PyPy3 is ~5-10x faster than CPython for tight loops.
#
# RULE OF THUMB for Python on CF:
#   Comfortable: ≤ 10^6 simple operations.
#   Risky:        10^6 to 10^7.
#   TLE almost certain: > 10^7 tight-loop operations in CPython.

# §2. THE INPUT BOTTLENECK

# input() in Python calls sys.stdin line by line with overhead.
# For problems with n=10^5 lines of input, this overhead is SIGNIFICANT.

# §3. RECURSION LIMITS

# • Python default recursion limit = 1000.
# • A DFS on n=10^5 nodes hits this.
# • Fix: sys.setrecursionlimit(300000) OR convert to iterative.
# • Iterative is ALWAYS safer — no risk of stack overflow on any judge.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   Python recursion limit is 1000 by default; iterative DFS with explicit stack avoids the limit
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
#   - "maximize the minimum"
#   - "minimum days"
#   - "fewest operations"
#   - "binary search on answer"
#   - "parametric search"
#
# ❌ MISTAKES:
#   ✗ Searching on array indices when you should search on answer values
#   ✗ check(mid) function is O(n²) making total O(n² log n) — optimize check() first
#
#
