# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 🧠 28A. AHO-CORASICK AUTOMATON  [STR]

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# ► Full annotated implementation in Chapter 26 Expansion.
#   Search: "Aho-Corasick" — includes trie build, BFS failure links, and search.
#
# Pattern: insert all patterns into trie, compute failure links via BFS (like KMP),
#          then scan text following automaton transitions.
# ⚡ Complexity: O(Σ|Pᵢ| + |text|).  Use for |patterns| up to 10⁵.
#
# ── THEORY: FAILURE LINK CONSTRUCTION ─────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Each trie node u has a failure link  fail[u]  pointing to the longest proper
# suffix of the string represented by u that is ALSO a prefix of some pattern
# (i.e., a node in the trie). This mirrors KMP's failure function but generalised
# to a trie of multiple patterns.
#
# Construction via BFS (level order guarantees fail[parent] is ready before child):
#   • Root's children: fail[child] = root.
#   • For every other node u with parent p and edge character c:
#       v = fail[p]           # follow parent's failure link
#       while v ≠ root and v has no child on c:
#           v = fail[v]       # keep following failure links
#       fail[u] = v.child[c] if v.child[c] ≠ u else root
#
# GOTO FUNCTION (automaton transition):
#   goto(u, c) = u.child[c]  if it exists,  else  goto(fail[u], c)
#   Precompute for all (node, char) pairs in BFS order so queries are O(1).
#   This turns the automaton into a proper DFA with |trie| × |alphabet| transitions.
#
# DICTIONARY LINK (output link):
#   dict_link[u] = nearest ancestor via failure links that is a terminal node.
#   Used to count ALL patterns ending at the current position, not just the longest.
#   Set dict_link[u] = fail[u] if fail[u] is terminal, else dict_link[fail[u]].
#
# ── THEORY: FAIL TREE AND DP ON AUTOMATON ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# The FAIL TREE is the tree formed by reversing failure links:
#   parent of u in fail tree = fail[u].
#
# KEY PROPERTY: DFS on the fail tree gives "string matching on automaton" DPs.
#   • Subtree of node u = all strings that have u's string as a suffix.
#   • After scanning text, the count of times pattern P is matched equals the
#     sum of visit counts over the entire subtree of P's terminal node in the fail tree.
#   → Use DFS on fail tree + prefix sums to answer "how many times does P appear"
#     for ALL patterns simultaneously in O(n + Σ|Pᵢ|) after one text scan.
#
# COMMON DP PATTERN (avoid a pattern in a constructed string):
#   State: (position_in_string, automaton_node) — automaton node tracks which
#          suffix of the string-so-far is a prefix of some pattern.
#   Transition: for each character c, move to goto(node, c). If the new node
#               (or any node reachable via dict_link) is a terminal, this state
#               is forbidden. Count strings of length L that never hit a terminal.
#   This DP runs in O(L × |trie| × |alphabet|) — feasible for L ≤ 10⁵ with
#   matrix exponentiation for very large L.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
