# META-SKILLS — The 20% that produces 80% of rating gains
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# ── HOW TO READ A COMPETITIVE PROGRAMMING PROBLEM ────────────────────────────
#
#   Step 1 — READ CONSTRAINTS FIRST, NOT THE STORY
#     n <= 20        -> Bitmask DP, exponential search, permutations
#     n <= 300       -> O(n^3) Floyd-Warshall, cubic DP, matrix chain
#     n <= 5000      -> O(n^2) two nested loops
#     n <= 10^5      -> O(n log n) or O(n): sort, BFS/DFS, segment tree
#     n <= 10^6      -> O(n) linear: sieve, Kadane, two pointers
#     n <= 10^18     -> O(log n) or O(sqrt n): binary search, math
#
#   Step 2 — IDENTIFY WHAT YOU ARE OPTIMIZING
#     "minimum number of X"  -> DP or greedy
#     "maximum number of X"  -> DP or greedy
#     "number of ways"       -> counting DP, combinatorics
#     "can we achieve X"     -> binary search on answer, flow, matching
#     "find any valid"       -> constructive, greedy
#
#   Step 3 — MAP THE STRUCTURE
#     Items with dependencies -> graph / topological sort
#     Items on a line / array -> DP, two pointers, binary search
#     Items on a tree         -> tree DP, HLD, LCA
#     Items on a grid         -> BFS/DFS, prefix sums, DP
#     Items chosen/not chosen -> knapsack, bitmask
#
#   Step 4 — CHECK THE TIME BUDGET
#     CF gives 2s for C++. Python gets ~3x multiplier -> treat as 6s.
#     Estimate: n=10^5 with O(n log n) = ~10^5 * 17 = ~2*10^6 ops -> safe
#     Estimate: n=10^5 with O(n^2) = 10^10 ops -> TLE, must optimize
#
# ── HOW TO RECOGNIZE DISGUISED PROBLEMS ──────────────────────────────────────
#
#   STORY                                     REAL PROBLEM
#   ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   "factory ships products to warehouses"  -> bipartite matching / flow
#   "employees assigned to tasks"           -> bipartite matching
#   "roads closed, find alternate route"    -> bridge detection / 2-edge-conn
#   "city built day by day, query connect"  -> DSU offline (reverse time)
#   "parent inherits resources from child"  -> tree DP
#   "can Alice guarantee a win?"            -> game theory (Grundy / Nim)
#   "split array into k parts, min max"    -> binary search on answer
#   "students and subjects, must assign"    -> bipartite matching
#   "bacteria doubles every hour, count"   -> matrix exponentiation
#   "number of valid bracket strings"      -> Catalan number
#   "number of paths in a city grid"       -> DP (unique paths)
#   "find the single different one"        -> XOR trick
#   "encode message, minimize total cost"  -> Huffman / greedy
#   "remove nodes to disconnect graph"     -> articulation points / cuts
#   "minimum edges to make graph connected"-> spanning tree / DSU
#   "sequence of operations, range apply"  -> lazy segment tree
#   "reachable states in a game"           -> BFS on state graph
#   "k-th element in merged sorted lists"  -> binary search on value
#   "sum of all subsets"                   -> SOS DP / bit contribution
#   "string with wildcards matches pattern"-> DP (like edit distance)
#   "paint fence with k colors, no adj same"-> DP (chromatic polynomial)
#
# ── TIME MANAGEMENT IN A 2-HOUR ROUND ────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   First 5 minutes: read ALL problems. Estimate which ones you can solve.
#   The easiest problem (A/B) is often worth 500 points and takes 5 minutes.
#   Don't fall in love with a hard problem if an easier one is unsolved.
#
#   Triage heuristic (Div2):
#     A:   solve immediately (<10 min). If taking >15 min, read again.
#     B:   solve within 20 min. Use brute force if n is small.
#     C:   spend 30-40 min. If no idea after 20 min, try D briefly.
#     D:   high-value. Don't guess randomly; think about structure.
#     E/F: only if A-D solved. Often requires insight, not implementation.
#
#   Rule: if stuck for >20 minutes with no progress, switch problems.
#         Come back with fresh eyes.
#
# ── WHEN YOUR SOLUTION GETS WRONG ANSWER ─────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. Check edge cases: n=1, n=0, all same values, sorted input, reverse sorted
#   2. Check overflow: Python doesn't overflow but check int sizes in formulas
#   3. Check off-by-one: array indices, loop bounds (< n or <= n?), 0-indexed vs 1-indexed
#   4. Check the wrong subtask: maybe you solved a simpler version
#   5. Re-read the problem: "at most" vs "exactly", "distinct" vs "any", 1-indexed queries
#   6. Print intermediate values on the failing case (use small custom test)
#   7. Write a brute force checker and stress test against your solution
#
# ── RATING IMPROVEMENT ROADMAP ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   < 1200:  Learn I/O, basic loops, if/else, arrays. Solve CF div2 A problems.
#   1200-1400: Sorting, greedy, prefix sums, basic DP. Solve div2 B-C.
#   1400-1600: BFS/DFS, binary search, complete search, two pointers.
#   1600-1800: Dijkstra, DSU, Kruskal, tree DP, segment tree basics.
#   1800-2000: Advanced graph (SCC, bridges), CHT, HLD, LCA.
#   2000-2200: Number theory, advanced DP, segment tree beats, flows.
#   2200+:     String algorithms, geometry, game theory, advanced DS.
#
#   Most important skill at every level: being able to PROVE your solution
#   is correct before submitting, not just "it looks right."
#
# ── THE MOST COMMON SOURCES OF WRONG ANSWER ──────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. Integer overflow / modular arithmetic mistakes     (30% of WA)
#   2. Off-by-one in binary search or loop bounds        (20% of WA)
#   3. Wrong edge case (n=1, empty input, all-same)      (15% of WA)
#   4. Misread problem (wrong constraint / output format) (15% of WA)
#   5. Greedy that's wrong (need DP instead)             (10% of WA)
#   6. Graph direction / undirected vs directed          (5% of WA)
#   7. Floating point comparison (use epsilon or avoid)  (5% of WA)
#
