# 26E. EXPRESSION PARSING — SHUNTING-YARD ALGORITHM

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ⚡ THEORY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# PROBLEM: Evaluate an arithmetic expression given as a string, e.g. "3+5*2-4/(2+0)".
# Handles: +, -, *, /, (, ) with standard precedence (* and / > + and -).
#
# APPROACHES:
# • Shunting-Yard Algorithm: Convert infix to Reverse Polish Notation (RPN), then
#       evaluate RPN
# • Two-stack approach.
# • Recursive Descent Parser: Parse grammar rules top-down.
#
# SHUNTING-YARD (Dijkstra, 1961):
# Two stacks: output queue (numbers + operators in RPN order) and operator stack.
# Rules:
#   - Number → push to output.
#   - Operator op → while stack top has ≥ precedence and is not '(': pop to output.
#                   Then push op to stack.
#   - '(' → push to stack.
#   - ')' → pop from stack to output until '(' is found. Discard both '(' and ')'.
# End: pop remaining operators to output.
#
# • PRECEDENCE: * and / have precedence
# • + and - have precedence
# • LEFT-ASSOCIATIVE: 3-2-1 = (3-2)-1 = 0 (not 3-(2-1)=2).
# • For left-associative, pop operators with ≥ precedence.
# • For right-associative (exponentiation), pop operators with > precedence only.
#
# DRY RUN — Parse "3+5*2":
#   Read 3: output=[3]
#   Read +: stack=[+], output=[3]
#   Read 5: output=[3,5]
#   Read *: prec(*)=2 > prec(+)=1, so don't pop. Push *. stack=[+,*], output=[3,5]
#   Read 2: output=[3,5,2]
#   End: pop * → output=[3,5,2,*], pop + → output=[3,5,2,*,+]
#   Evaluate RPN [3,5,2,*,+]: 5*2=10, 3+10=13 ✓
#

# ── eval_expression — inline ──
# Evaluate arithmetic expression string (digits and +-*/)
ops=[]
sorted_vals=[]
prec={"+":1,"-":1,"*":2,"/":2}
# _apply — expression evaluator helper; inlined into eval_expression above
