# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 THEORY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# • A STRING s is called a LYNDON WORD if it is STRICTLY SMALLER than all of its
#       proper suffixes (equivalently, strictly smaller than all of its rotations)
# • Examples: "a", "ab", "aab", "abcd", "aababab" — but NOT "abab" (rotation
#       "abab"="abab")
#
# LYNDON FACTORIZATION THEOREM (Chen-Fox-Lyndon):
# Every string s has a UNIQUE factorization s = l₁ l₂ ... lₖ where:
#   1. Each lᵢ is a Lyndon word.
#   2. l₁ ≥ l₂ ≥ ... ≥ lₖ (lexicographically non-increasing).
#
# WHY USEFUL?
#   - Finding the lexicographically smallest rotation of a string.
#   - Necklace/bracelet enumeration.
#   - Construction of suffix arrays.
#   - CF problems involving "lex smallest" with cyclic structures.
#
# • DUVAL'S ALGORITHM — O(n) time, O(1) space: Maintains indices i, j (current
#       start), k (current comparison): Compare s[k] with s[j + (k-i) % (j-i+1)]
# Actually, the standard description:
#   i = 0: current start of factorization
#   j = 0: start of current Lyndon candidate
#   k = 1: current position being extended
#   While k < n:
#     If s[k] > s[j + (k-i) % (j-i)]:   ← current candidate can be extended
#       k++
#     Elif s[k] == s[j + (k-i) % (j-i)]:
#       k++
#     Else (s[k] < ...):                  ← candidate is not Lyndon, output factors
#       Output factor of length (k-j) // (k-j) copies (the current run)
#
# CLEANER STANDARD FORM (from cp-algorithms):
# Duval's algo uses 3 pointers. Here is the exact loop:
#
# DRY RUN — Factorize "abacaba":
#   i=0, j=0, k=1: s[1]='b'>s[0]='a' → extend. k=2.
#   k=2: s[2]='a'<s[1]='b'? Compare s[k] vs s[j+(k-i)%(j-i)] = s[0+(2-0)%2]=s[0]='a'.
#         Equal → continue. k=3.
#   ... (following Duval): factorization = ["a","b","a","c","a","b","a"]
# • All single chars since "abacaba" has no repeated Lyndon structure here.
# • Better example: "aababab" → Lyndon word? "abab" → NOT Lyndon ("abab" = its own rotation).
# • Factorization: "ab","ab".
#

# ── lyndon_factorize — inline ──
lf=[]
i=0
s2=s
while i<len(s2):
    j=i
    match_len=i+1
    while match_len<len(s2) and s2[j]<=s2[match_len]:
        if s2[j]<s2[match_len]:
            j=i
        else:
            j+=1
        match_len+=1
    while i<=j:
        lf.append(s2[i:i+match_len-j])
        i+=match_len-j
# result→_lf (list of Lyndon words in Lyndon factorization)
#
        period = k - j
        while i <= j:
            factors.append(s[i: i + period])
            i += period
    # return factors
#
# • lyndon_factorize("abcbcd") → ["abc","bcd"] ✓ (both Lyndon, non-increasing
#       order) lyndon_factorize("banana") → ["b","an","an","a"] ✓
#       lyndon_factorize("aababab") → ["aababab"] ✓ (it IS a Lyndon word)
#       lyndon_factorize("abab") → ["ab","ab"] ✓
#
# APPLICATION — Lex smallest rotation:
# The lex smallest rotation of s starts at the beginning of the LAST Lyndon factor
# in the factorization of s+s (Booth's theorem).
#

# ── lex_smallest_rotation — inline ──
s2=s+s
count_n=len(s)
