# 3H. MEX — MINIMUM EXCLUDANT
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🎯 THEORY
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# MEX (Minimum Excludant) of a set S = the smallest non-negative integer NOT in S.
# Examples:
#   MEX({0,1,2,3}) = 4
#   MEX({1,2,3})   = 0    (0 is missing)
#   MEX({0,2,3})   = 1
#   MEX({})        = 0
#
# WHY IMPORTANT?
# • - Sprague-Grundy theorem: Grundy value of a game position = MEX of reachable positions.
# • - Array problems: MEX of a subarray, or MEX after queries.
# • - "Find the first missing positive" → MEX of the positive integers in array.
#
# 🎯 ONE LINE:
#   MEX (minimum excludant) of a set = smallest non-negative integer not in the set — linear scan
#
# 🔍 SIGNALS:
#   - "minimize the maximum"
