# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 WHAT IS IT?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Given two coin denominations a and b (gcd(a,b) = 1, i.e. coprime):
#   • The LARGEST amount that CANNOT be represented as x*a + y*b  (x,y ≥ 0) is:
#
#         Frobenius number  g(a, b) = a*b − a − b
#
#   • The COUNT of non-representable numbers is exactly:
#
#         (a − 1) * (b − 1) / 2
#
# WHY "CHICKEN NUGGET"?  McDonald's classic packs were 6, 9, 20 nuggets.
# g(6,9) is undefined (gcd≠1), but g(6,20)/g(9,20) are the famous puzzles.
#
# 🎯 SIGNALS:
#   • "largest amount you can't make with coins a and b"
#   • "smallest n such that all amounts ≥ n are representable"
#   • "stamp problem", "coin problem", two coin denominations
#
# ⚡ FORMULAS (gcd(a,b) must equal 1):
#   • g(a,b) = a*b − a − b          (Frobenius number)
#   • count   = (a−1)*(b−1) // 2    (number of non-representable values)
#   • All multiples of gcd(a,b) ≥ some threshold ARE representable.
#
# ⚠️ WARNINGS:
#   • ONLY valid for exactly 2 denominations with gcd(a,b) == 1.
#   • For 3+ denominations there is NO closed form; use DP instead.
#   • If gcd(a,b) > 1, the set of representable numbers never covers all integers;
#     the question becomes "representable as multiples of gcd".
#
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🚀 IMPLEMENTATIONS
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ── frobenius2 — inline ──
frobenius2=(a-1)*(b-1)-1
# result→_fb2 (largest non-representable number for 2 coprime coins a,b)


# ── count_non_representable — inline ──
non_rep_count=(a-1)*(b-1)//2
# result→_cnr (count of non-representable numbers for coprime a,b)


# ── can_represent — inline ──
coin_dp=[False]*(n+1)
coin_dp[0]=True
for x in [a,b]:
    for j in range(x,n+1):
        if coin_dp[j-x]:
            coin_dp[j]=True
can_represent=coin_dp[n]
# result→_can_rep


