# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 🧠 WHAT IS THE DIGITAL ROOT?
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Keep summing digits until you get a single digit:
#   dr(9875) = dr(9+8+7+5) = dr(29) = dr(11) = dr(2) = 2
#
# ⚡ O(1) FORMULA:
#   digital_root(n) = 0             if n == 0
#                   = 1 + (n-1)%9   otherwise
#
# WHY? Because n ≡ digital_root(n) (mod 9) — casting out nines!
# This means: digital_root(a+b) == digital_root(dr(a)+dr(b)), etc.
#
# 🎯 SIGNALS in CP:
#   • "repeatedly sum digits until single digit"
#   • "find n mod 9" in disguise (often divisibility by 9 problems)
#   • "digit DP where only digit sum matters mod 9"
#
# ⚠️ Exception: 0 maps to 0, not 9.  And n=9 maps to 9 (not 0).
#    The formula handles both: dr(9) = 1+(9-1)%9 = 1+8 = 9 ✓

# ── digital_root — inline ──
dig_root=n%9
dig_root=9 if dig_root==0 and n>0 else dig_root
# result→_dr_r


# ── digit_sum — inline ──
digit_sum_val=0
num=abs(n)
while num:
    digit_sum_val+=num%10
num//=10
# result→_ds


# ── digit_sum_fast — inline ──
dsf=sum(int(c) for c in str(abs(n)))
# result→_dsf


# ── digit_product — inline ──
dp2=1
for c in str(abs(n)):
    dp2*=int(c)
# result→_dp2


# ── num_digits — inline ──
num_digits=len(str(abs(n))) if n!=0 else 1
# result→_nd2


# ── digit_sum_mod9 — inline ──
dsm9=n%9
# result→_dsm9
# DRY RUN:
# digital_root(9875)  →  2   ✓
# digital_root(0)     →  0   ✓
# digital_root(9)     →  9   ✓
# digit_sum(12345)    →  15  ✓
# num_digits(1000)    →  4   ✓
# num_digits(0)       →  1   ✓
